<2ND_LINE>AM-Holiday Fires Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0688,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Killed, Four Burned in Holiday Fires</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 10th graf, `Escher said ..., to UPDATE
with Texas fires; picks up 11th graf: `The Florida ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A kitchen stove that was used to heat a house sparked a fire
early Thanksgiving Day in New Jersey that left three boys dead and
two others seriously injured, authorities said.
   In Dunnellon, Fla., a propane heater inside a camper exploded and
burned a family of four, police said.
   And in Lynn, Mass., a woman escorted her six children to the
street before returning to her apartment, locking herself in and
apparently igniting the fire that killed her, fire officials said.
   ``She rounded up her kids, got them all out of the house and then
went back in and set the house on fire,'' said Fire Chief Edward
Higgins of Evelyn Iliopoulus, was released Wednesday from a
psychological counseling center.
   The blaze, which began shortly after 1 p.m., forced the
evacuation of 32 people and two firefighters received minor injuries.
   Firefighters arrived at the East Camden, N.J., residence to find
the rear of the house engulfed in flames, said Fire Inspector Paul
Escher.
   Neighbors rescued a 4-year-old boy from the blaze before
firefighters arrived, authorities said, and city rescue workers
pulled four other young boys from the burning building.
   The 4-year-old was in serious but stable condition at a hospital,
where he was treated for smoke inhalation. An 11-year-old boy pulled
from the fire by rescue workers was being treated for severe burns.
   The other three boys, an 8-year-old and two 9-year-olds, were
pronounced dead from burns and smoke inhalation.
   Escher said the boys were related but not brothers. He said an
adult was in the house and survived the fire.
   In Texas, two 4-year-old boys died in separate fires.
   A heater apparently ignited the mobile home fire in the central
Texas town of Comanche that killed 4-year-old Brian Hatley and
hospitalized his parents and two younger sisters with severe burns,
fire officials said.
   And in the east Texas community of Hemphill, authorities said a
4-year-old boy was killed in a house fire and his brother
hospitalized in the Shrine Burn Center in Galveston. The identities
of the boys were not immediately available.
   The Florida fire left John Roof Sr., 37, with burns over 70
percent of his body, said Shands Hospital spokeswoman Jennifer
Fanzlow.
   Roof and his wife, Julie Roof, 34, were in critical condition.
Their two children were in fair condition, Ms. Fanzlow said.
   ``He was attempting to light it, and it exploded,'' Ms. Fanzlow
said. ``Whether it was a malfunction of the heater or it was his
fault in lighting it, we don't know at this point.''
   The force of the blast blew out the camper's ceiling and one of
the walls. The children, Jamie, 3, and John Jr. 7, were in bunk beds
and escaped with less serious burns.
</TEXT>
