<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Guyana-Sugar     11-24 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Guyana-Sugar,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Sugar Producer Must Import Sugar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guyana, a major sugar producer, will
import sugar from Mexico for domestic consumption and use its
stockpile to meet European commitments, the government said.
   The state-run Guyana Sugar Corp. said Thursday that extremely low
production this year forced it to purchase 4,000 tons of sugar from
Mexico and scale down its annual sugar harvest target from 210,000
to 170,000 tons.
   Guyana, the English-speaking Caribbean's largest sugar producer,
earns most of its foreign exchange from sugar, rice and bauxite. It
has never had to import sugar before.
   Last week the company said it was unable to meet its U.S. quota
of 10,000 tons and asked Jamaica and Belize to take up the slack
under a 1984 agreement.
   The company said a four-week strike in January, a drought lasting
until May and periodic work stoppages are to blame for the low
production.
</TEXT>
