<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Smokers-Carols     11-24 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smokers-Carols,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A British Christmas Carol: `O Little Lungs Of Smoking Men'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There may be a little less peace on earth for
smokers in Britain this Christmas.
   The National Society of Non-Smokers has rewritten five Christmas
carols to give them a seasonal anti-smoking flavor, and it hopes the
rest of the nation will sing along.
   Thus ``O Little Town of Bethlehem'' has become ``O Little Lungs
of Smoking Men,'' and ``We Three Kings'' has been transformed from a
story of the Magi to a tale of three representatives of the tobacco
industry.
   To the tune of ``God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen,'' the society has
written the ominous-sounding lyrics, and ``Away in the Manger'' was
changed to ``Oblivious of Danger.''
   The popular British carol ``The Holly and the Ivy'' became ``The
Cigarette and Cigar.''
   The tobacco industry calls the idea ``cheap, discreditable and
offensely irreligious.''
   ``It's a tatty attempt to involve Christmas in an extremist
pressure group activity,'' said Clive Turner, director of public
affairs for the Tobacco Advisory Council which represents the
industry.
   ``I think a lot of people who've got no interest in tobacco,
non-smokers, even some of the people who don't like us, would regard
this as a pretty cheap and tacky little move,'' Turner said.
   ``I think it's going to offend a lot of people.''
   But Dr. Penny Coyer, spokeswoman for the charity that helps
smokers stub out their fags _ as cigarettes are known in Britain _
calls it ``a light-hearted and topical way'' to talk about the
danger of smoking.
   ``At this time of year those tunes are popular, they're in
everyone's heads, and therefore it's a way of capitalizing on
something ... to put a message across in a light-hearted way,'' she
said.
   ``They're not in any sense intended as a stab at smokers. They're
not intended to be in any sense offensive.''
   To the tune of ``We Three Kings,'' the non-smokers offer the
following tale:
   ``We three reps from industry are
   Bearing fags (cigarettes) we travel afar
   To the afflicted and the addicted
   We bring nicotine and tar.
   Oh! Tar of cancer, tar of death
   Tar that gives you filthy breath
   Keep on smoking, croaking, choking
   It's much worse than drinking meths (spirits).''
   Instead of ``God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen,'' the revisionists came
up with:
   ``God rest you merry smoking folk
   Does nothing you dismay?
   With every single cigarette
   You smoke your lives away;
   Yet still you puff the noxious stuff
   Whatever others say
   Does this bring you comfort and joy,
   Comfort and joy?
   Does this bring you comfort and joy.''
   To the tune of ``O Little Town of Bethlehem,'' the non-smokers
wrote:
   ``O little lungs of smoking men
   How ill we see thee lie:
   All through your owner's fretful sleep
   You wheeze and cough and sigh.
   While in your dark interstices
   Well hidden out of sight
   If something grows, though no one knows
   It may soon come to light.''
   Britain remains a nation of heavy smokers, and cartons of
cigarettes still are considered an appropriate Christmas gift. More
than 14 million people, 33 percent of the populace, are smokers.
   The anti-smoking campaigners have no plans for distributing their
revised carol book. They say they have given them to children who
have then taken them to school, and they hope publicity will prompt
Britons to write in for copies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
