<DOCNO> AP881124-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 2358EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Tut'sTomb     11-24 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tut's Tomb,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tut's Real Curse: Bacteria Eating Wall Paintings In Famous Tomb</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIMI MANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALLEY OF THE KINGS, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rapidly multiplying bacteria
are eating away vivid pictures from the walls of King Tut's tomb,
one of Egypt's most-visited tourist sites.
   Specialists have begun applying an antidote they hope can arrest
the bacteria, but antiquities officials say the original color never
can be restored to the small, pox-like black specks and blotches
marring the walls.
   ``The situation inside the tomb is extremely serious,'' said
Mutaw'ie Balboush, the Egyptian Antiquities Organization's director
for upper Egypt. ``Damage is appearing almost everywhere you look
among the figures.''
   At the start of the winter tourist season in early November,
officials were so worried they considered closing the tomb to let
conservators work unhindered.
   After the antidote was developed last week, however, work to save
the paintings was scheduled before and after tourist hours.
   Tutankhamun, a young pharaoh who died in 1323 B.C., was buried in
a makeshift tomb stuffed with riches in the barren Valley of the
Kings _ the southern wasteland where royalty and nobility were
buried for 500 years.
   During tourist season, his single-chambered tomb draws more than
2,500 visitors a day.
   Its wall paintings, some with colors as bright as the day they
were painted, depict noblemen and officials transporting Tut's mummy
to the tomb. They include a unique scene of the ``Opening of the
Mouth'' rite in which the dead king is given eternal life.
   ``We can't simply remove the infection, because the bacteria have
become part of the paint itself,'' said restoration director Shawky
Nakhla. ``We have to put the bacteria in a situation that won't
endanger the tomb itself.
   ``In the past the bacteria were dormant, but something has
triggered them to life. When we looked at them in Cairo, they were
so active they were duplicating every day.''
   They found four kinds of bacteria and actinomycetes _ an
intermediate step between bacteria and fungi that in humans cause
abscesses under the skin.
   Omar Arini, science officer at the U.S. Embassy in Cairo, said
bacteria have been present in Egyptian tombs since they were sealed
thousands of years ago.
   ``If something changes the environment inside a tomb, such as a
rise in humidity, then bacteria can come to life,'' Arini said.
   ``When this happens, the situation is extremely dangerous not
only for the tomb but for others in the vicinity. The bacteria can
spread.''
   Nakhla said bacteria in Tut's tomb could have been activated by
high humidity, difficult to control with so many visitors. And the
number of tourists is expected to increase dramatically during peak
season over the next two months.
   Though smaller and with lesser-quality paintings than some of the
62 nearby tombs, Tut's burial place mesmerizes visitors.
   It owes part of its allure to the myth of a curse visited on
anybody who violates it. It gained prominence in the 1920s and
1930s, after a number of people from the expedition team that found
the tomb in 1922 died unusual deaths.
   Egyptologists scoff at the idea. Grave robbers violated the tomb
at least twice in antiquity and Egyptologist Howard Carter, the
expedition leader, died naturally in 1939 at age 66.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 2354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Chile-Military Bjt   11-24 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Military, Bjt,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Seen Leading Army Back To Barracks, Away From Politics</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military President Augusto Pinochet, his
15-year-old rule nearing an end, is swiftly moving his army back to
the barracks and away from the political battlefield where he
suffered a major defeat in October.
   Political observers and specialists say recent government and
military appointments by Pinochet are aimed at restoring the army's
professionalism and reaffirming his leadership over the service,
which has served as the backbone of his power since a 1973 coup.
   ``He is trying to preserve the army after the electoral defeat he
led it into,'' said Ricardo Lagos, a socialist and prominent
opposition leader.
   In an Oct. 5 referendum, Chilean voters rejected a proposal by
Gen. Pinochet and other military commanders that he remain in power
until 1997. As a result, he was obliged to call open elections,
planned for late next year, and must hand over power in March 1990.
   ``Pinochet is now a dictator with a deadline,'' Lagos said. He
suggested that the 72-year-old president, who is army commander, is
paving the way for his scheduled departure from power in 16 months.
   In early November, Pinochet ordered the largest overhaul in the
army in 35 years. He sent 16 generals into retirement and moved
other high-ranking officers from political posts in the government
back to purely military duties.
   Among them were several generals and other top officers who
participated actively in his referendum campaign or were outspoken
in their support for his continued rule.
   The changes, while corresponding to the regular year-end
reorganization of the army's high command, were the largest since
1952. Pinochet told reporters during a recent provincial trip that
the step was part of ``the transfer from a military government to a
civilian one.''
   In yet another indication of his plan to lead the final stretch
of his lame-duck government with minimal military participation,
Pinochet reshaped his 16-member Cabinet. Only one active military
officer remained, compared to four in his previous Cabinet.
   In addition, in mid-November he appointed seven civilians and
four retired military men to head 11 of the nation's 13 regional
governments. Only two active-duty officers stayed on, in Santiago
and the extreme southern territory of Magallanes. Previously, active
officers serving as regional government chiefs totaled 12.
   Augusto Varas, a sociologist specializing in military affairs,
disagreed with some opposition politicians who saw the changes as
prompted by pressures on Pinochet from within the army.
   ``This should be seen as a decision of Pinochet himself,'' Varas
said in an interview. ``These things do not happen against the
commander's will. To the contrary.''
   Varas said he thinks Pinochet is ``trying to protect the
institution after the defeat, because it was too involved in the
political campaign.''
   Gabriel Valdes, a centrist opposition leader and a potential
candidate to succeed Pinochet in the 1989 election, called the
changes ``positive, because they show a concern with the army's
professionalism'' instead of politics.
   Varas said, ``This process in the army favors the restoration of
democracy, because it generates a consensus among civilians and the
military that the armed forces must be dedicated to their
professional duties, not to politics.''
   He said the process shows that the military ``have understood the
tremendous damage it makes to them getting involved in politics.''
   ``I think they are leaving power `inoculated' against future
political involvement,'' Varas said.
   He said Pinochet, by assuming the task of restoring the army's
professional standards, is also seeking to reaffirm his leadership
of the institution, which has about 57,000 men and is by far the
most powerful of the military branches.
   But Varas and others stressed that the army's discipline and
loyalty to Pinochet remain strong.
   According to a 1980 constitution promulgated by his government,
Pinochet can remain as army commander for at least four years after
he leaves power in 1990. He has not stated his plans, but Varas said
he thinks he will step down sooner.
   He said he believes the process in the army is also having a
strong impact on the other armed services and encouraging similar
processes.
   The Chilean military are estimated to have a combined force of
100,000 men. In addition, the militarized national police, the
Carabineros, have 29,000 men. The Carabineros have shared the
government duties with the other branches under Pinochet.
</TEXT>
