<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     11-24 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MISSOULA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the saying goes, some people would
rather be right than president. Many Missoula County residents would
rather write than settle for a president.
   Voters wrote in 1,514 names instead of simply checking off the
candidates listed on the Nov. 8 ballot, said Wendy Cromwell, county
elections manager.
   That number led the state and topped the county's previous record
of 1,044 write-ins, set in the June primary, she said.
   Write-ins included professional politicians such as Jesse Jackson
and Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., and sports personalities like Chicago
Bulls star Michael Jordan and the late karate expert Bruce Lee.
   Jackson received 54 votes for president, and Dole chalked up 19.
   An Oliver North-Clint Eastwood ticket for president-vice
president received one vote, and someone paired up network news
anchormen Tom Brokaw of NBC and Dan Rather of CBS for the
presidential ticket.
   Cromwell attributed the number of write-in votes to the ease of
writing on the county's optic scan ballot and to an editorial in the
Missoulian newspaper recommending write-ins in Montana's U.S. Senate
race.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newly found mineral has been named for
him, but don't ask Lehigh University geology professor Charles Sclar
to identify it.
   He's never seen ``sclarite.''
   Sclar was accorded the honor by Peter J. Dunn of the Smithsonian
Institution and Joel Grice of the National Museum of Natural Science
in Ottawa, Canada.
   The two named it after Sclar to recognize his years of digging
for and researching minerals.
   ``I got this letter unsolicited in the mail one day, and there it
was. ... My eyes popped out. I had no idea this was going to
happen,'' Sclar said after learning he would be joining an elite
group of about 15 people a year who have new minerals named after
them.
   Sclar and his students during the last 20 years have extensively
studied the area's zinc ore deposits. Sclarite, he said, is similar
to loseyite, another rare zinc carbonate.
   The new mineral and its name, which was approved by the
Commission on New Minerals and Mineral Names of the International
Mineralogical Association earlier this year, will be duly recorded
among the approximately 2,500 known mineral species in the Glossary
of Mineral Species.
   Sclar said minerals can be named after people or towns, but the
name must have a connection to mineralogy.
   ``You can't name something after your Aunt Tillie,'' he said.
</TEXT>
