<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRouche     11-24 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former LaRouche Ally Testifies On Money-Raising Tactics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former money-raiser for Lyndon H.
LaRouche Jr. says he was ordered to get tough with potential
contributors _ whether old ladies or unemployed workers _ because
``the minute you listen to their excuses, you're dead.''
   Christian Curtis, of Alexandria, Va., said at the political
extremist's conspiracy trial Wednesday that top LaRouche staffers
reserved special scorn for those who complained their loans to the
movement were not repaid.
   They were called ``pigs or swine,'' Curtis said as the trial
finished its third day and recessed until Monday.
   Throughout Wednesday, jurors heard LaRouche and his chief
lieutenants described in most unflattering ways by Curtis and former
LaRouche security aide Charles Tate. Curtis quit the organization in
May 1986, and Tate left two years earlier.
   The prosecution fired another salvo by introducing a May 20,
1985, internal memo by a LaRouche staffer which mocked those lending
money to the movement.
   LaRouche and six associates are accused in U.S. District Court of
conspiring to defraud lenders by having a policy of not repaying
more than $30 million in loans.
   LaRouche alone is charged with conspiring to defraud the Internal
Revenue Service, by failing to declare as income the money LaRouche
organizations spent for his personal benefit. LaRouche has not filed
tax returns since 1979, the indictment said.
   The defendants contend they intended to pay the loans back, but
ran short of funds after the movement had to spend money to defend
itself against government and news media attacks.
   LaRouche has denied that the money spent on his behalf was
income, arguing much of it went for security to protect him from
assassination plots. Tate, who logged many of the alleged threats in
a file labeled ``Mongoose Reports,'' testified such plots were
products of LaRouche's imagination.
   Tate said the three-time presidential candidate insulted
employees, lied to them and ordered them around while intoxicated.
   ``I had a lifetime of hatred in that organization,'' Tate said,
under sometimes fierce cross-examination from LaRouche lawyer Odin
Anderson. The witness denied that he harbored hatred for LaRouche
now.
   When Tate admitted that other LaRouche staffers often ridiculed
him, Anderson said, his voice rising, ``Now you figure it's your
turn to give it back.'' The remark drew a rebuke from U.S. District
Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr.
   The 1985 memo on fund raising was written by LaRouche aide
Franklin Harrison Bell, who said from the witness stand his comments
about lenders were meant to be humorous.
   The memo said there would be four categories to pay back loans to
LaRouche's campaign organizations if lenders refused to convert the
loans to gifts.
   The ``hardship@medical'' category ``is not for every lender who
pulls at your heart strings about needing money to finance the
opening of his new apple stand,'' wrote Bell. ``It is reserved for
real LaRouche supporters in dire straits.''
   The ``legal@security'' category was reserved for those ``who
have active court cases against us or who pose a danger to the
organization.''
   ``The political category is not the dumping ground for those
phone team contacts who make themselves obnoxious by calling during
soap opera commercials,'' the memo said. ``It is the reserve of
supporters who are judged to be people who will continue to back the
LaRouche faction.''
   The final ``schedule'' category was for ``those supporters who
simply are insistent on getting their monies refunded on a regular
basis.''
   Bell, who still works for LaRouche, disputed prosecution
contentions that there was a policy not to repay loans. ``There was
no policy not to repay loans,'' he testified.
   Curtis, the former fund-raiser, said he was told by superiors
that solicitors had been ``too soft'' in the past.
   ``If you're talking to a little old lady who says she's going to
lose her house, get the money,'' Curtis said he was told. ``If
you're talking to an unemployed worker, get the money. These people
are immoral, anyway.''
   ``The minute you listen to their excuses, you're dead,'' he said
he was told.
   LaRouche was indicted in October on 13 counts of mail fraud,
conspiracy to commit mail fraud and conspiracy to defraud the IRS.
Conviction on all counts could carry a maximum prison term of 65
years and fines of $3.25 million.
   His six co-defendants are charged with conspiracy to commit mail
fraud and mail fraud, and would face lesser sentences if convicted.
   The mail fraud charges stem from promissory notes and letters of
credit sent through the mail by the LaRouche organization.
   LaRouche's co-defendants are chief fund-raiser William Wertz;
legal adviser Edward Spannaus; and former fund-raisers Michael
Billington, Dennis Small, Paul Greenberg and Joyce Rubinstein.
</TEXT>
