<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HouseDeadlock 1stLd-Writethru a0767 11-24 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House Deadlock, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0767,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deadlocked Indiana House Moves Toward Holiday Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Bayh reporting agreement
near; picks up 3rd graf pvs: ``From what ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state House of Representatives is a house
divided against itself, but Gov.-elect Evan Bayh said Wednesday it
will either figure out how to share its power or lawmakers will
spend Thanksgiving in session.
   ``Order the turkeys,'' Rep. Robert Bischoff said after House
leaders earlier Wednesday reported no progress in resolving the
deadlock.
   For the first time Indiana's House is split between 50
Republicans and 50 Democrats. Their leaders went back into
negotiations late Wednesday, but both sides at first said they were
deadlocked in dividing power in the chamber.
   Bayh announced shortly before midnight that the two sides were
trying to nail down final details on an agreement. But the proposal,
whose details were not revealed, still had to be endorsed by each
party's caucus and ratified by the entire House.
   ``From what I've seen over the last 30 hours, the people of this
state have every right to view these proceedings with disappointment
and alarm,'' said Bayh, the Democratic secretary of state presiding
over the House organization.
   ``The people of Indiana did not vote for chaos. They didn't vote
for gridlock,'' he said. ``They did not vote for a government that
can't govern itself.''
   The organization session began Tuesday.
   Then, on two roll call votes, one Tuesday and the other
Wednesday, the House split 50-50 along party lines in its attempt to
elect a speaker, traditionally the second most powerful position in
Indiana government.
   The House adjourned early Wednesday morning and appeared headed
toward a Thanksgiving Day session after no agreement was reached.
   By late Wednesday, Republican candidate Paul S. Mannweiler, who
was House speaker the last two years, said he was willing to
withdraw if his Democratic rival, Michael K. Phillips of Boonville,
would do the same.
   The chamber could then turn to an impartial outsider such as
former Indiana University President John Ryan to preside over the
House, Mannweiler said.
   Phillips flatly rejected that offer, saying he intends to be the
next speaker.
   Bayh kept sending the two sides back to the bargaining table.
   ``We're not going to go home for Thanksgiving if the public's
business needs to be done,'' said Bayh.
   The unprecedented split in the House occurred when Democrats, the
chamber's minority party for 12 years, picked up two seats in the
Nov. 8 election in which Bayh became the first Democrat to win the
Indiana governor's office in 24 years.
</TEXT>
