<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Turkey-Ozal     11-24 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turkey-Ozal,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier's Attacker Sentenced to 20 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state security court has sentenced a
32-year-old schoolteacher to 20 years in prison for shooting Premier
Turgut Ozal during a speech at a June party convention.
   The defendant, Kartal Demirag, had pleaded guilty on Oct. 31,
saying he was sorry and asking the forgiveness of Ozal, whom Demirag
hit in the right thumb with a bullet.
   Demirag was convicted on charges of attempting premeditated
murder, carrying an unlicensed weapon and using a false identity. In
Turkey, convictions and sentences are announced the same day.
   Demirag fired at Ozal twice while the premier was delivering a
speech to delegates of the governing Motherland Party. One of the
bullets hit the microphone in front of Ozal and the other hit his
right thumb.
   Twenty other people and the gunman were wounded as bodyguards
returned the fire. Demirag was captured at the scene.
   Six months before the assassination attempt, Demirag had escaped
from prison in the western city of Mugla where he was serving a
10-year term for knifing a man in a coffee house brawl.
   Demirag has maintained throughout his questioning and trial that
he acted alone. He has said he shot Ozal because the premier did not
declare a general amnesty for prisoners.
   The indictment attributed neo-fascist views to Demirag.
   Turkish papers had reported earlier that Demirag was a member of
the Gray Wolves, the militant youth organization of the defunct
National Movement Party. Mehmet Ali Agca, the Turkish gunman
imprisoned in Italy for the 1981 shooting of Pope John Paul II,
allegedly belonged to the same organization.
   Prosecutor Nusret Demiral said that Demirag would start serving
the 20-year-term after finishing the sentencing for the stabbing.
</TEXT>
