<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 0127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SeizedJet     11-24 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seized Jet,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colombian Airline Fined, Loses Jet For Cocaine Stash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs Service agents seized a Colombian cargo
jet and fined the airline $4 million after finding 250 pounds of
cocaine in the aircraft's hold early Wednesday, a spokesman said.
   It was the third time agents at Miami International Airport
discovered smuggled cocaine in packages aboard Lineas Aereas del
Caribe jets in as many months, said Customs spokesman Cliff
Stallings.
   Inspectors with the Customs Contraband Enforcement Team seized
the DC-8 cargo jet following Flight 236 from Bogota and Baranquilla,
Colombia, after opening a wooden crate and finding the cocaine
inside.
   No arrests have been made, Stallings said.
   It was the first time the Customs Service seized one of LAC's
jets, but cocaine seizures have become almost routine with the
airline, Stallings said. Agents recovered 25 pounds of the drug Nov.
6, two pounds Sept. 1 and made 10 seizures overall on LAC jets since
1981, he said.
   LAC has signed the Customs Carrier Initiative Agreement, which
commits the airline to providing significant security and inspection
procedures to reduce or eliminate drug smuggling on its aircraft,
Stallings said.
   Penalties for unmanifested drugs are $500 per ounce for marijuana
and $1,000 per ounce for cocaine.
   Customs will hold the DC-8 as a lien against the fine until the
airline furnishes a letter of credit and agrees to improve its
inspections, he said.
   ``What we want to make sure is that the airline is making a
tangible, honest effort to improve their security,'' Stallings said.
``This amount of cocaine is not a small amount of cocaine.''
</TEXT>
