<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     11-24 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto 14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tony Award-winning playwright David Henry Hwang
hopes to rediscover his musical roots when he teams up with composer
Philip Glass to create ``The Voyage,'' a work commissioned by the
Metropolitan Opera.
   The production is set to be staged in October 1992 to mark the
500th anniversary of Columbus's discovery of America, Metropolitan
Opera officials say.
   ``This is a collaboration we're very excited about,'' Bruce
Crawford, the Met's general manager, said Tuesday.
   ``We have seen a plot outline, which is really more about
discovery than about Columbus, and although we have not yet seen any
of the libretto, I don't expect there will be any significant change
in course,'' Crawford said.
   ``The Voyage'' will be Hwang's first libretto, but he said he has
a strong musical background that predates his theater work.
   ``I'm a pretty decent violinist,'' Hwang said. ``I was trained as
a musician before I was interested in any other art, and I suppose
my introduction to the theater was playing violin in a pit
orchestra.''
   The production, Hwang's second collaboration with Glass, is to be
directed by David Pountney of the English National Opera.
   Hwang's play ``M. Butterfly'' won the Tony for best Broadway play
last season.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thief who broke into Robert DeNiro's
hotel suite as the Oscar-winning actor slept has been arrested,
authorities said.
   The man, who took more than $3,000 worth of clothing and the keys
to DeNiro's rented Mercedes-Benz, was arrested Wednesday. The car,
which also was stolen, was recovered, police said.
   William Dalton, 25, was booked him for investigation of receiving
stolen property, said police Lt. Norman Eriksen.
   The break-in occurred Sunday as DeNiro slept in the Sunset
Boulevard hotel room in West Hollywood, police said.
   DeNiro, a two-time Oscar winner for his roles in ``Raging Bull''
and ``The Godfather: Part II,'' has also starred in ``Taxi Driver,''
``The Deer Hunter'' and ``The Untouchables.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Family Ties'' actress Courteney Cox says she is
tired of playing the prissy intellectual and is hoping to land a
role as a wanton bombshell.
   When the NBC comedy ``Family Ties'' wraps up its final season,
Cox, who plays Michael J. Fox's girlfriend, will hardly be
misty-eyed.
   ``Everyone's ready to move on,'' Cox said in December's Self
magazine. ``They've written just about everything you can write
about a family.''
   Now, Cox wants to play a complex character.
   ``I'm kind of itching to do a very real drama, something like ``
'night, Mother,'' or a romantic lead. I always play the
intellectual, never the sexy or the bad girl.''
   Cox, who was Bruce Springsteen's dance partner in the video for
``Dancin' in the Dark,'' also said she feels she has outgrown her
youthful image.
   ``I don't feel like the sweet little girls I play,'' said the
24-year-old actress.
   ``If anything, I'm a little too old for my age,'' she said. ``I
started working when I was young, I lived on my own, I dated an
older man.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mel Gibson, the swaggering actor who has starred
in such movies as ``Mad Max'' and ``The Year of Living
Dangerously,'' says he is ``tired of beating myself up'' and has
given up drinking alcohol.
   The New York-born, Australian-raised actor said in US magazine's
Dec. 12 issue that he is instead focusing his attention on his wife,
Robyn, and five children.
   Gibson, 37, said he made the change after exhausting himself by
starring in four movies in 1984.
   Anthony Hopkins, who co-starred with him in ``The Bounty,'' said
at the time, ``He's in danger of blowing it unless he takes care of
himself.''
   The magazine recalled his arrest for drunken driving while
shooting ``Mrs. Soffel'' and that he looked miserable on camera when
he was a presenter at the 1984 Academy Awards.
   ``Yeah, I used to drink a lot of beer,'' he said.
   But, he said, ``Your physical side runs down. So you just stop
one day and think, `My God, I'm really beating myself up.' ''
   He finally quit cold turkey because he said he realized it ``just
doesn't do you any good.''
