<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0781,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with closing. Pick up 4th pvs,
`The currency...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen Thursday,
and share prices lost ground on the Tokyo Stock Exchange after
rising for eight consecutive trading days.
   The dollar closed at 121.15 yen, down 0.63 yen from Tuesday's
close of 121.78 yen. Opening at 121.07 yen, the currency moved in a
range of 121.05 yen and 121.28 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 145.86-point
winner Tuesday, lost 90.09 points, or 0.31 percent, to close at
29,340.03.
   The currency and stock markets were closed Wednesday for a
national holiday.
   The dollar opened lower in Tokyo trading following the currency's
overnight decline in New York, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
On Wednesday, the currency closed at 121.25 yen in New York.
   ``At the moment, buying and selling orders are quite balanced and
the dollar's downward force is not so strong, although the dollar
once dived to the 120-yen level,'' he said.
   Currency sources said the Bank of Japan intervened in the market
to save the dollar from further decline. The central bank refused to
comment.
   Meanwhile, Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told reporters
Thursday morning the central banks of major nations, including the
Bank of Japan, will intervene in the currency market when necessary
to support the U.S. unit.
   On the stock market, players were inclined to sell to collect
profits after consecutive gains for the last nine trading days, said
a dealer with a major securities firm in Tokyo.
   ``The index has become quite high, and some participants are
getting a little cautious about the trend,'' he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
