<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Thanksgiving     11-24 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Thanksgiving,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Celebrates Thanksgiving For Its Overworked Laborers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly harvested rice was offered to the gods on
Japan's own Labor Thanksgiving Day, an unusual midweek national
holiday falling on the eve of the day people in the United States
count their blessings.
   Wednesday's holiday was intended to reward the Japanese for their
hard work year-round and also to mark the traditional thanksgiving
for the harvest.
   Millions of people saw a government broadcast of a feature-length
cartoon Wednesday to encourage the Japanese to pay more attention to
their personal lives. In the cartoon, workaholic Mr. Uchide ruins
his health by working 30 years without ever taking sick leave or
being late for work.
   Eventually, his boss learns he has to allow his employees more
time for themselves. Uchide learns to spend more time with his
family.
   The Labor Ministry commissioned the cartoon ``to reach the entire
family in a way that would be easily understood,'' said Yasushi
Fukushima, manager of the ministry's Wage and Welfare Division.
   Labor Thanksgiving Day, traditionally a thanksgiving for the rice
harvest, has since World War II also served as Japan's Labor Day.
   At the imperial palace, 87-year-old Emperor Hirohito's failing
health prevented him conducting the traditional ceremony, called
Niinamesai or Feast for the New Tasting. A palace official said
ritualists performed it, offering newly harvested rice to the gods
with Crown Prince Akihito and other imperial family members in
attendance.
   Japanese work an average 2,150 hours a year, compared with 1,924
hours in the United States and 1,655 hours in West Germany,
according to the Labor Ministry. That's 60 more work days a year
than West Germans.
   Some firms require employees to work as much as 3,000 hours a
year, according to the government-affiliated Leisure Development
Center.
   Japanese rarely take more than a week or two of annual vacation,
fearing it would put too great a burden on their co-workers, said
Dr. J.I. Shibata, a psychologist who cares for people with
work-related neuroses.
   Last year, says Fukushima, only 28.5 percent of Japanese workers
actually had two days off a week, every week. In April, government
employees began taking two days off every other week _ just like 80
percent of private-sector employees.
   In its first revision of the Labor Standards Law in 40 years, the
government in April set an undated goal to shorten the legal work
week to 40 hours from 48.
   It was responding to public pressure to make Japan a more
pleasant place to live. The law also is intended to boost economic
activity through increased leisure spending.
   Earlier this year, Takashi Ishihara, head of the Japan
Association of Corporate Executives, urged the government to act to
``translate cash-rich Japan into a truly affluent society.''
   The General Council of Trade Unions of Japan said 66 percent of
people it polled felt they work too hard. About 40 percent said they
worked overtime voluntarily for no extra pay.
   Japan's virtual full employment reflects shortages of skilled
workers in services, construction and computer industries.
   But younger generations are accustomed to affluence _ summers
spent shopping, windsurfing and snorkeling; vacations abroad. As
they reach adulthood, they are challenging the work ethic that has
made Japan an economic powerhouse, says social psychologist Sumiko
Iwao of Keio University in Tokyo.
   Young people ``are more interested in their own private
satisfaction or gratification,'' Ms. Iwao said in a recent lecture.
   ``I think that the productivity of the Japanese economy will
decline, but I do not think it's such a bad thing,'' Ms. Iwao said.
   ``It's insane for people to say that their hobby is just work.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
