<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iraq-Scandal     11-24 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-Scandal,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father of Slain Bodyguard Seeks Clemency for President's Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of a slain presidential bodyguard
has asked President Saddam Hussein to pardon his own son, whom the
president has accused of killing the guard, state-controlled
newspapers said today.
   In a letter published in all government dailies, Hana Gegeo asked
the Iraqi president to call off a judicial investigation ordered
this week to determine how his son, Kamel Gegeo, died.
   Saddam, in a letter carried by the state media on Monday, ordered
Justice Minister Akram Abdul Qader Al-Douri to investigate the
killing. Al-Douri on Tuesday appointed a three-member committee of
judges to carry out the investigation, the official Iraqi News
Agency said.
   Saddam's letter said Kamel Gegeo, a Christian and trusted
bodyguard, was slain Oct. 18 after shooting his gun in a private
villa near the presidential palace. In a dispute when Gegeo refused
to stop, Odai hit him over the head with a bat, the president's
letter said. Gegeo died later in the hospital.
   Odai, 25, the eldest of the president's five children, tried to
commit suicide after hearing that Gegeo died and was himself
hospitalized before being jailed three days later, Saddam's letter
said.
   The Iraqi leader said Odai tried to commit suicide on two other
occasions while in prison, but his life was again saved by doctors.
   Hana Gegeo called the killing of his son `` an act of fate and
the will of God which could not have been avoided.''
   ``It was an hour of trial,'' Gegeo said in his letter. ``Let God
and history be witnesses that we have passed this trial.''
   The state-run media have carried a series of articles and
editorials asking Saddam to pardon his son.
   Informed sources in Nicosia said the bodyguard, believed to be in
his 20s, was the son of the president's cook and the governess who
raised his three daughters.
   Odai resigned as president of Iraq's Olympic Committee after the
incident but stayed on as head of the governing board of Saddam
University, founded this year.
   The sources in Nicosia, frequent travelers to Baghdad who spoke
on condition of anonymity, said Odai has a reputation as a playboy
who drives a Porsche sports car and frequents the capital's
nightclubs and discotheques.
</TEXT>
