<DOCNO> AP881124-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 0315EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GeneTechnique     11-24 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gene Technique,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Technique Will Help Gene Research, Scientists Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ``ingenious'' research technique published
today should aid research into genetic diseases by helping
scientists produce mice with altered genes, scientists say.
   The procedure helps scientists select genetically altered cells
to transplant into a growing mouse embryo, an initial step in
creating the mice, researchers said.
   While that can be done relatively simply now for a few genes, the
new technique will work with many if not all mouse genes. It thus
expands the usefulness of a recently developed strategy for
targeting genes for replacement or alteration, the researchers said.
   Such a strategy may be used one day to replace defective genes in
people, said researcher Mario Capecchi.
   The selection technique is described in today's issue of the
British journal Nature by Capecchi, biology professor at the
University of Utah and member of the Howard Hughes Medical
Institute, with colleagues Suzanne Mansour and Kirk Thomas.
   The procedure is ``ingenious,'' Brigid Hogan and Karen Lyons of
the Vanderbilt University Medical School in Nashville, Tenn., wrote
in an accompanying editorial
   In interviews, other scientists said alternative techniques also
are under study, and the new procedure may turn out to be preferable
for only some experiments.
   Genes are the inherited chemical ``blueprints'' that govern the
structure and functioning of cells. They lie along threadlike
structures called chromosomes.
   Scientists can alter genes or add new ones by inserting genetic
material into cells. They have recently learned how to aim the
insertions at particular locations on the chromosome.
   But their aim is not perfect, leaving them with the problem of
determining which cells have taken up the insertion in the right
place, and which are carrying it somewhere else. Researchers want to
select only the right cells to slip into a mouse embryo.
   The key to the new procedure lies in the design of the stretch of
genetic material to be inserted. Researchers add two genes to help
in the later selection process.
   One gene makes a cell resist a toxic drug called G418. The other
gene, which makes a cell vulnerable to the drug gancyclovir, is
added in such a way that it will be deleted if the inserted genetic
material ends up in the correct place on the chromosome.
   The selection process begins after researchers insert the genetic
material into thousands of cells. The cells are exposed first to the
drug G418, and then gancyclovir.
   Only cells that have taken up the genetic material somewhere in
their chromosomes will survive exposure to G418. And only cells that
took it up in the right place will live after being exposed to
gancyclovir, because only they will have removed the vulernability
gene.
   In one experiment, only about one in every 2,000 cells that took
up the inserted material had it in the right place. But 19 of 24
cells that survived the selection procedure had it in the right
place, nearly a 2,000-fold improvement in the concentration of
useful cells.
   Alternatives to Capecchi's technique are under study, and the
choice of which to use in research will probably depend on what a
scientist seeks to accomplish, said Alexandra Joyner of the Mount
Sinai Hospital Research Institute in Toronto and Raju Kucherlapati
of the University of Illinois in Chicago.
   Capecchi's method may be best for disabling genes and a different
method may be preferred for making tiny alterations, Joyner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 0336EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-24 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Hits Record Low, Stock Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell to a record low against the Japanese
yen today, and share prices fell after eight straight days of gains.
   The dollar closed at 121.15 yen, down 0.63 yen from Tuesday's
finish at 121.78 yen. The currency opened at 121.07 yen, and ranged
between 121.05 yen and 121.28 yen. The markets were closed Wednesday
in Tokyo for the Labor Thanksgiving national holiday.
   Today's closing rate was the lowest since 1973, when Japan
abandoned the Bretton Woods agreement and began floating the yen.
   That agreement, implemented at the end of World War II, had fixed
the exchange rate at 360 yen to the dollar.
   The dollar opened lower in Tokyo following the currency's
overnight decline in New York, said Mitsuhiko Kinugasa of Daiwa
Bank. On Wednesday, the currency closed at 121.25 yen in New York.
   ``Trading here just followed what had happened in New York. There
was no major economic factor in Tokyo to lower the dollar
otherwise,'' he said.
   Currency market sources said the Bank of Japan has intervened in
the market, trying to save the dollar from further decline. The
central bank routinely refuses comment on its activity.
   Meanwhile, Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told reporters today
that the central banks of major industralized nations, including the
Bank of Japan, will intervene in the currency market when necessary
to support the U.S. unit.
   Daiwa Bank's Kinugasa said: ``The dollar recovered slightly when
investors sold yen as they heard TV news about the emperor.''
   Emperor Hirohito, 87, who has been bedridden for more than two
months, discharged and vomitted a ``small amount'' of blood this
afternoon for the first time in about two weeks, according to the
Imperial Household Agency.
   Kinugasa said most market players were sitting inactive because
there was no trading in the United States due to the Thanksgiving
holiday today.
   Meanwhile, the 225-issue-Nikkei Stock Average lost 90.09 points,
or 0.31 percent, to close at 29,340.03. On Tuesday, the index
reached a record high of 29,430.12.
   Share prices fell back in a wait-and-see mood following the
eight-day gain, said an analyst with Nomura Securities, Japan's
largest brokerage.
   ``Players were inclined to sell to collect profits after the
consecutive gains,'' he said, speaking anonymously. ``The index has
become quite high, and some participants are getting a little
cautious about the trend.''
   In a moderate trading, volume on the first section was estimated
at 900 million shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
