<DOCNO> AP881124-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 0352EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Church-Suicide Bjt   11-24 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Church-Suicide, Bjt,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects ``Clergy Malpractice' In Youth's Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dismissal of a ``clergy malpractice''
suit brought by relatives of a man who committed suicide after
pastoral counseling is a deliverance from legal interference in
spiritual matters, church leaders said.
   The man's father, however, called the state Supreme Court ruling
``a disaster.''
   The court ruled Wednesday that non-professional counselors have
no legal duty to refer a patient to a psychiatrist or take any other
steps to prevent suicide.
   ``Neither the Legislature nor the courts have ever imposed a
legal obligation on persons to take affirmative steps to prevent the
suicide of one who is not under the care of a physician in a
hospital,'' said the opinion by Chief Justice Malcolm Lucas.
   Imposing legal responsibilities on pastoral counselors would also
be ``impractical, and quite possibly unconstitutional,'' because
those duties ``would necessarily be intertwined with the religious
philosophy of the particular denomination,'' Lucas said.
   ``This is not a very good day for us,'' said Walter Nally, whose
24-year-old son, Kenneth, killed himself in April 1979 with a
shotgun blast. ``In fact, it is a disaster.''
   Eight years ago, Nally and his wife, Maria, sued Grace Community
Church of the Valley for $1 million over their son's death in what
experts in church-state relations said was the first ``clergy
malpractice'' suit filed in the United States. The 10,000-member
church in Sun Valley is the largest Protestant church in Los Angeles
County.
   The Nallys' lawsuit said the church's pastors who counseled their
son for several years knew he was suicidal and should have sent him
to a psychiatrist. The parents also said the church's method of
counseling, which allegedly stressed sin and guilt, worsened his
depression and helped cause his death.
   As evidence, the Nallys offered a taped statement of one of their
son's counselors, Richard Thomson, made 18 months after Kenneth's
death, saying that ``suicide is one of the ways that the Lord takes
home a disobedient believer.''
   But the court said that statement was irrelevant because there
was no evidence Thomson ever said anything like that to Nally.
   While referring to Nally's death as a ``profound tragedy,'' Lucas
said the church and its counselors ``had no duty to Nally on which
to base liability for his unfortunate death.''
   Allowing a lawsuit against an unlicensed counselor for failing to
refer a client to a psychiatrist, on the grounds that the client's
suicide was foreseeable, ``may stifle all gratuitous or religious
counseling,'' Lucas said.
   National religious leaders, who had feared the case could lead to
what they believed was undue interference into the pastoral realm by
the courts, were pleased by the ruling.
   ``Anything that has the effect of dismissing this horrible case
is a deliverance,'' said the Rev. Dean M. Kelley, director of the
religious and civil liberty office of the National Council of
Churches.
   Dennis Kasper, an attorney who represented the National
Association of Evangelicals, said: ``It will reduce the fear of
being sued that clergy have been feeling lately and free them to be
more available to people who need their help.''
   Representatives of every Protestant denomination filed court
documents supporting the defendant, said attorney Samuel Ericsson,
executive director of the Christian Legal Society in Washington.
   ``If it (the ruling) had gone the other way, the law would drive
a wedge between those who need help the most and those who stand
most ready to help,'' said Ericsson, who represented the church in
the suit.
   John F. MacArthur Jr., the pastor of Grace Community Church, said
the ruling will allow the church to carry on with its mission of
``prayerful ministry and spiritual counseling.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
