<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HouseDeadlock 1stLd-Writethru a0463 11-24 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-House Deadlock, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0463,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Power-Sharing Pact Avoids Holiday Session In Deadlocked Indiana
House</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with quotes; editing to conform;
picks up 14th grfa pvs, `The chamber ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Indiana House, evenly split for the first
time in history, broke a two-day stalemate today by agreeing to
share power with alternating speakers in what's being called the
``speaker du jour'' plan.
   The agreement, greeted by a standing ovation in the House and
affirmed by party leaders' handshake at 2:10 a.m., also will give
some powers previously held by the speaker to the chamber's
membership.
   The accord was reached under the threat of a Thanksgiving-Day
session and after two days of closed-door negotiations between
Republican leader Paul S. Mannweiler, Democratic leader Michael K.
Phillips and advisers.
   It would let each political party have a speaker who will serve
on alternate days and give each party a co-chairman and equal
membership on each committee of the 100-seat chamber.
   Democratic Gov.-elect Evan Bayh, who in his capacity as secretary
of state told lawmakers he would keep them in session until they
broke the impasse, applauded the agreement.
   ``I think this is a reasonable outcome, given the 50-50 split in
the House,'' said Bayh, who presided over the House's organization
session.
   Mannweiler and Phillips are scheduled to be formally named
co-speakers next Wednesday when the House reconvenes to ratify a
final draft of the agreement. The House will return for regular
business in January.
   ``These are extraordinary times, and they require extraordinary
action,'' said Mannweiler, who served as House speaker the last two
years.
   ``If given the opportunity, I think it will work,'' he said.
``It's a whole new system for us.''
   Phillips said the agreement ``truly returned the power to the
elected members of this body.'' Phillips, who had predicted he would
be the sole speaker, said the accord restores fairness and equity to
a legislative process dominated too long by speakers, traditionally
the state's second most powerful position.
   The organization session began Tuesday.
   Then, on two roll call votes, one Tuesday and the other
Wednesday, the House split along party lines in its attempt to elect
a speaker.
   The House adjourned early Wednesday and appeared headed toward a
Thanksgiving Day session after no agreement was reached.
   ``Order the turkeys,'' Rep. Robert Bischoff said at one point.
   By late Wednesday, Mannweiler said he was willing to withdraw if
Phillips would.
   The chamber could then turn to an impartial outsider such as
former Indiana University President John Ryan to preside over the
House, Mannweiler said.
   Phillips flatly rejected that offer, saying he intended to be the
next speaker.
   The unprecedented split occurred when Democrats, the chamber's
minority party for 12 years, picked up two seats in the Nov. 8
election in which Bayh became the first Democrat to win the Indiana
governor's office in 24 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
