<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CancerInstitute-Broder     11-24 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cancer Institute-Broder,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Researcher Selected To Head Cancer Institute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Samuel Broder, a cancer researcher who
helped show the drug AZT is effective in treating AIDS, has been
chosen as the new director of the National Cancer Institute, it was
reported today.
   Citing unidentified senior health officials, The Washington Post
reported in today's editions that President Reagan has decided to
appoint Broder from among three names submitted as candidates for
the job.
   Broder, 43, now is director of the clinical oncology program at
NCI.
   He would replace Dr. Vincent T. DeVita Jr., who recently left a
three-year tenure as head of NCI to become chief physician at New
York's Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center.
   DeVita was quoted by the Post as saying Broder would make be an
excellent choice to lead the NCI, the nation's largest cancer
research facility. ``He has one of the best minds I have ever run
across,'' DeVita said.
   The other two people considered for the job, according to the
Post, were Dr. John Minna, chief of the NCI-Navy Oncology Branch,
and Dr. Alan Rabson, acting director of NCI.
   The cancer institute, although a part of the National Institutes
of Health, has considerable autonomy because of the emphasis
Congress put on fighting cancer in the 1970s. The NCI chief is the
only one of the various institute heads appointed directly by the
president.
</TEXT>
