<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Soviet     11-24 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Soviet,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Foreign Minister To Go To Soviet For First Visit In 31
Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Qian Qichen will travel to Moscow
Dec. 1 for the first visit by a Chinese foreign minister to the
Soviet Union in 31 years, the government said today.
   The two-day visit for talks with Soviet counterpart Eduard
Shevardnadze is expected to set the stage for the first
Chinese-Soviet summit since Nikita Khrushchev came to Beijing in
1959.
   Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Li Jinhua said at a weekly briefing
that Qian's talks in Moscow will focus on Cambodia, the main
stumbling block to improved political ties between China and the
Soviet Union.
   ``If the talks between the two foreign ministers on the question
of Kampuchea go well, then the Sino-Soviet meeting of top leaders
can be held soon,'' Ms. Li said.
   China says the Soviet Union must prod Vietnam into withdrawing
its troops from Cambodia before relations can be fully normalized.
   Moscow is Vietnam's chief supplier of arms and credit, and China
supports the anti-Vietnam resistance forces in Cambodia.
   Asked whether the Kremlin's decision to suspend the withdrawal of
Soviet troops from Afghanistan could stall plans for a summit, Ms.
Li said only, ``We hope the Soviet Union will continue to make
practical efforts in removing the obstacles between China and the
Soviet Union.''
   China has said there are three obstacles to normalized ties _ the
Soviet occupation of Afghanistan, Soviet military presence along the
Chinese border and Cambodia. The Chinese regard Cambodia as the most
serious.
   Soviet sources said that after Qian's trip, Shevardnadze will
make a return visit to Beijing, probably in January or February.
   The sources said a visit by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
to Beijing for a meeting with senior leader Deng Xiaoping and other
Chinese top officials could come in the first half of 1989.
   China and the Soviet Union split over ideological and strategic
differences in 1960 and fought a short border war in 1969.
   Trade has grown and other contacts have increased since the early
1980s, but China has ignored Soviet appeals to end the long
political freeze.
   Chou En-lai, who served as both premier and foreign minister at
the time, was the last Chinese senior diplomat to visit Moscow, in
1957. Andrei Gromyko was the last Soviet foreign minister in China
when he accompanied Khrushchev in 1959 for Communist China's 10th
anniversary celebrations.
   Ms. Li said the two nations had agreed to exchange foreign
minister visits in 1986, but that the three obstacles had blocked
such visits up to now.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
