<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-24 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed and trading in a narrow range
in Europe today, foreign currency dealers said. Gold prices firmed
slightly.
   Trading was thin due to the American Thanksgiving Day holiday,
and dealers said a sudden large order to sell dollars, or central
bank intervention, could have an exaggerated effect on the market.
   ``Days like this are extremely dangerous because the totally
unexpected can happen,'' said one trader in Rome.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at a record low of 121.15 yen, down 0.63 yen from
Tuesday's finish, despite reported intervention by the Bank of Japan.
   The markets were closed Wednesday in Tokyo for the Labor
Thanksgiving national holiday.
   Later, in London, the dollar was quoted lower at 121.05 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.7170 West German marks, up from 1.7155
   _1.4412 Swiss francs, down from 1.4415
   _5.8665 French francs, down from 5.8685
   _1.9373 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9365
   _1,275.75 Italian lire, down from 1,276.50
   _1.1950 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1982
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8350, slightly cheaper than
late Wednesday's 1.8355.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $419.20 a troy ounce,
down from $419.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $419.85.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $419.80, up from $419.25 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.29 to close at a bid $421.16.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.14 a troy ounce,
up from Wednesday's $6.12.
</TEXT>
