<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 0728EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TurkeyRecall     11-24 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turkey Recall,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Companies Recall 30,000 Turkeys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customers scurried back to grocery stores
throughout the Northeast after two major turkey processors issued a
recall of 30,000 possibly spoiled birds.
   One Boston-area store reported customers were still returning
turkeys Wednesday evening. Other grocers said they were inundated by
people worried about birds that were not subject to the recall.
   Lester M. Crawford, director of the Agriculture Department's Food
Safety and Inspection Service, said no illnesses have been reported.
   Norbest Inc., the nation's fifth largest turkey processor and
distributing company in Salt Lake City, said it voluntarily recalled
20,000 of its ``Family Tradition'' fresh turkeys because of possibly
spoiled necks and giblets packed inside the birds.
   The turkeys were processed for Norbest in Columbia City, Ind.,
and were distributed in Maine, New Hampshire, Vermont,
Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut, Pennsylvania and Indiana,
officials said. No other Norbest products or frozen turkeys were
involved in the recall.
   Meanwhile, Giant Food supermarkets recalled 10,000 Shady Brook
Farms turkeys in the Baltimore and Washington areas for possible
spoilage.
   One truckload, which contained 1,800 turkeys, was shipped
improperly but the supermarket chain recalled 10,000 turkeys because
it could not be certain where the bad birds were sent, officials
said.
   Bob Walsh, vice president of sales and marketing for Rocco
Enterprises Inc., the parent company of the Harrisonburg, Va.,
turkey producer, said only turkeys labeled Shady Brook Farms prime
young turkeys that were sold through Giant Food were recalled. Rocco
is the nation's ninth largest turkey processor.
   ``We do believe it was a very isolated situation,'' Walsh said.
   Checks at other supermarket chains in the Baltimore-Washington
area, New York and New England found no problems, he said.
   But grocers said they were inundated with calls.
   ``We've had phone calls like you would not believe,'' said Paula
Alward, bookkeeper for the IGA Foodliner in East Providence.
   Many customers called with questions about their frozen Norbest
turkeys, which were not inculded in the recall, Alward said.
   The store thawed its frozen turkeys so customers could cook them
in time for Thanksgiving dinner, Alward said.
   Mike Ferry, manager at a Star Market in Providence, said the
store also exchanged several turkeys. ``Yes, we're playing musical
turkeys,'' he said.
   The birds in question have the USDA number of P-2487 on the metal
package closure, the federal number of Gobbler's Retreat Inc., a
Columbia City, Ind., plant that processes the turkeys under a
packaging agreement with Norbest, said Norbest spokesman Mike
Korlogos.
   Gobbler's Retreat President Ralph Heine said he shipped turkeys
to Norbest and bagged his own under the Gobbler's Retreat label.
Officials said they did not know how the cause of the spoilage.
   A U.S. Agriculture Department spokeswoman, Susan Rehe, said the
turkeys were processed and distributed between Nov. 1 and Nov. 18.
Norbest notified the department on Tuesday, she said.
   The Norbest turkeys are packaged in pre-printed plastic bags with
the name ``Family Tradition Fresh Young Turkey'' on the label. Near
the bottom of the label, in smaller print, are the phrases, ``Packed
for Norbest'' and ``Keep Refrigerated.''
   Distributors in Rhode Island, Maine and Masschusetts said they
had recovered most of the suspect birds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
