<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea     11-24 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Roh Expected To Call For Pardon For Chun</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo is expected to
appeal to the nation in the next few days to pardon former president
Chun Doo-hwan and end controversy surrounding the ex-leader,
according to reports today.
   Government sources, who declined to be identified further, said
Roh was planning to make an appeal in the coming week to pave the
way for a pardon for Chun. The sources said Roh hopes to restore
political calm.
   Roh, to smooth the way for public acceptance of a pardon for
Chun, will take unspecified steps to correct wrongs committed under
the previous government, including the forced dismissal of opponents
and the killing of opposition activists, the sources said.
   A shake-up of the government and the governing Democratic Justice
Party is expected in the next few weeks to remove officials
identified with Chun. Roh reportedly wants to purge all Chun
loyalists and sever connections with the former administration.
   The president is expected to try and meet with opposition party
leaders to seek a compromise over Chun. Opposition leaders say Roh
must resolve the dispute to the satisfaction of the nation.
   Seoul newspapers carried extensive reports today that Roh would
grant Chun a pardon or at least lay the groundwork for amnesty by
appealing for public mercy. ``President Roh, recognizing that Chun's
open apology was the best he could do, has decided to give him a
political amnesty,'' The Korea Times quoted an unidentified
presidential aide as saying.
   Chun, a former general who took power with military backing in
1980, went on national television Wednesday to apologize for
corruption and repression under his authoritarian government. He
said he accepted full responsibility for misdeeds under his
government.
   The former president said he was surrendering all his property
and going into rural exile. Chun and his wife, Lee Soon-ja,
immediately left Seoul and moved to a Buddhist monastery on the east
coast.
   Opposition and dissident groups have been calling for a probe to
reveal the full extent of corruption and human rights abuses under
the Chun government.
   Top opposition leaders said Chun's apology was insufficient and
demanded a full accounting of misdeeds under his government.
   Top opposition leader Kim Dae-jung contends the Chun government
misappropriated billions of dollars that have not been accounted for.
   Public reaction to Chun's apology was still not clear today.
Government officials hope many Koreans will accept Chun's apology as
sufficient and allow him to fade into obscurity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
