<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 0819EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ireland-Iran     11-24 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ireland-Iran,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Denies It Illegally Shipped Airplane Parts To Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aer Lingus, the national airline, today
denied an American television report that it illegally shipped U.S.
aircraft parts to Iran.
   ``CBS Evening News'' reported Wednesday night that a federal
grand jury is investigating charges that the Dublin-based airline
has sold millions of dollars of parts for C-130 Hercules transport
planes to Iran since 1981.
   A Justice Department source, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
told The Associated Press that an investigation was under way but
could not comment on its status.
   Oisin O'Siochru, an Aer Lingus senior executive, said the airline
was aware of the investigation.
   But he stressed: ``Let us knock this C-130 thing on the head
straight off. Aer Lingus does not own or operate C-130 aircraft and
has not supplied parts for C-130 aircraft to anybody.''
   CBS said U.S. Customs agents in Miami uncovered evidence
implicating the Irish airline this year when they seized evidence
during an investigation of another aircraft firm.
   The parts helped Iran keep its C-130 fleet, built up during years
of good relations with the United States, in good condition for the
war with Iraq, CBS said.
   Selling U.S.-made parts for the planes, which are used for many
purposes including supplying troops and refueling jet fighters in
flight, was made illegal after Iran seized U.S. hostages at the
Tehran embassy in 1979.
   CBS quoted law enforcement sources as saying Aer Lingus made a
huge profit by ordering parts for its own civilian version of the
C-130 and then illegally shipping them through a subsidiary company
from London to Iran until 1987.
   O'Siochru said that from 1980 to the beginning of 1985, when all
contracts were terminated, Aer Lingus supplied spare parts and small
components for civilian aircraft to Iranian carriers.
   ``We supply spare parts only for aircraft we know something about
and the C-130 is not one of those,'' O'Siochru said,
   ``The aircraft for which we supplied spare parts were
predominately Boeing aircraft, say of the Boeing 747 type. They were
civilian aircraft.''
   Aer Lingus was ``a very minor participant in the supply of
maintenance services to Iran in circumstances where there was all
the appearance of tolerance by the United States of that
situation,'' he said.
   ``Under those circumstances, we really cannot see why this should
be regarded as a very big deal.''
   U.S. regulations were tightened at the end of 1984 and ``when
that was brought to the attention of senior management in Aer
Lingus, a decision was taken to end the contract,'' O'Siochru said.
   If charged with illegally shipping the parts and then convicted,
Aer Lingus faces several million dollars in fines.
   CBS reported that although an indictment is expected, the State
Department has expressed some reservations about bringing charges
against the national airline of a close ally.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0051 </DOCNO>
