<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   11-24 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0479,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede JERUSALEM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Die, Seven Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with more wounded, break-in at
mosque. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``The two...'' Changes byline.
^By MARY SEDOR</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALANDIA, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian woman was
fatally shot in the head today in the occupied Gaza Strip, and an
Arab man died of wounds after apparently being beaten by soldiers,
Palestinian doctors said.
   Troops also shot and wounded seven Palestinians in clashes in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, including a 10-year-old boy struck in the
left leg in Nablus' open-air market, hospital officials said.
   One of the wounded, a 21-year-old man from a village near
Ramallah, was in serious condition with a gunshot wound to the
stomach, the doctors said.
   A military spokeswoman said she was checking the reports.
   Also today, assailants broke into a mosque in the West Bank's
Kalandia refugee camp, smashing windows, destroying religious tapes
and ripping up holy books. A resident said $1,500 was missing.
   A police spokesman said an investigation indicated the motive was
criminal because the money and two tape recorders were stolen.
Palestinian residents blamed Israeli security forces, but conceded
there were no witnesses.
   ``Our suspicion is that local people from the camp broke into the
mosque to take money and valuables,'' said a West Bank police
spokesman, Mordechai Bareket. ``During their search things fell but
(there was no) intention to damage. It's an entirely criminal
matter.''
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, meanwhile, troops opened fire on
stone-throwing youths in the Shati refugee camp, killing 40-year-old
Nawal Abu Ittryah of Gaza City, an Arab reporter said. Circumstances
of her death were unclear.
   Officials at Mukassad Hospital in Jerusalem said Marwan Kneiry,
27, of the West Bank village of Yaabad died Wednesday after being
brought to the hospital Nov. 7 with a concussion and bruises. His
family told doctors Kneiry had been beaten by soldiers.
   The two deaths raised to 317 the number of Palestinians killed in
the 11-month Arab uprising against Israel's 21-year occupation of
the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Eleven Israelis have also died.
   The Hebrew-language Haaretz newspaper said that six Palestinian
prisoners were wounded last week during a riot that broke out in the
desert Ketziot prison, where some 2,500 Arabs are being held.
   Army spokesman Lt. Col. Hanan Rubin, in charge of the Southern
Command, denied anyone was wounded in the prison but did not
specifically deny the riot. The Haaretz report did not describe how
the prisoners were wounded.
   Haaretz also said authorities were using prison loudspeakers to
broadcast Hebrew songs throughout the prison grounds in an attempt
to drown out nationalistic Palestinian songs chanted by prisoners.
   A military spokeswoman in Jerusalem said prison guards had only
blasted one Hebrew song over loudspeakers and discontinued the
practice after three minutes because it had not been approved by
commanders.
   Most of the inmates in the desert prison are Palestinians held
without trial or charges under emergency laws established by the
British when they ruled Palestine in the 1940s. The laws are kept in
use by Israel.
   Also today, the army lifted curfews that confined residents to
their homes Wednesday in two Gaza Strip refugee camps and a Gaza
City neighborhood. But the military maintained a curfew on the West
Bank el-Amari refugee camp for the fourth day in a row.
   The 1.5 million Palestinians in West Bank and Gaza, which Israel
seized in the 1967 Middle East war, have been revolting since Dec. 8
against Israeli military rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
