<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mandela     11-24 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mandela,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha Reportedly Says Mandela Won't Go Back To Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American evangelist Pat Robertson
today quoted the president as saying jailed black leader Nelson
Mandela will not be returned to prison after he leaves a hospital.
   Instead, Mandela may be kept under guard to protect him from
possible assassins, Robertson quoted President P.W. Botha as saying.
   Robertson, a former U.S. presidential candidate, told reporters
he discussed Mandela during a meeting with Botha at government
headquarters.
   Robertson said Botha told him that Mandela ``will not be returned
to prison, but I did not get any indication he would be released.''
   ``I believe President Botha was quite concerned that there's a
real possibility that Mr. Mandela might be assassinated by people
either to the left wing or the right wing of the country, and he
doesn't want that to happen,'' Robertson said.
   ``He (Botha) said he did not feel (Mandela) would return to
prison but would be placed in some type of _ he didn't use the term
`protective custody,' those are my words _ in some other environment
after he finishes his stay in the clinic.''
   Mandela, 70, has been jailed since 1962 and is serving a life
prison sentence for conspiring with other leaders of the African
National Congress to wage an anti-government sabotage campaign.
   He was hospitalized in August for treatment of tuberculosis and
has been recuperating since Aug. 31 in the Constantiaberg Clinic, a
private hospital in a Cape Town suburb.
   Mandela is the most popular leader among South Africa's
disenfranchised blacks, and there has been a prolonged international
campaign seeking his release. In 1985, Mandela rejected a government
offer to set him free if he renounced violence.
   Recently, Botha hinted that Mandela could be released without
meeting this condition, but there has been no definitive government
statement on the matter.
   Robertson is in South Africa for a week, meeting political
leaders and producing shows to be telecast by his Christian
Broadcasting Network.
</TEXT>
