<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hungary 2ndLd-Writethru a0504 11-24 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0504,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western-Oriented Economist Elected Premier Of Hungary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to CORRECT that vote on Nemeth not secret
ballot. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``Kiraly said...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miklos Nemeth, a 40-year-old,
Western-oriented economist, was elected Hungary's new premier today,
succeeding Communist Party leader Karoly Grosz as the head of
government.
   Nemeth, who faces the tough task of implementing unpopular
austerity measures and sweeping reforms to boost the stagnating
economy, faced some opposition in Hungary's increasingly outspoken
Parliament.
   On Wednesday, he won the unanimous approval of the Communist
Party's policy-setting Central Committee. Today's ballot on Nemeth
was delayed by objections from one of Hungary's most outspoken
parliamentary deputies, Zoltan Kiraly, who was expelled from the
Communist Party last spring.
   Kiraly said Parliament should have a much fuller debate on the
choice for premier and hold the discussion only after it hearing a
report from leading reformer Imre Pozsgay on plans for changes in
Hungary's political institutions.
   Pozsgay, a Politburo member and minister of state, on Wednesday
billed his report as the government's ``package plan for democracy.''
   In the end, Kiraly's objections to the agenda were overruled. But
45 of Parliament's 383 deputies voted for his proposals and six
abstained.
   In the vote on Nemeth, 27 deputies voted against the new premier,
and 36 abstained, the state news agency MTI said.
   Reszo Nyers, the father of Hungary's innovative economic reforms
in the 1960s, also won parliamentary approval today in the newly
created post of minister of state for economics. Fifteen deputies
voted against him, and another 15 abstained, MTI said.
   Gyoergy Fejti, a Central Committee secretary, told journalists
Wednesday that the two men combined pragmatism with experience.
   Nemeth is expected to continue the ``stabilization program'' of
economic reform that Grosz began when he became premier in June 1987.
   Grosz announced his intention to resign the government post last
month, complying with his promise not to keep both jobs beyond the
end of the year.
   Grosz made no secret of his preference for Nemeth as his
successor. The front page of the independent weekly Reform showed a
picture of Grosz with the caption, ``My choice would be Nemeth.''
   Nyers also had been high in the running for his new post.
According to Communist party sources, parliamentary deputies and
Central Committee members were surveyed before the final decison was
taken.
   Nemeth, who spent a year at Harvard University on a visitors'
program, sees the introduction of a market-style economy as the only
way of pulling Hungary out of economic stagnation.
   In the November issue of the party monthly Social Review, he
described the present economy as ``deformed'' and called for a mixed
economy that would use capital and labor efficiently.
   ``In vain, we have tried to cram practice into theoretical
schemes,'' he wrote, suggesting that a system of leasing branch
offices of large companies could constitute ``a sort of school for
enterprise.''
   Nemeth, a pragmatic technocrat like Grosz, also sees the need for
a reform of political institutions to coincide with restructuring
the economy.
   In his article, widely seen as an unofficial government program,
he recognized the need to acquire the support of society.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 0916EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Seefried     11-24 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Seefried,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irmgard Seefried, Renowned Austrian Opera Singer, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irmgard Seefried, a renowned Austrian
opera singer, died today, Austrian radio reported. She was 69.
   The report did not say where she died or give the cause of death.
   Ms. Seefried was especially known for singing the role of Susanna
in Mozart's ``The Marriage of Figaro,'' which she performed at the
Vienna opera, Milan's La Scala, Covent Garden in London and New
York's Metropolitan Opera.
   The Austrian soprano also was well known for other roles in
Mozart operas, including Pamina in ``The Magic Flute,'' Zerlina in
``Don Giovanni,'' and Fiordiligi in ``Cosi Fan Tutte.''
   However, her range also included roles in Richard Wagner's ``Die
Meistersinger'' and Puccini's ``Madame Butterfly.''
   Born in 1919 in Bavaria, Ms. Seefried studied at the music
conservatory in Augsburg. In 1943, she joined the Vienna opera,
where she made her debut as Eva in ``Die Meistersinger.'' She stayed
with the opera for the rest of her career.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 0916EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArmsAid     11-24 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Aid,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Acts to Stop Fraud in Foreign Military Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an effort to combat fraud in the foreign
military sales program, the United States plans to require countries
buying arms with U.S. money _ and their American suppliers _ to
agree first to cooperate with federal investigators, The New York
Times reported today.
   Millions of dollars has been stolen from the program by people
who bribed foreign officials, set up dummy corporations, submitted
false invoices and diverted U.S. aid to secret foreign bank accounts
from which it could not be recovered, the Times said.
   Under the new rules, foreign governments buying arms with
American loans would have to agree in advance to make their records
and files available to federal investigators, the Times reported.
   Likewise, American companies that want to sell weapons to a
foreign government receiving American loans would have to give
investigators access to their records.
   Military contractors have objected to the new rules as burdensome
and unnecessary. Lobbyists for arms exporters also expressed concern.
   Joel L. Johnson, vice president of the American League for
Exports and Security Assistance, told the Times, ``These rules could
impose an enormous, unnecessary administrative burden.
   ``They are designed to make life easy for prosecutors. They are
not likely to deter fraud above and beyond the current
regulations,'' he added.
   But the Justice Department said it faced ``almost insurmountable
problems'' in investigating arms fraud cases involving foreign
countries, according to the Times.
   The new rules were disclosed in letters to several major military
contractors from Lt. Gen. Charles W. Brown, director of the Defense
Security Assistance Agency, and his deputy, Glenn A. Rudd, the Times
reported. The agency supervises foreign military sales.
   The Justice Department told the Times that investigating
corruption in arms aid has been especially difficult in the
Philippines, El Salvador and Egypt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
