<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-Iran 1stLd-Writethru   11-24 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0506,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Genscher To Visit Iran, Offers Role In Gaining Hostage Releases</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Iranian media reports,
background on West German hostages. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign minister will visit Iran
next week and has offered to act as an intermediary in gaining the
release of foreign hostages held by Islamic radicals, diplomatic
sources said today.
   Iranian media also reported that Hans-Dietrich Genscher may try
to negotiate the release of foreign hostages, and that a special
effort may be made in the case of kidnapped Anglican Church envoy
Terry Waite.
   The Foreign Ministry said Genscher will leave Sunday for two days
of meetings with Iranian government and industry leaders, but it
disclosed no details of the visit, which is expected to focus on the
Iran-Iraq war and means of improving trade ties between Bonn and
Tehran.
   Diplomatic sources said Genscher has offered to talk with Iranian
officials or groups in an effort to gain freedom for the hostages,
including nine Americans, held by pro-Iranian Islamic radicals in
Beirut.
   ``The minister has offered his services to secure the release of
all hostages,'' one official source told reporters. ``And the
Iranian government has assured us that this corresponds with their
aims.''
   The sources all spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, Cyprus, carried a report from the English-language daily
Tehran Times speculating that Genscher's trip is intended as
mediation in the hostage situation.
   ``Everything points to this being the case, and this accords with
recent moves to have Terry Waite, the Archbishop of Canterbury's
representative taken hostage in Lebanon, released,'' the Tehran
Times was quoted as saying.
   Asked whether Genscher expected a breakthrough in Waite's case,
one source said the case would be raised with Iranian officials, but
that he could not elaborate. Iranian government officials have in
the past contended they have no influence over the Beirut Shiite
groups, but the source said enlistment of the Tehran leadership in
gaining the hostages' release would be pursued.
   Waite and 13 other foreign hostages are held by Lebanese Shiite
groups considered loyal to Iran. There are no Germans known to be
held in Beirut.
   West German officials, including Genscher, have denied media
allegations that they paid for the release of former German hostages
Alfred Schmidt and Rudolf Cordes. The Hamburg-based Bild newspaper
said in September that as much as $22.2 million was paid for Cordes'
freedom.
   Cordes and Schmidt were kidnapped in Beirut in January 1987.
Schmidt was released Sept. 7 of that year and Cordes was freed two
months ago after 20 months in captivity.
   Waite disappeared in January 1987 after leaving his West Beirut
hotel room to negotiate the release of other hostages.
   The longest held hostage is Terry A. Anderson, 41, chief Middle
East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March
16, 1985.
   Genscher will be accompanied by about 30 influential German
businessmen who expect to meet with senior officials of the Iranian
economics and finance ministries as well as industry representatives.
   He will meet with Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati and
other senior government officials, but is not expected to see
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the sources said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
