<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Massacre 1stLd-Writethru a0450 11-24 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Massacre, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill 17 Villagers At Chapel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with 12 wounded, 31 others killed
in govt-rebel clashes. Pickup 4th graf pvs ``One of...''; DELETES
11th graf ``Ayap said...'' to remove outdated material.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CEBU CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed 17 people and wounded
at least 12 when they opened fire on mountain villagers attending
evening prayers in a private chapel, the military said today.
   The regional military commander, Brig. Gen. Jesus Hermosa, said
the communist New People's Army launched the attack because the
villagers refused to pay ``revolutionary taxes.'' But a survivor
said government-backed vigilantes had accused villagers of being
rebel sympathizers.
   A wealthy landowner who survived the attack said she believed she
was the target because of jealousy. And a military officer who spoke
on condition of anonymity said the military was hunting an
unidentified relative of the woman.
   The dead included four children and two elderly women, officials
and survivors said. A hospital spokesman said five of the wounded
were in critical condition.
   The military also reported today that 31 other people were killed
in scattered clashes nationwide between government troops and
communist rebels and between soldiers and Moslem rebels during the
past three days.
   Survivors of the chapel massacre said the gunmen, some of whom
were wearing fatigues, arrived Tuesday evening in the remote
mountain village of Bagtik, about 340 miles southeast of Manila on
Cebu island.
   One of the survivors, Lolita Gitgit, 28, said most villagers were
in the Roman Catholic chapel praying the rosary when they heard dogs
barking. Several men left the service and tried to drive off the
gunmen with stones but ``they were all mowed down,'' she said.
   The gunmen then sprayed the chapel and an adjacent residence of a
wealthy landowner and chapel owner Cresencia Hermosilia, who was
among the wounded, survivors said.
   Roldan Mangubat, a member of the provincial advisory board,
quoted Mrs. Hermosilia as saying she received a threat from an
undisclosed group not to go ahead with a village festival, held the
day before the attack, because it was too extravagant.
   ``There were many of them,'' said Jose Canelio, 27, who was
inside the chapel when the firing began. ``The shooting continued
for a long time, maybe 20 minutes. When the shooting ended and we
got up, they were gone. Many of us were dead. There was much
moaning.''
   Canelio said he and others made their way to nearby villages to
seek help. Officials in Cebu City heard of the attack only today
because Bagtik is about a two-hour walk from the nearest road and
has no telephones.
   The wounded were taken to the nearest town, Asturias, and
transferred early today to a hospital in Cebu City, about 40 miles
from Bagtik.
   Another survivor, Mercedita Bitoon, 23, told reporters that a few
days ago, a member of an undisclosed vigilante group threatened the
villagers and accused them of communist sympathies.
   The area is a stronghold of a militant farmer organization, which
vigilantes claim is a communist front.
   Hundreds of vigilante organizations operate in the Philippines
and have been organized by the military to help fight the 19-year
communist insurgency.
   Amnesty International and other human rights groups have accused
the vigilantes of widespread abuses of civil liberties.
   Two weeks ago, hundreds of area residents fled to Cebu City,
claiming they were being harassed by soldiers and vigilantes. They
have been receiving food and shelter from local civilian officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
