<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-Algeria     11-24 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Algeria,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Algeria, Egypt Resume Diplomatic Ties After 9-Year Break</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Algeria, one of four Arab holdouts against
normalizing relations with Egypt, reversed its policy today and
restored diplomatic ties. Official statements issued simultaneously
in Algiers and Cairo said the resumption takes effect immediately
and ambassadors will be nominated ``in the shortest possible time.''
   Algeria and 16 other Arab states severed ties with Cairo after
the Egyptians signed a peace treaty with Israel on March 26, 1979.
Including Algeria, 14 have restored relations, mostly in the past
year.
   The collective boycott of Egypt was part of Arab League sanctions
against Cairo that included suspension of league membership and a
ban on economic aid.
   Only three Arab states _ Sudan, Oman and Somalia _ maintained
diplomatic relations with Egypt. Jordan unilaterally restored ties
in 1985 and Djibouti, also an Arab League member, followed the next
year.
   An Arab summit conference in Amman, Jordan, last November gave
the green light for league members to resume ties with Egypt
individually.
   Algeria's decision brought to 12 the number of countries that
since have restored relations with Egypt. The others are Saudi
Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Iraq, Bahrain, North
Yemen, South Yemen, Qatar, Tunisia, Morocco and Mauritania.
   Only Syria, Libya and Lebanon remain unfriendly to Egypt.
   Radical Syria and Libya, the most hawkish of the Arabs, object to
the Amman summit decision and continue to oppose proposals by
moderates for Egypt's reinstatement to the Arab League.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
