<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sununu-Jews 1stLd-Writethru a0470 11-24 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sununu-Jews, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0470,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Leaders, Bush-adminstration Chief Of Staff Meet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs Sununu reax published today adfter 4th pvs
bgng ``At Wednesday's''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several Jewish leaders who met New Hampshire Gov.
John Sununu said the meeting left them reassured that the future
White House chief of staff is a strong supporter of Israel.
   ``It was a soothing meeting in terms of the anxieties we had
going in,'' Seymour Reich, president of B'nai B'rith International,
said after Wednesday's luncheon attended by about 30 Jewish leaders.
   Last week, several Jewish groups had expressed concern because
Sununu was the only governor in the nation to refuse to sign a
proclamation condemning a 1975 United Nations resolution that
equated Zionism with racism.
   At Wednesday's meeting, Sununu reiterated that he had refused to
sign the proclamation because he felt it was wrong for a governor to
make pronouncements on foreign policy. He also repeated that he
opposed the U.N. resolution.
   Sununu, in an interview published today in The Union Leader of
Manchester, N.H., said he told the Jewish leaders he had thought his
statements against the U.N. resolution were ``equivalent to''
signing a proclamation, and ``Obviously I have learned it wasn't.''
   Sununu said he ``would like to think'' he now has Jewish leaders'
confidence. He said he told them ``if there are issues we have to
talk about, let's get together and talk about them. I assured them
of accessibility.''
   He said he realizes ``it is a very diverse community,'' but ``you
have to come with a perspective that is somewhat unified. Don't
expect me to handle 40 different inputs and in a Solomon-like way
identify what the consensus ought to be.''
   The host of the luncheon, Jacob Stein, said Sununu also said he
was committed to ``the integrity and security of the state of
Israel.''
   Sununu assured the Jewish leaders that the Bush administration
will follow the lead of previous administrations and assign a
liaison to the Jewish community, Stein said.
   ``The governor's point of view ... was received well,'' said
Stein, a special adviser to President Reagan and leader of the
Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations from
1971 to 1973.
   ``His explanations satisfied the group,'' said Theodore Ellenoff,
president of the American Jewish Committee. ``There was a measurably
higher comfort level achieved at the meeting.''
   Peter Teeley, a spokesman for Sununu, said in Washington on
Wednesday that the meeting went well.
   He added that the subject of Sununu's ethnic background _ he is
of Lebanese descent on his father's side _ was raised but dismissed
as a ``non-issue.''
</TEXT>
