<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pell-Cuba     11-24 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pell-Cuba,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pell To Sound Out Castro on Prospects for Improved Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman
Claiborne Pell flew to Cuba Thursday for talks with President Fidel
Castro on the possibility of a friendlier U.S. relationship with the
island.
   ``There is an old saying that if something works, leave it
alone,'' Pell said through a spokesman before departing. ``The
policy toward Cuba is not working so it may be time to change it.''
   The Rhode Island Democrat said the United States has ``embargoed,
blockaded and invaded Cuba'' but the policies have not produced the
desired result.
   In addition to meeting with Castro, Pell plans during his
four-day stay to confer with church leaders and other private
citizens. He also will visit areas outside Havana.
   U.S. relations with Cuba have been unusually hostile during the
most of the Reagan administration, but the two countries have
demonstrated an ability to work constructively on a narrow range of
issues over the past year.
   In November 1987, Washington and Havana revived an immigration
agreement that Cuba had suspended in May 1985 in protest over the
start of Radio Marti, a Voice of America station aimed at Cuban
listeners.
   In addition, a U.S.-mediated negotiation produced a breakthrough
this week that will lead to the phased withdrawal of Cuban troops
from Angola. The presence of Cuban forces in Angola since 1975 has
been a sore point in Cuban-American relations.
   According to Pell's spokesman, Frank Sieverts, the senator
believes the time for a policy review is ripe because of the change
in administrations in Washington and troop withdrawal agreement.
   Pell visited Cuba as senator-elect in 1960, about two months
after the United States imposed an economic embargo against Cuba and
a month before the Eisenhower administration broke relations with
the island.
   Afterward, no member of Congress visited Cuba until 1974 when
Pell and the late Sen. Jacob Javits, R-N.Y., traveled there in
September of that year.
   Three years later, the United States and Cuba resumed limited
diplomatic contact with the opening of small official missions in
each other's capital.
   The Reagan administration has shown no interest in addressing the
principal problems blocking the way of a more normal relationship.
   In response to Cuban support for Nicaragua's leftist government
and for leftist rebels elsewhere in the hemisphere, the
administration has tightened the economic embargo against Cuba and
forbids most Americans from traveling to Cuba under the Trading with
the Enemy Act.
   Sieverts said it would be premature to say whether Pell, after
his return next Monday, will introduce legislation to ease the
embargo against Cuba. Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., initially had
intended to accompany Pell but decided not to go.
   Pell, who was briefed by administration officials prior to his
departure, is making the trip about two weeks before the Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev will visit the island for the first time
since he assumed power 3{ years ago.
   In early January, Castro will celebrate the 30th anniversary of
the triumph of his revolution.
</TEXT>
