<HEAD>Fog Closes Narita Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy fog blanketed the New Tokyo International
Airport at Narita on Thursday night, forcing 13 airliners to divert
to nearby airports and delaying departures of 30 flights, the
Transport Ministry said.
   A ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
fog reduced visibility at the airport to less than 200 yards and the
runway was closed for 3{ hours.
   Thirteen planes, including six airliners from other countries,
were diverted to Tokyo's Haneda airport and Nagoya in central Japan.
   Some plane departures were delayed nearly two hours, he said.
   About 300 planes take off and land daily at the Narita airport,
40 miles northeast of Tokyo, the official said.
   Fog forces the airport to close briefly several times each year.
</TEXT>
