<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Switzerland-Forests     11-24 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Switzerland-Forests,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swiss Trees Healthier For First Time Since 1983</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The health of Switzerland's forests
improved this year for the first time since 1983 as the overall
share of damaged trees fell from 56 percent to 43 percent, a
government survey said Thursday.
   It expressed concern, however, that trees in alpine regions,
mostly evergreens, showed only slight improvement and more than half
remain damaged.
   In keeping with trends toward improvement in neighboring West
Germany and Austria, the proportion of damaged trees in Switzerland
has receded to 1986 levels, the annual report said.
   Rodolphe Schlaepfer, the top Swiss forestry official, suggested
earlier fears about a catastrophic ``dying of forests'' were
exaggerated.
   Favorable weather and a drop in pollution, particularly that
caused by ozone, were major factors in the improvement over last
year, said the nationwide survey of 8,000 trees.
   Leafy trees showed sharply improved health in most areas, it said.
</TEXT>
