<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Vietnam-USDepot     11-24 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Vietnam-US Depot,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former U.S. Ammo Depot Explodes in Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. ammunition depot from the Vietnam
War exloded at an airport in Ho Chi Minh City but caused only minor
damage, according to a Vietnamese newspaper.
   The depot near Tan Son Nhut airport, which contained 81mm mortar
and 20mm cannon shells, blew up Oct. 24, the Giai Phong newspaper
reported.
   Explosions lasting about an hour caused ``insignificant'' damage
since the depot was surrounded by high earth embankments separating
it from nearby barracks and a residental area, the newspaper said.
   The blast may have been triggered by igniting of the old,
discarded ammunition and gunpowder, but an investigation was
continuing, the newspaper said.
   Tan Son Nhut was a major U.S. airbase during the war, which ended
when communist forces took Saigon, later renamed Ho Chi Minh City,
in 1975. The victors captured military equipment supplied to South
Vietnams by the United States.
</TEXT>
