<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SleepingDefendant     11-24 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sleeping Defendant,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeal Denied For Man Who Says He Slept Through Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted drug dealer who says a rare disorder
caused him to sleep through most of his trial is not willing to put
the case to rest.
   The man's lawyer, William Kunstler, called the latest appelate
ruling ``outrageous'' and said he would appeal the decision that
turned down the request for a mistrial.
   In upholding the conviction of Michael Bisnett on
weapon-possession and cocaine-trafficking charges, the Brooklyn
Appellate Division unanimously agreed Tuesday that the disorder _
obstructive sleep apnea _ is not a ``mental disease or defect.''
   ``Bisnett kept snoring during his trial and the judge asked his
attorney to jab him in the stomach to keep him awake,'' Kunstler
said in Thursday's New York Post. ``When his defense attorney said
this might cause Bisnett a heart attack, the judge said, `Please,
let him sleep.'''
   Bisnett, a former locksmith, is serving a 23 years to life
sentence in Attica state prison for his May 14, 1986 conviction.
   He claimed the disorder left him powerless to assist in his
defense.
   Brooklyn state Supreme Court Justice Herbert Kramer denied
Bisnett's demand for a mistrial because no one indicated before
proceedings began that Bisnett was incapable of standing trial.
</TEXT>
