<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1245EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     11-24 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roh Expresses Sorrow for Disgraced Chun</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo on Thursday
expressed sorrow for his friend and disgraced predecessor Chun
Doo-hwan and appeared to come a step closer to pardoning him.
   The president also hinted he would reorganize his government soon
to break a prolonged political standoff.
   ``Enough has been done,'' Roh told a group of ruling party
officials. ``As a long friend, I felt deep sorrow for the former
president, who had to leave in such a way.
   ``Any legal action against him is not only undesirable but also
against the repeated promise by all opposition leaders objecting to
political reprisals,'' he said.
   Roh said it was time to close the case, because the nation must
have learned a lesson from the crisis.
   Government officials said Roh was expected to appear on national
TV Friday night to appeal to the nation to forgive Chun.
   Roh also indicated he would carry out an extensive government
reorganization, saying: ``No persons, who adhere to the past way of
thinking, would be needed in the new era. A grand save-the-nation
march has begun.''
   The leading national newspaper, Hankook Ilbo, said Roh was
expected to shake up his Cabinet and ruling Democratic Justice Party
extensively next month.
   In his speech Friday, Roh also is expected to promise speedier
democratic reforms and announce specific measures to heal political
wounds left over from the Chun era, officials said.
   The measures would include the reinstatement of thousands of
illegally purged government officials and hefty financial
compensation for the victims of a bloody 1980 civil uprising in the
southern city of Kwangju, they said. By official count, the military
killed some 200 people Kwangju.
   Roh and Chun, both retired generals, have been friends since they
were classmates at Korea Military Academy in the early 1950's. Roh
succeeded Chun when he stepped down at the end of a seven-year term
in February.
   Chun, under attack for corruption and human rights abuses,
apologized to the nation Wednesday and left Seoul to live in
seclusion in the countryside in a traditional Korean form of
repentance for disgraced leaders.
   The ex-president and his wife, Lee Soon-ja, spent his first day
in rural exile at a remote 14th-century Buddhist temple in the
mountainous eastern area.
   In a nationally televised speech before going into rural exile,
Chun admitted his involvement in corruption and the abuse of power
and said he would surrender all his property, worth $24 million.
   Roh and other government officials maintain Chun's apology and
subsequent rural exile were enough to resolve the raging
controversy, but the opposition argues the actions were far from
enough.
   Many opposition and dissident groups said they would continue to
press for Chun to appear before parliamentary committees to testify
on some of his past major political mistakes, including the brutal
military suppression of the Kwangju uprising.
   On Thursday, about 200 radical students and dissidents staged an
outdoor protest at Seoul's Myungdong Cathedral, demanding Chun be
arrested and punished on corruption charges. Police stayed away
during the protest, which lasted several hours.
   Also Thursday, police stopped 12 Buddhist activists who were
trying to go by car to the temple where Chun is staying. The Buddist
monks reportedly told police they could not tolerate the presence of
a disgraced person such as Chun at a sacred temple.
   Dong-a Ilbo, a leading newspaper, said an informal phone survey
of 1,600 South Koreans in six cities indicated at least 50 percent
thought Chun's apology was insufficient, while 44 percent said the
statement was acceptable.
   Of those questioned, some 38 percent called for a major
parliamentary investigation into Chun's government, the paper said.
</TEXT>
