<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1250EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EmployableFelon     11-24 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Employable Felon,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wanted Felon Arrested While Working In Probation Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie Parks didn't even last until his first
lunch hour in his new job as a typist at the Hennepin County
probation office.
   He had just finished orientation and was at his desk Monday when
he was spotted by his own probation officer, Jack Hughes, who a
couple of months earlier had drafted an arrest warrant for Parks.
   Hugh said Parks had failed to make restitution to a bank he had
robbed and had failed to keep in touch.
   Astonished to discover his errant client working a mere 20 feet
from his own desk, Hughes simply asked Parks how he was doing. ``His
response was, `Well I'm doing fine, Jack. How are you?''' Hughes
said.
   ``He was with great calm and I was relatively amazed, and we just
went about our respective duties.''
   While Parks sat typing a letter, Hughes informed David Gair,
manager of the felony probations division, that he'd hired a felon.
Then he asked a deputy sheriff to come over and arrest his client.
   As the deputy was leading Parks out the door in handcuffs, Hughes
told him he would set a court date for a revocation of probation
hearing and see him in court with his attorney. ``His response to me
was, `Is this going to screw up my employment?''' Hughes said.
   When Parks applied for the $7.02 an hour job, he didn't mention
that he had been convicted of robbing a local bank on Dec. 15, 1986.
   One of the conditions of Parks' three-year probation was that he
repay the $300 he stole. After he was released from the workhouse,
where he served four months, Parks had made two payments, totaling
$115. But he hadn't made any payments since January or contacted his
restitution officer, Hughes said.
   Because the office was in urgent need of typists, Park was hired
before a background check could be done _ something that Gair said
won't happen again.
   ``It was embarrassing,'' Gair said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
