<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1253EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Festival     11-24 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Festival,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Time For Renewal: Full Moon, Camels, Dancers And Fertility</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DEL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LIU HEUNG SHING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUSHKAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of people converged
on the sacred lake of Pushkar this week _ as they do every November
when the full moon heralds the coming of winter _ to buy and sell
camels and celebrate the renewal of life.
   The rigors of their desert life are pushed aside for a week as
they watch the dances of gypsy women and listen to ballads sung by
transvestite performers.
   Most of the day is spent feeding, grooming and haggling over
prices of one-hump camels, but the Hindu faithful make their way to
the lake to bathe in the waters which tradition says spouted from
the desert when Lord Brahman dropped a lotus from his hand.
   Married women unwrap their saris to bare their breasts and dip
them in the lake, believing this will cause them to give birth to
more sons. Maimed beggars make their way to the lake seeking alms,
food and spiritual salvation.
   The rituals peaked with the appearance of the full moon
Wednesday, the 11th day of the Hindu month of Kartik and the day
Hindu traditions say Lord Brahma dropped his lotus. Brahma, foremost
in the Hindu trinity of gods, is reverered as the creator of the
universe.
   Pushkar, with a population of about 9,000, holds more than 400
temples where long-tailed gray monkeys with black faces swing from
dome to dome.
   About 300,000 villagers, most from Pushkar's Rajasthan state, and
more than 50,000 camels and cattle have gathered for the annual
festival.
   About 7,000 foreign tourists, mostly from North America and
Western Europe, joined the celebration this year, according to
R.V.S. Bhanwar, general manager of the Rajasthan tourist company.
   A city of colorful striped tents has sprung up to house the more
affluent visitors, who pay about $50 a night for an individual tent
and meals.
   For the foreigners, the biggest attractions are the chances to
ride camels and elephants and to watch the camel races.
   But livestock sales, along with the religious experience, are the
chief draws for Indian participants.
   The drought that had ravaged the desert state of Rajasthan eased
this year when the monsoon arrived after a three-year absence. This
meant the livestock sellers were more interested in getting good
prices, instead of getting rid of beasts they could not afford to
feed.
   A strong camel is fetching as much as $135 to $200 this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1254EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cosmonaut-Conversation     11-24 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cosmonaut-Conversation,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Man Hams It Up With Soviet Cosmonaut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ham radio operator who for years has
escaped the confines of a wheelchair and one-room trailer home by
taking electronic journeys has winged into a Soviet space station on
his call letters.
   Gordon Gunnels, 37, a former firefighter who has lost most of his
sight and muscle coordination to multiple sclerosis, spoke over his
radio Nov. 17 with one of the Soviet cosmonauts in the space station
Mir.
   The cosmonaut was Col. Vladimir Titov, the station's commander,
who goes by the amateur radio operator's call number U1MIR. Titov
and Musa Manarov on July 12 set the record for space endurance after
orbiting since Dec. 21.
   ``His English was better than mine,'' said Gunnels. ``He asked me
where I lived and told me I was sounding very strong. It was so
clear it was like he was hovering right over my trailer.''
   Then they had a ``good chuckle'' over Gunnels' call sign, KB6BUN.
``I told him it fit me perfectly because I'm in a wheelchair and
always sitting on my buns. And that was about it for the
conversation,'' Gunnels said.
   Titov and Manarov started hamming it up with earthbound radio
operators nearly two weeks ago, said Dave Sumner, executive vice
president of the Connecticut-based American Radio Relay League, an
organization of about 155,000 amateur radio enthusiasts.
   The league has gotten reports of radio contact with the space
station from operators around the world in what is the first such
communication with the Soviets. U.S. astronauts on several space
shuttle flights have talked to hams.
   ``We are very excited about it,'' Sumner said.
   Southern California league members say they believe Gunnels is
the first West Coast operator to contact the space station.
   Gunnels, who lives with a nurse attendant, said he took up the
ham radio hobby ``out of desperation'' about seven years ago and now
spends as much as eight hours a day on the radio.
   As exciting as the chat with the cosmonaut was, Gunnels said it
was only the second-most thrilling contact he has made over the
radio.
   The most exciting was when an operator made an emergency request
asking how to perform cardiopulmonary resuscitation on an accident
victim, he said.
   ``I called the paramedics and then told the man how to do CPR.
The guy who was hurt pulled through and later even came to thank me
in person. He wanted to give me $500, but I told him to use it for
his kids' college fund,'' said Gunnels. ``I don't do this sort of
thing for money. Ham radio keeps me alive. It has kept me going.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
