<DOCNO> AP881124-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1257EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     11-24 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>26 Killed in Two Massacres</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers killed 26 civilians in two
separate massacres, slaying a sleeping family of nine and spraying
automatic gunfire into a packed chapel, the military and survivors
said Thursday.
   Reports reaching Manila said 18 communist or Moslem rebels and 13
troops or militiamen were slain in the past three days in clashes
around the country.
   Military officials blamed communist rebels for Tuesday's chapel
massacre on Cebu island that left 17 dead and at least 12 wounded.
But a wealthy landowner who survived the attack said she believed
she was the target because of a dispute with neighbors.
   In the Zamboanga del Sur province on Mindanao island, the
military said machete-wielding attackers massacred a farmer, his
wife and seven children Tuesday as they slept in their home.
   The attackers, armed with machetes and knives, entered the house
of farner Patricio Laranjo in the Mindanao town of Midsalip and
hacked Laranjo, his wife and seven children to death, the military
said.
   Two other children survived the attack by hiding under the bodies
of their slain kin, the military said. The attack was an apparent
robbery because the killers fled with the victims' savings and other
belongings, it said.
   In the chapel massacre, the dead included four children and two
elderly women, officials and survivors said. A hospital spokesman
said three of the wounded were in critical condition.
   Survivors said the gunmen, some wearing fatigues, arrived Tuesday
evening in Bagtik, about 340 miles southeast of Manila.
   The gunmen sprayed gunfire around the chapel and the adjacent
residence of landowner Cresencia Hermosilia, the chapel's owner,
survivors told The Associated Press in telephone interviews from a
hospital in Cebu City.
   The village is in an isolated mountain area, at least a two-hour
hike to the nearest road and about 50 miles from the provincial
capital on rugged roads. Word of the massacre reached authorities
Thursday when the survivors arrived at the hospital.
   Lolita Gitgit, 28, said villagers were praying the rosary in the
chapel when dogs outside began to bark. Several men left the service
and tried to drive away the gunmen with stones but ``they were all
mowed down,'' she said.
   ``There were many of them,'' said farmer Jose Canelio, 27. ``The
shooting continued for a long time, maybe 20 minutes. When the
shooting ended and we got up, they were gone. Many of us were dead.
There was much moaning.''
   Canelio said that when the dogs barked, he rushed out to
investigate and saw two men climbing the balcony of Mrs.
Hermosilia's two-story house. He said he and other villagers tried
to drive the intruders away with stones, ``and the shooting suddenly
began.''
   The regional military commander, Brig. Gen. Jesus Hermosa,
visited the site Thursday and told reporters that communist New
People's Army guerrillas were behind the massacre.
   The rebels attacked because the villagers had refused to pay
``revolutionary taxes,'' Hermosa said. ``They view (the villagers)
as a threat to them. They had been resisting the NPA.''
   But Roldan Mangubat, a member of the provincial advisory board,
quoted Mrs. Hermosilia as saying she did not believe the attackers
were communist rebels. He quoted her as saying they could be
``jealous neighbors'' who accused her of using religion as a ``front
for making money.''
   Villagers and relatives of Mrs. Hermosilia said she built the
chapel and began sponsoring regular devotions to the Virgin Mary
more than 10 years ago in fulfillment of a vow after her daughter
recovered from a serious illness.
   Mangubat said Mrs. Hermosilia had received a death threat from an
unidentified group not to proceed with a religious celebration a day
before the attack. The group claimed the celebration was too
extravagant.
   A military officer who demanded anonymity said investigators did
not believe the attackers were rebels and were looking for an
unidentified nephew of Mrs. Hermosilia. He did not elaborate or say
why other military officials insisted on blaming the rebels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
