<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1259EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Freighter     11-24 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Freighter,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Helicopter Rescues Crew of Freighter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army helicopter on Thursday
rescued 27 crewmen from a Greek freighter that sprang a leak and was
in danger of sinking in rough seas and heavy winds off the coast of
Nova Scotia.
   Rescuers aboard the helicopter used a rope and harness to lift
the men from the deck of the 375-foot Katia to a nearby bulk
carrier, the Sankomoon, according to a spokesman for the Halifax
Search and Rescue Coordination Center.
   ``Nobody injured,'' said the skipper of the Sankomoon in a
ship-to-shore interview. ``Nobody hurt. Nobody sick. Everybody
healthy.''
   S.K. Saggi, the first engineer of the Katia and one of the first
to be rescued, said 20-foot-waves caused his ship to develop a leak.
   ``We had a leak into No. 1 hold and we could not pump it out,''
Saggi said, also in a ship-to-shore interview. ``The ship started
taking list on the portside (left).''
   ``We didn't think we'd make it,'' Saggi said.
   The Katia, a 5,000-ton freighter registered in Liberia, sent out
a distress call shortly after midnight about 225 miles southeast of
Nova Scotia's southern tip. The crew reported it could not cope with
the intake of water.
   The Katia is owned by Seatriumph Marine Corp. of Piraeus, Greece.
In an interview from Piraeus, a spokesman for the company said the
crew was from the Philippines and the officers were East Indian.
   The Katia was on its way to Halifax to refuel before heading to
Quebec with a load of twine.
   The Sankomoon had been headed to Turkey when it stopped to rescue
the freighter's crew. The Canadian Coast Guard ship Alert, the
Cormorant and the research ship Quest also were in the area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
