<HEAD>Jury Awards Student $125,000 For Unauthorized Search</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has awarded $125,000 to a teen-ager who
was strip-searched when school officials suspected her of carrying
marijuana.
   Kim Stevens, now 19, was a 15-year-old senior at Herbert Lehman
High School in the Bronx when the search occurred on Oct. 18, 1984.
   ``The testimony was that she was seen by school personnel in
possession of a small manila envelope of the type that they had
known to contain marijuana,'' said Ellen Zincke, a city attorney.
   ``They told me if I didn't drop my pants, they'd take me down to
the police station and men would search me,'' Stevens said.
   Both sides agreed that no marijuana or other narcotic was found
on Stevens.
   Another attorney with the city corporation counsel's office, Len
Olarsch, said the city would move to have Wednesday's verdict set
aside or reduced before pursuing an appeal.
</TEXT>
