<HEAD>Thai Police Seize 198 Pounds of Heroin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Border patrol police armed with M-16
rifles raided a heroin refinery near the Thai-Burmese border and
seized 198 pounds of the drug after a gunbattle, a senior police
officer said Thursday.
   Police Maj. Gen. Kovit Wattana said 20 guards at the refinery
opened fire as about 40 policemen prepared to attack Wednesday.
After a 15-minute shoot-out, the tribesmen from the minority Haw
hill tribe retreated into the surrounding jungle in northern
Thailand. Wattana did not mention any casualties.
   The attack occurred in Prao district of Chiangmai province, 430
miles north of Bangkok.
   The heroin is worth $1.5 million to $1.9 million on the local
market, he said. Police also found chemicals used in heroin
production.
   An official of the Thai Narcotics Control Board said they
estimate 700-800 tons of opium will come this year from the ``Golden
Triangle,'' a swath of territory in Burma, Thailand and Laos.
   It is one of the world's prime sources of illicit opium, from
which heroin is refined and smuggled to other Asian countries, the
United States and Western Europe.
