<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     11-24 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0936</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just because actress and game show star Vanna
White in a toga grabs almost as much attention as World War II, one
shouldn't gloat.
   NBC Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff decided he sounded
too smug in an earlier statement, so he apologized for things he
said after his network, with the help of Miss White's ``The Goddess
of Love,'' beat ABC and ``War And Remembrance'' in last week's
ratings.
   ``If the impression is that we were jumping in the air over
winning a week in the November ratings sweeps, I regret it,''
Tartikoff said Wednesday.
   Tartikoff was replying to his own statement released after news
that the TV movie ``The Goddess of Love'' earned ratings almost
equal to the 17{-hour megaseries to push NBC ahead of ABC for the
week. Miss White is normally seen on the game show, ``Wheel of
Fortune.''
   The statement said: ``Our calculated plan of youth-oriented
counterprogramming coupled with aggressive and creative promotion,
had the absolute right effect with the viewing audience. I'm happy
NBC has kept its prime-time win streak alive.''
   Tartikoff now says he should have toned the statement down a bit.
   He also praised ABC Entertainment President Brandon Stoddard and
Dan Curtis, who produced and directed ``War and Rememberance.''
   He called the show itself, about Nazi anti-Semitism and the
Holocaust, ``a monumental achievement.''
   ``It is landmark TV,'' Tartikoff said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANDSTONE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents here remember Linda
Petursdottir as friendly and fun-loving, pretty but modest and too
shy to appear in the school play.
   It turns out the 18-year-old Iceland native has won $54,000 for
parading in a bathing suit.
   Petursdottir, who was an American Field Service exchange student
in Sandstone during the 1986-87 school year, was crowned Miss World
in London Nov. 17.
   A blonde with big blue eyes and strong features, Petursdottir,
18, was judged most beautiful in a bathing suit and evening gown
among 84 competitors. She won $54,000 in cash, a new car, a
luxurious wardrobe, world travel and modeling contracts.
   ``I don't expect she'll behave any differently to me,'' said her
friend Dan Bonnin, who plans to visit Petursdottir in Iceland next
month.
   Jeannette Kester, Petursdottir's host mother in Sandstone, got a
call from her Saturday.
   ``All of a sudden I heard this voice: `Hi, Mom!' And it was just
like always,'' Kester said.
   Friends say a year of official appearances could change one thing
about Petursdottir _ her shyness.
   ``It's hard not to be confident when you're Miss World,'' Bonnin
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music performer Roy Clark says it
felt like home when he had pizza this week in Moscow during a
concert tour of the Soviet Union.
   Clark, star of the syndicated TV show ``Hee Haw,'' said the pizza
was served during a reception given by the American Embassy.
   ``It was wonderful to see everyone together and as a special
treat, they served pizza _ a touch of home,'' he said in brief
remarks he wrote for The Tennessean, a Nashville newspaper.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Tommy G. Thompson granted a
Thanksgiving pardon for a turkey that offended Green Bay Packers
Coach Lindy Infante when it waddled onto a football field during a
game with the Indianapolis Colts.
   Infante called the Nov. 13 stunt insulting to his NFL club. There
were predictions the intruder would be drafted for Thanksgiving
dinner.
   But the governor's office said Thompson agreed to save the turkey
from capital punishment.
   Thompson aides said they got a telephone call from CBS Sports,
suggesting some holiday humor. Aides responded by taking Thompson to
a Madison television studio to tape the mock pardon.
   The 60-second segment, they said, was to be used by ``NFL Today''
following the Detroit Lions-Minnesota Vikings televised game
Thursday.
   The turkey, smuggled into the Packers-Colts game at Lambeau
Field, was turned loose between the first and second quarters. The
game was delayed about two minutes while the bird was cornered.
   It was set free in a wildlife refuge near Green Bay. A Green Bay
television station reported it last week at the Brown County
Reforestation Camp.
   Marcy Gause, a station spokeswoman, said public sentiment was on
the side of the turkey.
   ``They're saying they can't kill him now,'' Gause said. ``He's
become so famous.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacques Cousteau, French underwater explorer,
filmmaker and ardent defender of the world's waterways, was elected
Thursday to the prestigious French Academy.
   The 353-year-old Academy, whose 40 members are known as
``Immortals,'' also elected Greek scholar Jacqueline de Romilly,
only the second woman after the late novelist Marguerite Yourcenar,
to don the famed green and gold suit.
   A professor at the College de France and founder of the chair in
Greek civilization which she currently occupies, De Romilly, 75, is
the author of some 15 works on Greek philosophy and literature.
   Cousteau, 78, the author of some 20 books and 90 feature films
and television documentaries, has enabled millions of land-locked
readers and viewers to discover the mysteries of a previously
unknown universe beneath the seas.
   Cousteau won an Emmy last year for his series on American
television, ``The Undersea World of Jacques Cousteau.''
   He is the co-inventor of the aqua-lung and the developer of other
technological innovations such as a one-man jet-propelled submarine
and the first manned undersea colonies.
</TEXT>
