<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SinkingFreighter 3rdLd-Writethru a0526 11-24 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sinking Freighter, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0526,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crewmen Rescued From Sinking Freighter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with crew saved. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-seven crewmen aboard a Greek
freighter were rescued by a helicopter today after their ship began
taking on water while being battered by 20-foot waves off Nova
Scotia.
   Rescuers aboard an army helicopter used a rope and harness to
lift the men from the deck of the 375-foot Katia to a nearby bulk
carrier, the Sankomoon, according to a spokesman for the Halifax
Search and Rescue Coordination Center.
   ``Nobody injured,'' said the skipper of the Sankomoon in a
ship-to-shore interview. ``Nobody hurt. Nobody sick. Everybody
healthy.''
   The Katia, a 5,000-ton freighter registered in Liberia, sent out
a distress call shortly after midnight when it was 225 miles
southeast of Nova Scotia's southern tip. The crew reported it could
not cope with the intake of water.
   The Katia is owned by Seatriumph Marine Corp. of Piraeus, Greece.
In an interview from Piraeus, a spokesman for the company said the
crew was from the Philippines and the officers were East Indian.
   The Katia was on its way to Halifax to refuel before heading to
Quebec with a load of twine.
   The Sankomoon had been headed to Turkey when it stopped to rescue
the freighter's crew.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1320EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HouseDeadlock 1stLd-Writethru a0550 11-24 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House Deadlock, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0550,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Reaches Co-Speaker Agreement And Divides Powers To Break
Deadlock</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf bgng ``Republicans had'' to include makeup of
Senate.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deadlocked lawmakers Thursday averted the
threat of Thanksgiving dinner at the Statehouse by adopting an
unprecedented ``speaker du jour'' plan under which a Democrat and a
Republican will preside on alternating days.
   The 100-member Indiana House, evenly divided between Republicans
and Democrats for the first time in history, also will give some
powers previously held by the House speaker to the chamber's
membership, breaking the speaker's 132-year domination of the
chamber.
   The agreement, sealed by party leaders' handshake at 2:10 a.m.,
broke a two-day stalemate. The announcement was greeted by two
standing ovations by lawmakers who had feared the conflict would
ruin their holiday.
   In addition to alternating speakers, both parties will have a
co-chairman and equal membership on each committee, and there will
be one clerk from each party to run the day-to-day administration of
the chamber.
   Republicans had controlled the chamber for 12 years before
Democrats picked up two seats in the Nov. 8 election to force the
tie. The GOP still controls the Senate, although Democrats picked up
four seats to narrow the margin to 26-24. Evan Bayh also was elected
the state's first Democratic governor in 20 years.
   ``It will work, but it won't work easy,'' said Rep. Patrick J.
Kiely, a Republican and past chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee. ``Everybody will have to work at it. If it gets partisan,
it won't work.''
   The agreement ``could well mean a diminishing of partisan
discussions we've had in the past and we don't need to have,'' said
Rep. Jeffrey K. Espich, also a Republican.
   The accord, dubbed the ``speaker du jour'' or speaker of the day
plan, was reached after two days of closed-door negotiations between
Republican leader Paul S. Mannweiler, Democratic leader Michael K.
Phillips and their key advisers.
   Mannweiler and Phillips are scheduled to be formally named
co-speakers next Wednesday when the House reconvenes to ratify a
final draft of the agreement. The House first met Tuesday to
organize and will return for regular business in January.
   Phillips said the agreement ``truly returned the power to the
elected members of this body.'' He said it restores fairness and
equity to a legislative process dominated too long by powerful
speakers.
   ``These are extraordinary times, and they require extraordinary
action,'' said Mannweiler, an Indianapolis lawyer who served as
House speaker the last two years.
   ``If given the opportunity, I think it will work,'' he said.
``It's a whole new system for us.''
   The plan has several rules changes, including one giving members
the right to call down their bills for votes on the floor.
Previously, only the speaker decided which bills would be voted on,
and his ability to kill a bill by refusing to call it constituted
one of the speaker's most important powers.
   ``The speaker will become more or less like a traffic cop,'' said
Rep. J. Jeff Hays, a Democrat and a longtime member. ``There will
have to be a lot of cooperation.''
   ``We guaranteed that Paul Mannweiler and Mike Phillips cannot be
arrogant or partisan or autocratic,'' said Rep. Stanley Jones, one
of the Democratic negotiators.
   In another rule change, a bill that gets a tie vote in committee
will advance to the floor. Previously, a bill needed a majority vote
to advance.
   Safeguards will allow each party an equal chance to advance
legislation. Each committee co-chairman will have five so-called
``wild cards'' that, when used, will permit a bill to be heard in a
committee even if the other party's co-chairman objects. On the
budget-writing Ways and Means Committee, each co-chairman will have
10 wild cards.
   Kiely previously was the sole chairman of Ways and Means. Now
he'll have to share power.
   ``Before if I didn't want to hear something, I just didn't hear
it,'' Kiely said. ``Now I lose all kinds of pressure in this
situation because it won't be all my decision.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
