<DOCNO> AP881124-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietInspectors 1stLd-Writethru a0552 11-24 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Inspectors, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0552,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Group Wants Holiday Fare for Soviet Inspectors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs next-to-last graf bgng ``The Defense'' to specify where
Soviets will eat dinner.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal policy denying Soviet nuclear
site inspectors the chance to visit local homes for Thanksgiving and
Christmas runs counter to the effort toward improving relations
between the two nations, a peace group says.
   The inspectors here as part of a U.S.-Soviet nuclear treaty can
not accept invitations to private homes under a U.S. Department of
Defense policy.
   Rosemary A. Holt, president of Women Concerned About Nuclear War,
said the rules ``thwart the development of better relations between
our two countries and encourage the old mentality that `we need to
have an enemy.'''
   The group asked the On-Site Inspection Agency to allow Soviet
inspectors living in Utah to spend Thanksgiving at the home of
University of Utah law professor Ed Firmage.
   The Defense Department said the Soviets may visit public places,
including schools and churches, but can not accept invitations to
private homes.
   The decision was for security reasons, a spokesman said.
   ``It's not a good idea, from a security aspect, to provide
security for the Soviets if they're going to individual homes,''
said the spokesman, who spoke on condition that his name not be used.
   ``But we'll allow the Soviets to visit public places, such as
churches, schools or just about any civic organization you can think
of,'' he said. ``We're simply saying `No' to requests that the
Soviets visit individual homes. There's just too many requests to
consider, and it makes guaranteeing their safety too difficult.''
   ``I'm underwhelmed with such reasoning,'' said Firmage. ``How is
it any less difficult to ensure security in a public building that
has many offices and entrances than it is for a private home?''
   The Defense Department spokesman said the Soviet inspectors would
be served a turkey dinner by a linguist at their living quarters in
Salt Lake City.
   Under terms of the Intermediate Nuclear Forces Treaty, Soviet
inspectors may not travel outside a 31-mile radius of the Hercules
Aerospace plant in Magna, a suburb of Salt Lake City, and they must
be escorted at all times by American guards. The same conditions
apply to American inspectors living in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
