<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Demjanjuk     11-24 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Demjanjuk,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Turns Down Defense Motions in Demjanjuk Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Thursday rejected a defense
request to question a Holocaust survivor to determine if he was
intimidated from testifying at John Demjanjuk's Nazi war crimes
trial, a court spokesman said.
   The five-judge panel ruled Richard Glazier could not be
questioned in Switzerland, where he now resides, as part of
Demjanjuk's appeal hearing, spokesman Yossi Hassin said. The hearing
is to begin Dec. 5.
   Demjanjuk, a retired autoworker from suburban Cleveland, is
appealing a conviction and death sentence for Nazi war crimes handed
down in April.
   The Ukrainian-born Demjanjuk, 68, was convicted of being ``Ivan
the Terrible,'' a brutal guard who operated gas chambers that killed
850,000 Jews at the Treblinka death camp in Nazi-occupied Poland.
   Demjanjuk maintains he is an innocent victim of mistaken identity.
   In the defense motion, Israeli defense attorney Yoram Sheftel
contended a taped conversation between Glazier and a defense
representative in 1986 showed Glazier was pressured by Israeli
authorities not to give testimony that would have cleared Demjanjuk.
   The prosecution contends Glazier was not called to testify
because he never saw ``Ivan the Terrible.''
   The judges agreed, however, to the defense submission of an album
of press clippings collected by the three-judge panel that convicted
Demjanjuk. The defense contends the clippings show the judges were
biased against Demjanjuk.
</TEXT>
