<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Thanksgiving,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans Celebrate Quiet Thanksgiving With Relatives, Friends at
Ranch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ President Reagan and his wife Nancy
gathered with relatives and friends Thursday for a quiet
Thanksgiving dinner at their mountaintop California ranch.
   Reagan's daughter, Maureen, who was present for last Monday's
ground-breaking ceremonies for the presidential library in Simi
Valley, Calif., was accompanied by her husband, Dennis Revell.
   Also attending the dinner at the Reagans' 688-acre ranch nesteled
in the Santa Ynez Mountains about 30 miles north of here were Mrs.
Reagan's personal secretary, Jane Erkenbeck; the first lady's press
secretary, Elaine Crispen; and Mrs. Crispen's daughter, Cheryl.
   The weather was overcast and damp, following a day of unusually
heavy rain along the Southern California coastline. As a result, the
Reagans had not been able to do as much horse-back riding as usual,
White House officials said.
   Besides turkey, the Thanksgiving dinner menu included cornbread
dressing, cranberries, string beans with almonds, mashed potatoes,
salad and pumpkin pie with whipped cream.
   The guests also were getting to sample some Monkey bread, a
sweet-bread that is dropped in a pan, like muffins, and is pulled
apart piece by piece.
   Mrs. Crispen said this has been a fixture on the Reagan holiday
menus ever since Mrs. Reagan discovered it while shopping at Sandy's
Bakery in the Brentwood section of Los Angeles.
   The vacation, which ends Sunday with the Reagans' return to
Washington, was their last at Rancho del Cielo before the
president's term expires Jan. 20.
   The Reagans will return to the West Coast on Dec. 23, with plans
to spend five days in Los Angeles around the Christmas holiday and
another five days in Palm Springs where they traditionally spend New
Year's Eve at the home of millionaire publisher and family friend
Walter Annenberg.
   Reagan's son, Ron, and his wife, Doria, are to visit the first
couple at the ranch on Friday, and remain there for the night.
</TEXT>
