<HEAD>Women Soldiers in Clothing Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Woman recruits at an Israeli army base lined up
for morning reveille wearing only brassieres and army trousers to
protest what they said was their commander's harsh treatment, an
army spokesman said Thursday.
   ``It was a prank by new recruits,'' the army spokesman said.
``They appeared at the morning lineup in irregular clothing.''
   The spokesman said the soldiers who took part will be banned from
the ceremonial parade that marks the end of basic training and also
will be given extra chores at the base.
   ``The soldiers will be punished for this,'' the army spokesman
said. ``They have given up their right to appear on the parade field
for the ceremony at the end of basic training.''
   The army said the event occured about two weeks ago at a base in
central Israel. It would not specify the location of the base, the
number of troops involved or the treatment that the soldiers
objected to.
   The soldier who organized the protest has been given a 10-day
suspended sentence, the army said.
   Israeli women serve for two years in the army following high
school. They generally work in support roles and are forbidden from
entering combat zones.
