<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Iran-ContraProbe     11-24 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra Probe,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Miami Connection to Iran-Contra Probe Being Investigated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in Washington reportedly
have renewed an investigation into possible improprieties in the way
prosecutors in Florida conducted a probe into illegal military aid
to the Nicaraguan Contras.
   Former Assistant U.S. Attorney Jeffrey Feldman said Wednesday he
testified last month at closed-door hearings of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, which is looking into the way the Contra
investigation started in Miami was handled.
   ``I did this because it was my ethical responsibility to report
any perceived ethical or legal violation that may have occurred
while the case was under review by the Justice Department and the
supervisors at the U.S. Attorney's Office,'' Feldman said.
   Feldman, the original prosecutor in the case that began in
January 1986, refused to disclose what he told investigators,
according to a story Thursday in the Fort Lauderdale News &
Sun-Sentinel.
   The newspaper said investigators are now focusing on whether the
Reagan administration deliberately stalled the investigation that
began in Miami in January 1986 to cover up Oliver North's activities
and the administration's role.
   An investigation of improprieties involving former U.S. Attorney
General Edwin Meese and former U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner was not
pursued when substantial evidence of irregularities did not turn up.
   U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen in Miami confirmed that this month
a team of investigators from the independent counsel asked to
interview people who were in office when the Contra inquiry was
under way.
   Former Assistant U.S. Attorney David Leiwant said Wednesday that
he was interviewed in Miami last week by two FBI agents and a
government attorney from the independent counsel's office, but had
nothing new to add. He was also interviewed in March 1987.
   The U.S. attorney's office investigation at question resulted in
indictments of 13 men who range in profession from an Alabama
produce dealer to a Texas oilman now living in France.
   The indictments, unsealed in July and August, accused the men of
aiding the Contra rebels militarily even though the United States
had not declared war on Nicaragua.
   A report released in November 1987 by the congressional
committees that investigated the Iran-Contra affair said that the
case had been monitored by top Reagan administration officials since
it began.
   That report, released in November 1987, said that national
security adviser John Poindexter and aide Lt. Col. North ``were able
to obtain information concerning the vulnerability of the
Enterprise'' _ the covert plan to give Iran and the Contras weapons
_ from government officials familiar with the Miami case.
   John Russell, a spokesman for the Justice Department in
Washington, said he had no comment on the revived investigations.
</TEXT>
