<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1419EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MattaSentencing     11-24 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Matta Sentencing,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Judge Gives Matta 3-Year Sentence for Escape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed drug lord whose recapture
touched off riots in Honduras has been sentenced to three years
behind bars for a prison escape 17 years ago.
   The sentencing of Juan Ramon Matta, 43, took place Tuesday at the
federal maximum security prison in Marion, Ill., where he is being
held.
   U.S. District Judge Roger Vinson went to the prison to conduct
the sentencing as a cost-cutting measure instead of having Matta
brought to this Florida Panhandle city. Matta, 43, was convicted
here Sept. 13.
   Whenever Matta leaves prison, about 25 guards accompany him
because he is considered a very high-risk inmate. Taxpayers saved
about $14,500 by avoiding a travel bill for the guards, said U.S.
Marshal Mac McLendon of Pensacola.
   The prison sentencing was agreed to by Matta's lawyer, Martin
Stolar of New York. He said he hoped a delay in the sentencing,
originally scheduled for Oct. 27 in Pensacola, would reduce what he
called hysteria surrounding his client. Vinson was unable to make
the trip at that time because he was in the midst of a trial.
   Matta escaped from the minimum-security federal prison camp at
Eglin Air Force Base about 40 miles east of Pensacola in 1971 while
serving a three-year term for illegally entering the United States.
   Several people were killed and the U.S. consulate was set afire
in the Honduran capital of Tegucigalpa during rioting that followed
his arrest there April 5.
   Demonstrators claimed Matta's extradition to the United States by
way of the Dominican Republic violated the Honduran constitution. He
was taken into custody by U.S. marshals when his plane arrived in
New York.
   Matta is under indictment in three narcotics cases in California
and one in Arizona. He also had been wanted for questioning in the
1985 slaying of a U.S. drug enforcement agent in Mexico but has not
been charged in that case.
   Matta had been living openly in Tegucigalpa since 1986 when he
escaped from a Colombian prison where he had been held on charges
involving the Medellin drug cartel.
   Honduran police used helicopters to raid his home and then sent
him out of the country accompanied by U.S. officials.
   Matta is appealing the escape conviction on grounds his arrest
was illegal. His lawyer had made the same argument to Vinson prior
to trial but the judge rejected it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
