<DOCNO> AP881124-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1420EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Herzfelde     11-24 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Herzfelde,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Berlin Writer-Publisher Dead at 93</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wieland Herzfelde, a leading publisher and writer
who was persecuted by the Nazis for his communist views, died in
East Berlin on Wednesday at the age of 93.
   The Swiss-born writer and intellectual spent 10 years in New York
during the Nazi dictatorship. In 1944 he founded the Aurora Verlag
publishing house in New York, working with noted German writers such
as Bertolt Brecht, Heinrich Mann and Alfred Doeblin.
   Born in Weggis, Switzerland, on April 11, 1896, Herzfelde grew up
in Austria and Germany. In 1917 he founded the Berlin publishing
house Malik Verlag, which printed Dadaist and anti-war literature
and the works of young Soviet writers.
   The publishing house was banned by the Nazis in 1933, and
Herzfelde, a member of the German Communist Party since 1918, fled
the country.
   He first emigrated to Prague, where he published a magazine
together with other German writers and intellectuals in exile.
   In 1939, as Adolf Hitler's Third Reich spread throughout Europe,
Herzfelde fled to New York.
   He emigrated to communist-ruled East Germany in 1949, and
remained there until his death. Herzfelde continued his work as a
writer and publisher, and was also a literature professor at the
University of Leipzig.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
