<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1422EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Tanks     11-24 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Tanks,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Postpones Decision on U.S. Tanks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Cabinet failed Thursday to resolve its
dilemma over whether to re-equip the army with British or U.S.
battle tanks, but officials said a decision likely would be made
before Christmas.
   At stake is an order worth at least $2 billion for a new
generation of 500 tanks to replace Britain's aging homemade
Chieftains.
   The choice is between the M1 Abrams, made by General Dynamics
Corp. in Michigan, and Challenger Mark 2, built by Vickers PLC of
Britain.
   Vickers, the sole British tankmaker, says that if Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's government buys American it will kill Britain's
tank manufacturing capacity and lose this country billions of
dollars of Middle East orders.
   ``They had a good look at it,'' a government spokesman said
Thursday after Mrs. Thatcher and her ministers debated the issue at
a Cabinet meeting.
   ``They identified further points that need to be looked at, but
its a complex issue. We hope to have a decision within weeks,''
added the spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Defense Ministry has refused to comment on reports that
British military chiefs have doubts about the Challenger's fire
control system and prefer the Abrams tank for its sophistication and
off-the-shelf availability.
   Vickers chairman Sir David Plastow says the company has solved
the fire control problems and can produce a competitive tank at its
plant in Leeds, central England.
   He added that if Vickers loses the order, Britain will cease to
be an international tank manufacturer, leaving the lucrative Middle
East market to the Soviets and Americans.
   In its last major choice between British or American weapons, the
Thatcher government in 1986 opted for the U.S. Boeing airborne early
warning radar systems and scrapped a Nimrod version by the British
General Electric Co. on grounds it did not work properly.
   Legislator Derek Fatchett, who represents a Leeds constituency,
said the Cabinet delay Thursday in the tank decision ``indicates a
growing interest in the American alternative.''
   He said Defense Secretary George Younger had made no
recommendation to the Cabinet, adding, ``That is an abdication of
his responsibilities to the country's defense industry.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
