<DOCNO> AP881124-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1426EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SecretVote     11-24 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Secret Vote,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Limitations on Secret Vote _ Secretly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a secret ballot, senators decided Thursday to join
the lower house of Parliament in all but abolishing the secret
ballot.
   The action, aimed at adding stability to Italian government,
completed a victory for Premier Ciriaco De Mita who had indicated he
would resign if the measure did not pass in the Chamber of Deputies.
   Open voting in Parliament is expected to strengthen the executive
system and create a more stable political climate in the country
that has had 48 postwar governments.
   With the secret vote, governments often were confronted by
``snipers'' who used the secret ballot to vote against their party
line, particularly to ensure passage of pet spending products.
   Now, parliamentarians who vote against their party directives
will do so at their own risk.
   Senators voted 165-132 with two abstentions Thursday to abolish
the secret vote except on measures involving personal rights, family
rights and in votes on procedures or personnel, such as the election
of a Senate president. The government needed 150 votes in the Senate
to abolish the vote.
   The Senate rejected amendments that would have also retained the
secret vote on measures involving constitutional law or on proposals
to amend parlimentary procedures.
   Under the Chamber's rules, secret votes are still allowed on
measures dealing with special government bodies such as the
anti-Mafia commission, specific persons, issues of conscience such
as abortion, personal liberties and substantive changes in the
constitution.
   Italy was one of the few Western democracies where most
parliamentary votes were secret and citizens had no certainty about
how their representatives voted on various issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
