<DOCNO> AP881124-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1427EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BloodCrisis     11-24 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blood Crisis,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shortage Forces Hemophiliacs To Use Potentially Unsafe Blood
Product</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of hemophiliacs nationwide must use
a blood-clotting product that could contain the AIDS virus because
of a severe shortage of the product normally used, doctors and
officials said.
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has impounded millions of
units of the usual concentrate, called Factor 8, after declaring it
was improperly screened for contamination.
   As a result, many patients needing large amounts of the clotting
substance must be given cryo-precipitate, a relatively crude
preparation made from fresh plasma that carries a higher risk of
contamination than the impounded concentrate, doctors said.
   ``It's really very ironic,'' said Dr. Carol Kasper, director of
the Hemophilia Center at Orthopedic Hospital in Los Angeles, one of
the largest hemophilia clinics in the world.
   ``Our supply of concentrate is one-third of what we usually
have,'' Kasper said Wednesday. ``We cannot do elective surgery. We
have to restrict the amount patients take home.''
   Hemophiliacs depend on injections of concentrate because their
bodies lack the ability to produce clotting substances, putting them
at constant risk of severe internal bleeding from everyday
activities.
   The American Red Cross, which usually provides 20 percent of the
nation's supply of concentrate, was ordered to keep its concentrate
on the shelf because of a slight chance the product harbors the
hepatitis or AIDS viruses.
   An FDA audit found that in a few instances the blood banks had
not followed regulations for screening blood, from which concentrate
is made.
   Despite the order, federal and Red Cross officials agree that it
is highly unlikely that the concentrate is tainted. The concentrate
has already been treated to destroy any viruses that might have
slipped through the screening.
   ``My feeling is the products they are preparing are likely to be
perfectly safe,'' said Dr. Joel Solomon, director of blood products
for the FDA.
   Solomon said the FDA cannot bend its regulations and release the
concentrate, however, because of a recent U.S. Supreme Court ruling
that held that the agency can be sued for failing to follow its own
regulations.
   ``As a result the FDA and every other federal agency has been put
on notice to be extra careful _ even when we think we have good
cause to release something,'' Solomon said.
   The supply will remain quarantined for several weeks while the
Red Cross attempts to prove that the concentrate is virus-free or
applies for a permit to use it as an experimental substance, he said.
   ``We've gone through this for weeks on end _ the problem is a
legal one and we've been searching for an out,'' Solomon said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
