<DOCNO> AP881124-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1428EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Rights     11-24 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Rights,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Denies Mexico Has Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico has no political prisoners or secret
jails, the government declared Thursday, two days after human rights
activists disrupted the Senate to protest the disappearances of 369
people.
   ``No one is persecuted or jailed in Mexico for their ideas,'' the
Interior Ministry said in a statement. ``There are no political
disappearances or clandestine jails or people who vanish because of
official acts on the margin of the law.''
   Twenty-one mothers of missing people, representing the human
rights movement Eureka, were ejected from the Senate gallery Tuesday
after shouting demands for an investigation of 369 people who
allegedly disappeared for political reasons.
   ``What we want is for our sons to be freed, or at least for
someone to tell us where they are and why they were detained,'' said
the leader of the group, Rosario Ibarra de Piedra. She is a former
presidential candidate whose son, a leftist medical student,
disappeared in 1975.
   The Interior Ministry said Thursday the federal attorney
general's office found nothing amiss when it investigated ``the
situation of the people detained or disappeared since Dec. 1,
1982,'' the beginning of President Miguel de la Madrid's
administration. He leaves office Tuesday.
   It said 37 of the 41 detainees cited by Mrs. Ibarra de Piedra are
either free or held for crimes. The statement said of the other
four: ``Investigations have determined that none of these people
took part in political activities.''
   ``No public security force took part in any act related to these
four people and the supposed disappearances cannot be attributed to
any decision by the Mexican state to violate the rule of law which
it has always respected,'' the ministry declared.
   The human rights organization Amnesty International also has
reported political prisoners and killings in Mexico. The government
said the latest Amnesty allegations, issued last month, ``deform
reality.''
   Amnesty cited reports of ``arbitrary detention and
assassination'' of peasants and Indians in connection with land
disputes. ``Many assassinations were attributed to gunmen linked to
landowners who appeared to have the tacit consent of the
authorities,'' it said.
   According to Amnesty International, at least 23 political
prisoners were held in Mexico in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
