<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Navy     11-24 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Navy,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Introduces High-Speed Patrol Boat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This story was submitted to the Israeli military censor, who
ordered significant deletions.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HAIFA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-speed patrol boat capable of carrying
130mm rockets and torpedoes was introduced into the Israeli navy
Thursday to repel Palestinian guerrilla raids.
   The Super Dvora, an Israeli-made boat, is ``the fastest military
patrol boat in the world,'' with a top speed of 46 mph, said Navy
officials at a ceremony at the Haifa naval base.
   It will replace the navy's current Dabur class patrol boat and is
twice as fast, the officials said.
   Patrols foiled at least four sea infiltration attempts since
December, the military says. All occurred off the coast of southern
Lebanon, which Israel patrols to block Palestinians from reaching
the Israeli coast.
   The new 71-foot boat weighs 48 tons and has a range of 700 miles.
It was built by Ramta, a subsidiary of the government-owned Israel
Aircraft Industries, and its export price is about $2.5 million, a
company official said.
</TEXT>
