<HEAD>Court Paroles Ex General Involved in 1981 Revolt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military court paroled an ailing
ex-general who participated in a 1981 coup attempt, a Defense
Ministry spokesman said Thursday.
   Former army Gen. Luis Torres Rojas left Gomez Ulla military
hospital Thursday after the court approved his release due to ill
health, the spokesman said.
   Torres Rojas, 70, who served half of his 12-year sentence for
military rebellion, was among the last four revolt leaders still in
prison, the spokesman said.
   The Defense Ministry is studying whether to recommend a pardon
for another ailing leader of the revolt, former army Lt. Gen.
Alfonso Armada, serving a 30-year sentence, he said.
   In the revolt Feb. 23, 1981, a Civil Guard officer and 200 guard
members supported by some army officers held Parliament hostage
overnight. King Juan Carlos ordered them to surrender.
