<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0553 11-24 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0553,0726</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Begin Prisoner Exchange</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Red Cross statement. Pick
up
4th pvs, ``A dispatch ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq began a 10-day exchange of
sick and wounded prisoners of war Thursday, but a jet chartered by
the International Red Cross shuttled fewer men than than promised
between the enemy capitals.
   A Red Cross statement issued in Geneva said only 19 Iranians and
41 Iraqis were flown home Thursday despite an accord with both sides
providing for the repatriation of 41 Iranians and 115 Iraqis every
day.
   The statement said the reduced numbers resulted from
``differences of interpretation between the two parties with regard
to criteria and procedures.''
   Iraq, which received the first prisoners, accused Iran of
reneging on the agreement, according to which 1,570 men are to be
repatriated. In retaliation, Baghdad reduced the number of Iranians
sent home.
   A dispatch from Iran's official news agency, monitored in Cyprus,
said fewer Iraqis were returned because 15 of the 115 asked for
political asylum, 21 already had been granted asylum and 27 no
longer were eligible for repatriation because Red Cross doctors
found them recovered from their illnesses.
   It said each departing prisoner was given gifts of Persian
craftwork and a copy of the Koran, the Islamic holy book.
   Iran and Iraq began a cease-fire Aug. 20 after nearly eight years
of war, and this is the first prisoner exchange since the truce. It
is being made under an agreement they signed earlier this month with
the International Committee of the Red Cross.
   Under Red Cross auspices, 765 ill or wounded Iraqis and 613
Iranians have been repatriated since 1981. The Red Cross says it has
registered 50,182 Iraqi POWs and 19,284 Iranians, but the total held
by both countries is estimated at about 100,000.
   Pilot Riegert Poloux said the trip between the capitals, which
are only about 500 miles apart, took 2{ hours because he had to fly
via Turkey.
   He said the governments originally agreed to let the plane use a
direct route, but final arrangements were not made in time. The next
shuttle Saturday is expected to be direct.
   The 730-mile border was the battleground in the war, which began
in September 1980. U.N.-sponsored peace negotiations since the
cease-fire have made little progress and the Red Cross fashioned the
POW exchange agreement in separate talks with Iran and Iraq.
   Iraqi prisoners arriving at Saddam International Airport had
shaved heads, long beards and clean military-style uniforms. Most
wept when they stepped from the DC-9 and many shouted nationalistic
slogans.
   One who knelt to pray on the tarmac at the airport, which is
named for President Saddam Hussein, said afterward: ``It is great to
be home again. I feel reborn.''
   Some shouted ``Long live Iraq! Long live Saddam Hussein!'' Others
bent to kiss the ground while comrades prayed loudly, thanking God
for the return home.
   Red Cross officials helped many out of the plane and turned them
over Iraqi medical personnel. Many were in wheelchairs, some walked
with sticks and all appeared frail.
   Officials would not let reporters interview the repatriated
prisoners.
   When the returning Iraqis were out of the plane, 19 Iranian
prisoners dressed in yellow track suits boarded it. Few were young
and none used wheelchairs or crutches.
   A senior Iraqi officer kissed them goodbye at the plane. Each was
offered a copy of the Koran, but some refused it.
   ``It is not Islamic. I will not take it,'' one said.
   Iraq accused Iran of withholding some Iraqi prisoners for
``political reasons.''
   Akram Witri, head of the legal department at the Foreign
Ministry, said the Red Cross told the Baghdad government a few hours
before the exchange that fewer Iraqis would be repatriated.
   ``We have informed the Red Cross and the United Nations that the
Iranians failed to accomplish their commitment and their
international duties,'' he told a news briefing at the airport just
before the plane arrived.
   He said Iraq would continue the repatriation but will not return
the number agreed upon unless Iran does.
   Witri said the repatriated Iraqi prisoners would be given medical
examinations before rejoining their families.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
