<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Strikes,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controller Strikes Lead To Flight Cancellations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Planned strikes by air traffic controllers and radar
operators have prompted the cancellation of at least 45 national and
international flights a day in Italy in the next seven days,
newspapers said Thursday.
   In Sudan, meanwhile, air traffic controllers stayed away from
work for a second day Thursday, paralyzing operations in Khartoum's
international airport.
   The Italian air controllers plan to strike daily from 11 a.m.
until 3 p.m. for a week beginning Friday. Radar operators have
declared they will strike from 7 a.m. until 8 p.m. Friday through
Monday.
   The controllers and radar operators are demanding higher pay and
lighter workloads. Their strikes are the latest in a series of
national labor contract disputes that have plagued Italian flight
schedules for months. Italian airline pilots ended a strike Thursday.
   The walkout by radar operators also could disrupt flights that
have not already been canceled, news reports said.
   The cancellations, announced by the state-run Alitalia Airlines
and its domestic subsidiary ATI, primarily affect flights to and
from Rome and Naples and selected incoming flights to Rome from
Switzerland, France, Greece and Africa.
   In Sudan, the strike over a wage dispute has halted both domestic
and international flights starting Wednesday morning. It is due to
end Fruday.
</TEXT>
