<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     11-24 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Fighting Erupts in South Beirut; Report Israelis Fire on TV
Crew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias clashed with
mortars, rocket-propelled grenades and machine guns for the second
time in three days in south Beirut, police said.
   They said there was no immediate report of casualties from
fighting between the pro-Syrian Amal militia and the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah. They clashed in the densely populated south Beirut slums
of Haret Hreik, Ghobeiri and Mesharrafiyeh.
   Blasts from mortars and grenades echoed across the Lebanese
capital for hours after the hostilities broke out in the afternoon.
Police closed the Beirut airport highway that runs close to the
embattled slums.
   In a separate development, U.N. sources in Tyre said Israeli
troops fired on a three-man West German TV crew that was
photographing United Nations peacekeeping troops in south Lebanon.
There were no casualties.
   The command of the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon complained to
the Israeli army about Wednesday's shooting. Israeli officers in
their self-proclaimed security zone contended they fired at the ARD
television crew because they were taking pictures of an Israeli
military position, the sources said.
   Several shots were fired at the U.N.-escorted television crew
near the village of Qaqayet El-Jisr, two miles north of the security
zone, said the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In Beirut, statements from Hezbollah, or Party of God, and Amal,
Arabic for hope, blamed each other for breaking a cease-fire called
Tuesday to halt an eight-hour flare-up in which two combatants were
killed and 10 wounded.
   Police said they could not tell what shattered that truce, which
was negotiated by the Syrian command of a peacekeeping force in
charge of security in Beirut's Moslem sector.
   The two factions long have been vying for dominance of the 1
million Shiites who are the largest single sect among Lebanon's 4
million people.
   Hezbollah has accused Amal of attempting to assassinate four
senior Hezbollah leaders by a remote-controlled car bomb in east
Lebanon's Bekaa valley on Monday. The four escaped unharmed.
   Amal earlier accused Hezbollah of assassinating its three top
commanders in a south Beirut ambush Sept. 22.
</TEXT>
