<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1454EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     11-24 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Vietnamese Pullout From Cambodia, Thais Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam has withdrawn none of the 50,000
troops it pledged to pull out of Cambodia by year's end, a Thai
military official said Thursday.
   But Col. Phanom Jinavijarana of the northeastern Burapa Field
Force said about 29,000 Vietnamese troops have retreated up to 20
miles from the Thai-Cambodian border.
   Two other regional field forces, however, interpreted recent
Vietnamese troop movements inside Cambodia as regular troop
rotations and reinforcements.
   ``Fresh units being sent to free others near the (Thai-Cambodia)
border would suggest Vietnam's new readiness to engage in escalated
fighting with the Cambodian resistance groups,'' Lt. Patana Jiranant
of the eastern Chantaburi-Trat Field Force told a monthly news
conference.
   Western analysts say more than 100,000 Vietnamese troops are in
Cambodia fighting a three-party resistance coalition of the Khmer
Rouge and two non-communist groups. Hanoi pledged to pull out all
its forces by 1990.
   Fighting is expected to intensify over the next several months,
said Supreme Command spokesman Lt. Gen. Naruedol Dejpradiyuth.
   Shells from fighting that began in early October have landed
inside six Thai border provinces, killing and wounding an
unspecified number of Thais, Naruedol said. He added that the dry
season has made it easier for warring groups to transport arms and
rapidly mobilize their troops.
   Naruedol said Vietnamese forces continued to pursue and ambush
the resistance forces, with skirmishes in Cambodia's western
provinces of Battambang, Siem Reap, Oddar Meanchey and Pursat.
   The Vietnamese, he said, also had taken positions on strategic
hills and built roads to facilitate troop deployment.
   Naruedol expressed skepticism over a recent Laotian claim that
all Vietnamese troops in communist Laos had returned to Vietnam.
   He was responding to a statement Tuesday by Laos' Deputy Foreign
Minister Soubanh Sarithirat who told Thai reporters in Vientiane
that all Hanoi's troops had left that country.
</TEXT>
