<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen in Army Uniforms Raid Sugar Factory, Kill Four</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two dozen men in Sri Lankan
army uniforms raided a sugar factory, shooting managers and their
wives and killing four after robbing them, officials said Thursday.
   An Indian and a Sri Lankan executive died when about 25 gunmen
attacked the factory's residence Wednesday night, police said.
Another Indian executive was wounded and the wives of both Indians
were killed, they said.
   ``The gunmen demanded money and after being given money, they
opened fire,'' a senior police official said, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   Police said they did not know how much money the gunmen took.
   In another development, a Cabinet minister said extremists killed
445 Sri Lankans between Oct. 15 and Nov. 15. He blamed 324 of the
killings on Sinhalese radicals and the rest on Tamil rebels.
   Many Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, want a separate homeland
because they say they are discriminated against by the majority
Sinhalese, who are predominantly Buddhist. Sinhalese extremists say
a July 1987 peace accord aimed at ending the civil war grants too
many concessions to Tamils. Indian troops are on the island to help
enforce the accord.
   Police initially attributed the sugar mill attack in southeastern
Sri Lanka to an extremist Sinhalese group, the People's Liberation
Front, but later said they were not sure of the attackers' identity.
   A spokeswoman for the Indian High Commission, or embassy, said
the attack was carried out by either Sinhalese extremists or Tamil
rebels. The spokeswoman, commenting on condition of anonymity, said
the dead Sri Lankan executive was Sinhalese.
   The sugar mill, an Indian-Sri Lankan joint business venture, is
in Siyambalanduwa, about 110 miles east of Colombo. Tamil rebels
have not been known to operate that far south, although they have
staged attacks about 20 miles north of Siyambalanduwa.
   The People's Liberation Front has used army uniforms in the past,
and front members routinely raid army camps in search of weapons.
According to the government, some members of the front are Sri
Lankan army deserters.
   The Cabinet minister's report on ethnic killings came during a
monthly debate in Parliament on extending emergency laws that have
routinely been renewed since the Tamil separatist war started in
1983. Emergency rule was extended by a vote of 80-2 in the
168-member Parliament, which has been plagued by absenteeism and
boycotts.
   Vincent Perera, minister of sports and parliamentary affairs,
said Tamil rebels killed 115 Sinhalese civilians and six Sri Lankan
security men in northern and eastern Sri Lanka in the month ending
Nov. 15. He said Sinhalese radicals had committed 112 ``political
murders'' and 212 ``other murders'' in southern and central Sri
Lanka.
   Perera said the victims of ``political murders'' were government
supporters and politicians. He said ``other murders'' referred to
the killings of government officials, police informers and civilians
who ignored strike calls issued by the People's Liberation Front.
   The front has called a series of strikes to press for the
dissolution of Parliament and the resignation of President Junius R.
Jayewardene.
   Jayewardene has said he will step down after the Dec. 19
elections to choose his successor, but the front claims his
government will not conduct a fair vote.
   About 8,500 people, mostly Sinhalese civilians, have been killed
in the Tamil guerrilla war and massacres since 1983.
   The accord offered Tamils a measure of autonomy if Tamil fighters
surrender their arms, but the largest Tamil militia rejected the
accord and is battling Indian forces. India became involved because
of its role as a regional power and the political clout of its own
Tamil minority.
</TEXT>
