<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-PLO     11-24 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-PLO,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Arafat Calls Moratorium on Attacks Against Israel from
Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lebanese newsletter claimed Thursday
that PLO leader Yasser Arafat has called a moratorium on guerrilla
attacks against Israel from Lebanon.
   It is part of Arafat's efforts to promote the newly declared
independent Palestinian state, said the English-language daily
Middle East Reporter.
   Arafat's mainstream Fatah faction of the Palestine Liberation
Organization already has received orders to halt attacks against
Israel by Lebanon-based guerrillas, the newspaper said.
   It quoted unidentified Palestinian sources as saying Arafat was
negotiating to get other PLO groups to abide by the moratorium.
   For 20 years Palestinian guerrillas have launched cross-border
attacks against northern Israeli settlements from southern Lebanon.
Earlier this year Lebanon abrogated a 1969 accord permitting the PLO
to use Lebanese territory for such attacks, but the guerrillas
ignore it.
   Middle East Reporter said Syrian-backed guerrillas opposed to
Arafat ``may try to escalate their guerrilla activity from the
Lebanese side of the border to discredit him and his policy.'' It
did not elaborate.
   The Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile,
declared an independent Palestinian state Nov. 15 at a conference in
Algiers.
   It also renounced terrorism and endorsed United Nations Security
Council resolutions 242 and 338, indirectly recognizing Israel's
right to exist.
   The PLO has announced that Arafat will address the U.N. General
Assembly in New York on the Middle East situation early in December.
   The United Nations has asked the U.S. State Department to
facilitate granting Arafat a visa.
   The PLO leader arrived in Qatar on Thursday and immediately held
talks with the emir, Sheik Khalifa Bin Hamad Thani, continuing his
swing through Arab capitals following the proclamation of a
Palestinian state.
   He already has visited North and South Yemen, Egypt, Iraq,
Morocco and Mauritania.
   The official Qatar news agency said Arafat and the emir discussed
ways of consolidating and escalating the nearly yearlong Palestinian
uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Arafat has said that 54 Arab, Islamic and non-aligned countries
have extended diplomatic ties to the new state, which would include
both territories occupied by Israel since 1967.
 
