<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BronxSchools     11-24 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bronx Schools,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kids The Losers As Schools Boards Are Probed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local residents say they're not counting on much
improvement around P.S. 64, the school where some of the local
district's suspended board members were said to have cocaine parties.
   Nothing seemed to change after a principal at a nearby elementary
school in the same South Bronx district was arrested recently on
drug charges.
   ``You got kids on drugs, you got teachers on drugs and you got an
administration on drugs,'' said Patricia Martin, the mother of two
students at P.S. 64. ``How can anyone be shocked?''
   New York City Schools Chancellor Dr. Richard Green suspended the
entire eight members of the District 9 board Wednesday saying he had
to ``take the unusual step of suspending the current school board
without having any knowledge about the long-term effects'' of a
grand jury probe into the allegations.
   The fence behind the South Bronx elementary school has gaping
holes. Shattered glass and assorted trash ring the playground. And
the local crack dealers will be back on Monday to greet the kids
after the Thanksgiving weekend.
   ``Every day, right there,'' said 11-year-old Carlos Ortiz, a
fourth-grader there, gesturing toward a street corner near the
school. ``I saw them this morning _ a lady and a man.''
   While the drug dealers worked the outside, Bronx District
Attorney Paul Gentile is investigating what went on inside the
school, where members of Community School Board No. 9 allegedly held
weekly Friday night cocaine and booze parties.
   A grand jury is also probing alleged bribery, extortion and theft
involving school boards throughout the Bronx. Gentile said Board 9
is ``the focal point'' of that probe.
   The board was unquestionably in trouble, officials said, whether
the charges are true or not. Part of the blame falls on the city's
school decentralization policy, which makes each of 32 district
boards autonomous with very few monitoring measures.
   School Board No. 9 failed to meet even those requirements,
officials said.
   It had failed to file mandatory annual reports with the Board of
Education since the 1984-5 school year, said board spokesman Frank
Sobrino. Minutes of the school board's scheduled monthly meetings
were requested by the Board of Education, but ``they haven't been
filing regularly,'' said Sobrino.
   Reading scores in the 9th _ with its 26,000 students and 34
schools in the predominately black and Hispanic area _ were the
fifth worst of the city's 32 school districts. State Sen. Israel
Ruiz said the charges of illegal activity by the board have been
``common knowledge for years.''
   While he couldn't provide an exact number, Sobrino said there
have been ``numerous complaints'' about Board No. 9. Gentile said
the allegations against the board have mushroomed in the past two
weeks since the arrest of one of its principals, Matthew Barnwell of
P.S. 53.
   Conditions at Barnwell's school are about the same as those at
P.S. 64 _ the school sits across from a vacant lot filled with
abandoned furniture, empty liquor bottles, trash bags and broken
glass. The area is so bad, residents of a neighboring nursing home
are kept inside virtually round-the-clock.
   Gentile warned the investigation would be a lengthy process
unlikely to produce any quick indictments or action.
</TEXT>
