<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1501EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     11-24 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nemeth Pursues Change With Best Qualified People, Not Best
Connected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Western-oriented economist was elected
premier Thursday and Miklos Nemeth immediately declared he wants to
reform the economy with help from the best qualified people, not the
best connected.
   Parliament approved Nemeth, 40, to replace Communist Party leader
Karoly Grosz as head of government in a show of hands with 27
deputies voting against and 36 abstaining. There are 383 deputies.
   Acknowledging polite applause, Nemeth told parliament he would
continue Grosz' program of economic reform and austerity coupled
with political change.
   To ensure efficiency and make room for a growing trend toward
more pluralism, Nemeth said, the government need not be composed
solely of Communist Party members.
   ``Work must be based not on prestige, but on high professionalism
and moral impeccability,'' he said. ``Virtues should be the basis
for selection (to top posts) ... amid a democratic framework.''
   Hungary already has a non-communist president, Bruno F. Straub,
and several other officials like Nemeth have risen to senior posts
without decades of work in the party apparatus.
   His rival for the premiership, fellow Politburo member Reszo
Nyers, was elected minister of state for economic affairs.
   At 65, Nyers is one of the most experienced men in the
leadership. The father of Hungary's stalled economic reforms of the
1960s, he was removed from the Politburo when reform was slowed in
1974 but made it back to the ruling party body in May.
   Nyers told a news conference his goals did not differ from
Nemeth's.
   Reforms must be pushed through ``if we want to maintain our
credibility'' at home and abroad, he said.
   As the Communist Party's Central Committee secretary for
economics since June 1987, Nemeth helped prepare the reforms under
Grosz, who became premier almost 18 months ago and took over as
Communist Party leader in May.
   Grosz introduced Eastern Europe's first personal income and value
added taxes, as well as laws to increase the flow of hard currency
into Hungary by loosening restrictions on foreign ownership and
joint ventures.
   The unpopular measures aim to reduce the $17 billion foreign debt
and turn a stagnating economy into what Grosz calls a ``socialist
market economy.''
   Nemeth has not had a high profile in the increasing debate over
political reform in Hungary and the possibility of a multiparty
system under the new constitution due in 1990.
   He said Thursday he favored ``social pluralism from the grass
roots.''
   A former student and then professor at Budapest's prestigious
Karl Marx University of Economics, Nemeth also spent a year at
Harvard University on a visitor's program.
   Hungary must act as a bridge between East and West, he said.
   Both Nyers and Nemeth won the unanimous approval of the Communist
Party's ruling Central Committee on Wednesday.
   But things did not go so smoothly in parliament, where
traditionally docile proceedings have given way recently to debates
that reflect growing divisions in the countryside.
   The vote was delayed an hour by Zoltan Kiraly, an outspoken
deputy who said parliament should spend more time debating who
should replace Grosz.
   Grosz said Kiraly had ``a legitimate question'' and defended the
nominations, saying he initiated Nyers' appointment so the veteran
could bring his ``great work and skill in economic matters'' to
Nemeth's government.
   Kiraly eventually was overruled.
</TEXT>
