<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Shirley Temple,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shirley Temple Black: `I've Gotten Younger'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 6 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shirley Temple Black thinks she was more mature
as a child movie star than she is as a 60-year-old former ambassador.
   ``I was never as sophisticated and as grown up as when I was 12
to 14,'' she said in the current issue of Parade magazine. ``Ever
since, I've gotten younger.''
   The most rewarding part of that early career, she said, is ``the
cross-generation popularity of those movies. Just about everyone of
every age has the ability to enjoy my films.''
   Mrs. Black, a former ambassador to Ghana, works part-time at the
State Department, training new ambassadors for overseas assignments.
But she has bigger goal.
   ``I'd like to be director of the U.S. Information Agency,'' she
said. ``With my background in entertainment and government service,
I think I'd be good at it.''
   ``You may not know, but early in the Reagan years there was
speculation that Walter Cronkite would become USIA director and I
would be his deputy,'' she added. ``But this time, I'd (like to) be
the head and he'd be the deputy.''
