<DOCNO> AP881124-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1509EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrotherVets     11-24 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brother Vets,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Vets Travel to Help Soviet Afhghan Vets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM LACEKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Vietnam combat veterans are heading for
the Soviet Union to reassure some brother war veterans that their
fears, anger, sadness and depression are normal human reactions to
war.
   ``If just one person had assured me I was OK, that it was a
normal reaction, it would have made an incredible difference in my
life,'' Todd Brandoff said, recalling the five years he figures
Vietnam took from his life.
   The Soviet soldiers are not veterans of Vietnam, but of
Afghanistan _ the Soviet military men called ``Afhghantsi.'' Their
destination is Alma-Ata, a city of about 1 million almost on the
Chinese border and only about 500 miles northeast of Afghanistan.
   ``What we're attempting to do is, in a period of two weeks, try
to share with the Soviet veterans from Afghanistan what it's taken
us 20 to 25 years to learn about delayed stress and post-traumatic
stress,'' Brandoff said.
   The five men, all from Missoula, will be in a group of 30 who
will fly into Moscow on Monday to begin two weeks as guests of the
Soviet government and the men they hope to help. They are paying
$1,600 to $1,800 apiece to get to Moscow, but the Soviet government
will pay for their travel in the U.S.S.R., some 4,000 miles, and
they will stay in private homes.
   ``I think the Soviet people are anxious for this to take place,''
said another of the five, Steve Lohning, addictions therapist with
the Recovery Foundation.
   News reports about the Soviet Union's difficulties in Afghanistan
set the Missoula veterans musing about being able to talk to the
Afghantsi, Lohning recalled. Then they learned that such a trip was
being organized by Diana Glasgow of Earthstewards Network, based in
Bainbridge, Wash. She has guided 20 such trips to the Soviet Union
in the last three years, Brandoff said.
   ``We'll be talking about delayed stress and effects of the war
... on an apolitical basis,'' he said. ``We are men who were called
up by our countries to fight an unpopular war. That makes us their
brothers _ big brothers, because we have 20 years on 'em.
   ``The Soviets have not been spat on and despised, but in many
cases their parents still think they were in Afghanistan planting
trees.''
   The Soviets have no equivalent of our Veterans Administration,
Brandoff said.
   ``They don't have anything officially, as far as I know, an
agency of the government where they can go and say, `I'm stressed
out, having problems with my wife, drinking too much, taking drugs.''
   Brandoff, co-pilot of an assault helicopter, was wounded in an
ambush that shot down 12 of 14 helicopters in the flight, all in
about one minute. His helicopter managed to land, but it had 17
holes in it and Brandoff had seven, plus shrapnel wounds.
   Brandoff, a writer and salesman of industrial textiles, considers
himself fortunate to have survived as well as he did, despite seven
operations and years of depression and post-traumatic stress
symptoms.
   The trip to the Soviet Union is full of ironies. Brandoff says he
and some other veterans are sure they were wounded with Soviet-made
weapons. He is certain that some of the Afghantsi were wounded by
American-made weapons.
   Lohning paused when asked why he was willing to pay so much money
for this trip. He spoke of his occupation, of helping people deal
with pain and confusion, and of directions in his own life.
   ``I've got some skills,'' he said finally, ``and I think it's
time for people to start sharing what we've got instead of killing
people.
   ``I'm willing to pay the money to do that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
