<HEAD>Toyota May Make Small Trucks in United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Toyota Motor Corp. is negotiating with General
Motors on joint production of Toyota's one-ton truck in the United
States, a Toyota official said Thursday.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, was commenting
on a news report that Toyota plans to produce 100,000 of the trucks
annually, beginning in 1990 at the earliest, at a plant the two
companies operate in Fremont, Calif., in 1984.
   ``Dicussions (on small truck production) between Toyota and GM
are still underway,'' he said without elaborating.
   Kyodo News Service reported the two companies plan to rebuild the
idle GM plant at their joint venture New United Motor Manufacturing
Co. compound in Freemont, near San Francisco, at a cost of tens of
millions of dollars.
   Kyodo said Toyota has applied to the Bay Area Air Quality
Management District to increase the level of exhaust gas produced by
the plant.
   The Toyota official said the Freemont plant's application to the
air quality district ``was made to allow them more flexibility with
possible production expansion in the future. This doesn't signal a
decision on truck production there.''
   The Freemont plant produces 250,000 passenger cars a year, Kyodo
said.
   Toyota, Japan's largest automaker, sells about 300,000 small
trucks a year in the United States.
