<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Soviet     11-24 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Soviet,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand to Offer Guaranteed Loans to Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French banks and the Soviet Union are preparing a
loan package, part of it made up of export credits guaranteed by the
French government, the finance minister said Thursday.
   The French credit package is expected to be signed during a
two-day visit by President Francois Mitterrand to Moscow that begins
Friday.
   Finance Minister Pierre Beregovoy, speaking to reporters, did not
specify the amount, although Foreign Minister Roland Dumas said in a
radio interview that loans of about $2 billion were being made
available to the Soviets.
   Dumas also said the loans would be linked to progress in
disarmament talks on conventional weapons in Europe, but he did not
spell out how the connection would be made.
   The French hope the credit package will boost economic
cooperation between the two countries. Several large business deals
are expected to be signed during the visit.
   France has been running a trade deficit with the Soviet Union
that in the first nine months of 1988 amounted to about $62 million.
   Beregovoy declined to give details on the credit package except
to say that the interest rates would be variable.
   France would be the fourth West European country to offer trade
credits to Moscow in recent weeks following similar packages signed
with Britain, Italy and West Germany.
   Credit Lyonnais, the state-owned bank which is lead manager for
the consortium of lending banks engineering the credit package,
declined to comment on Beregovoy's statement.
