<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SharpevilleSix 1stLd-Writethru a0576 11-24 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharpeville Six, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0576,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Critics Urge Botha To Follow Reprieves With Bolder Moves</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 10th graf ``I call...'' to ADD Mandela
development. Pick up 11th graf `Prakdash Diar...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha's decision
to spare the lives of the ``Sharpeville Six'' earned him rare praise
from around the world, but his critics at home want further proof of
his good will.
   Several leading human rights activists Thursday demanded the
abolition of capital punishment. Other government opponents
suggested Botha acted out of expediency and called for him to free
political prisoners like Nelson Mandela and dismantle apartheid,
South Africa's legalized race separation.
   Across the political spectrum, there was agreement that Botha
made a politically astute move Wednesday when he commuted the death
sentences of 13 people.
   They included four white policemen convicted of killing
non-whites and the Sharpeville Six _ five black men and a woman
convicted of complicity in the killing of a black official during
1984 rent riots.
   ``The arbitrariness of the selection of those reprieved is
frightening,'' said Brian Currin, director of South Africa's Lawyers
for Human Rights Organization. ``Why should others, who do not
become political play balls, be less fortunate?''
   He commented after five convicted murderers were hanged at dawn
Thursday. Just before, two other condemned men were granted stays of
execution so clemency petitions could be considered.
   So far this year, 115 people including three whites have been
executed while Botha has reprieved 49 Death Row prisoners, the
Prison Service said. More than 200 people still await execution.
   The Rev. Stanley Mogoba, president of South Africa's Methodist
Church, said the clemency was ``one of the best Christmas presents I
can think of.''
   ``Mr. Botha has illustrated, in this statesmanlike act of
reprieve, that he too understands the Christian message of peace and
good will,'' Mogoba said.
   ``I call on him to extend this understanding to others, in
different ways, such as releasing political prisoners like Mandela
... and dismantling the heretical structures that prop up
apartheid,'' he added.
   The government showed further flexibility in Mandela's case
Thursday when Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee said the 70-year-old
black leader won't be put back in prison after he recovers from
tuberculosis.
   Mandela will be moved to a ``suitable, comfortable and secure''
location from a private clinic where he is hospitalized, Coetsee
said in a statement.
   Mandela, head of the outlawed African National Congress, was
sentenced to life in prison for plotting sabotage against the white
minority government. He has refused to renounce violence in exchange
for his freedom.
   Prakash Diar, lawyer for the Sharpeville Six, was bitter that
Botha gave his clients long prison terms _ 18-25 years _ instead of
freeing them.
   Two of his clients ``believe that they would be better off if
they hanged rather than spending such long times in prison,'' Diar
said.
   Cape Town's Argus newspaper questioned whether ``premeditated,
cold-blooded murder'' by policemen should be equated with a crime
committed ``in the heat of a public upheaval.''
   One of the most negative reactions came from an official of the
South-West African People's Organization, the leftist guerilla
movement fighting to end South African rule over South-West Africa,
also known as Namibia.
   Nayuala Kapuka, SWAPO's chief representative in Zimbabwe, called
the reprieves a ``hoodwinking ploy'' to fool the international
community.
   They came barely 24 hours after another South African action was
welcomed internationally _ the acceptance of a Namibian peace plan.
   The Times of London linked the developments in an editorial
Thursday that said they ``suggest a new mood of flexibility in a
government whose chief characteristic has too often been
self-defeating intransigence.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
