<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mandela 1stLd-Writethru a0583 11-24 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandela, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0583,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Says Mandela Won't Go Back to Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf `Earlier Thursday...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with Winnie Mandela comment. Pickup 8th graf `Robertson, a...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jailed black leader Nelson Mandela
won't be returning to his prison upon his recovery from tuberculosis
but will be moved to a ``suitable, comfortable and secure''
location, the justice minister said Thursday.
   The 70-year-old Mandela, head of the outlawed African National
Congress and the country's best-known black leader, has been
recovering from tuberculosis since August in a private clinic in a
suburb of Cape Town.
   The statement by Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee did not give any
details on when Mandela would leave the hospital, where he would be
taken, or what restrictions he would face.
   It strongly suggested, however, that the government was trying to
gradually release Mandela, whose freedom has been the object of a
worldwide campaign.
   Mandela's health ``has improved to such an extent that should the
improvement continue it will eventually no longer be necessary to
care for him in a clinic,'' Coetsee said.
   ``When the time arrives he will be transferred to suitable,
comfortable and secure living accommodation, where he will be able
to receive members of his family more freely and on a continual
basis,'' Coetsee added.
   Mandela's wife, Winnie, said in a statement issued by family
attorney Ismail Ayob that she ``attaches no significance to the
statement.''
   ``Mr. Mandela still remains a prisoner of the South African
government and there is no indication of any imminent release,'' the
statement said.
   Earlier Thursday, President P.W. Botha reportedly made a
statement similar to Coetsee. U.S. evangelist Pat Robertson said
Botha told him Mandela would not return to prison from the clinic
but might be kept under guard for his own protection.
   Robertson, a TV preacher and former Republican presidential
candidate, told reporters he and Botha had spoken about Mandela
during a meeting at government headquarters in Pretoria.
   Part of the discussion was taped for broadcast in the United
States on Friday, but Robertson did not say if the Mandela
discussion would be included.
   Standing on the steps outside Botha's office, Robertson said the
president had just told him Mandela ``will not be returned to
prison, but I did not get any indication he would be released.
   ``I believe President Botha was quite concerned, as he expressed
it to me, that there's a real possibility that Mr. Mandela might be
assassinated by people either to the left wing or the right wing of
the country, and he doesn't want that to happen,'' Robertson said.
   ``He (Botha) said he did not feel that (Mandela) would be
returned to prison but would be placed in some other type of _ he
didn't use the term `protective custody,' those are my words _ but
some other environment after he finishes his stay in the clinic.''
   Mandela has been jailed since 1962. He is serving a life sentence
for conspiring with other leaders of the African National Congress
to wage an anti-government sabotage campaign.
   In early August, Mandela was transferred from the Pollsmoor
Prison to the state-run Tygerberg Hospital for treatment of
tuberculosis. Since Aug. 31 he had been recuperating in the clinic.
   In 1985, Mandela rejected a government offer to set him free if
he renounced violence. Recently, Botha has hinted that Mandela could
be released without meeting this condition, but the government has
made no definitive statement on the matter.
   The reports Thursday appeared to support a statement made in
Washington by South African Ambassador Piet Koornhof that Mandela
``is no longer in prison.'' Koornhof reportedly said Mandela was in
the process of being returned to society and felt he would be
released ``sooner rather than later.''
   Robertson is in South Africa meeting political leaders and
producing shows for his Christian Broadcasting Network. He said he
hoped to meet Sunday with Mandela's wife, Winnie, before a religious
rally in the black township of Soweto.
   Robertson said Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu had refused to
meet with him. Tutu is a former Nobel Peace Prize-winner and a
leading opponent of apartheid, the system under which South Africa's
26 million black majority ahs no say in national affairs.
</TEXT>
