<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1547EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Prices     11-24 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Prices,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Food Costs High, More State Subsidies to Come</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite heavy subsidies, food in
Czechoslovakia costs 2{ times more than in West Germany in relative
terms, the state news agency CTK reported Thursday.
   Food costs, especially in the lower-income group of the
population, ``represent a decisive component of the family budget,''
said CTK, quoting a recent survey conducted by several Czechoslovak
research institutes.
   ``It turns out that especially in young families with several
children, the needs of nutrition are not fully met, especially as
far as nutrients are concerned,'' the report said. It added that the
problem also affects ``almost one third of all pensioners.''
   In Czechoslovakia, retail food prices are 2{ times higher than in
West Germany, 1.8 times higher than in East Germany and 1.1 times
above those in Austria, according to the survey. CTK said it was
based on the number of working hours needed to purchase 2.2 pounds
of given products such as meat, fruit or vegetables.
   Foodstuffs in Czechoslovakia are subsidized heavily by the
government.
   In 1986, the state food production, including tobacco products,
yielded a $4 billion profit, while subsidies totaled $2.2 billion,
CTK said.
   ``It is true that some foodstuffs are subsidized, and this
concerns mainly milk and milk products ... but on the whole the
state does not lose money in food production,'' the agency said.
   In anticipation of the restructuring of wholesale prices in the
economy on Jan. 1, 1989, and after a partial ban on food exports and
over-the-counter sale curbs, popular fears of retail food price
increases have led to panic buying in some shops.
   Vaclav Grametbauer of the Czechoslovak Finance Ministry was
quoted by the Communist Party daily Rude Pravo Thursday as saying
state subsidies will keep food prices at current levels in 1989.
   Subsidies are likely to equal the state's entire income from the
turnover tax on foodstuffs, including higher profits from alcoholic
drinks, cigarettes and coffee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
