<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Education     11-24 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Education,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students, Teachers of 15 Universities Hold Two-Day Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students and teachers of 15 universities
and colleges held protest strikes Thursday demanding reforms, higher
subsidies and wider autonomy for higher education, the state news
agency MTI reported.
   One government official went on record as promising some
financial improvement, but sweeping reform may take years.
   The two-day boycott, which began Wednesday, was the latest in a
series of protest actions on higher education in Hungary.
   In the spring, students first spoke of crisis symptoms in
university education at a ``student parliament'' in Veszprem.
   In September, students at Szeged and Pecs universities launched a
warning strike. The Szeged students presented demands to the
Ministry of Education and Culture of radical improvement of the
financial status of universities, the protection of the real value
of scholarships, and an improvement of living and working conditions
of students and teachers.
   In its reply, the ministry indicated that between three and five
years might be required ``to overcome the difficulties,'' MTI said.
   The students reportedly rejected several points of the
ministerial reply and decided to stage the two-day strike to express
their dissatisfaction.
   Andras Rupp, a senior government official Thursday was quoted by
the Communist Party daily newspaper Nepszabadsag as promising that
the higher education budget would reach $256 million in 1989.
   A higher education development fund set up this year will be
increased in 1989, Rupp said, and the sum allocated for social
allowances and scholarships will be raised by 10 percent.
   Rupp reportedly promised that teachers' salaries would be
increased by 6 percent, rejecting a demand for a 40 percent
increase. Hungary's current annual inflation rate is about 18
percent.
</TEXT>
