<2ND_LINE>AM-Ride Collapse,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fair Re-Opens, Deadly Accident Probed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State investigators examined a carnival
ride Thursday that partially collapsed while in operation and killed
a teen-ager at the Broward County Fair.
   The fair's other rides and shows were operating as usual.
   One of six arms of the whirling ``Giant Octopus'' or ``Spider''
ride broke apart and crashed to the ground Wednesday evening,
authorities said. Each arm supported four cars, and about 40 people
were in the cars that fell nearly 10 feet, authorities said. At
least seven people were injured.
   Wallace Rich, chief of the state Bureau of Fairs and Expositions,
and deputy George Kolias were conducting the investigation.
   Investigators believe the dead girl was in a car connected to
another arm and was struck by the falling part of the machine.
   ``It was going faster than usual, really spinning fast, and then
all of the sudden it started shaking, and the wires got caught
between one another and then the cubes crashed to the ground,'' said
Heather Humphrey, 13, who was not injured.
   ``I turned around and looked, and a girl had her head thrown back
and there was blood all over the place,'' said Jennifer Hopp, 13.
   Some passengers were stranded above ground and were helped out of
the cars by other fairgoers, police said.
   The fair began Nov. 16 and will close Sunday.
   ``The fair is pretty safe,'' Hallandale Mayor Sonny Rosenberg
said. ``Unfortunately, these things sometimes happen. The fair will
continue. Unfortunately, we had a fatality, and that's tragic.''
   Authorities said Christy Schafale, 17, from Cooper City, was dead
of head injuries on arrival at Humana Hospital-Biscayne in Miami.
   Police said at least seven people sought medical and one was
hospitalized in satisfactory condition.
</TEXT>
