<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Army     11-24 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Army,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prospect of Orthodox in Government Spurs Draft Evasion Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prospect of ultra-Orthodox religious parties
joining the government sparked debate among former generals Thursday
over charges that some possible Cabinet ministers would encourage
draft dodging.
   The issue arose from deferments from military service given
students in yeshivas, or Jewish seminaries, and reports that
Orthodox parties may ask to widen the deferments as a price for
joining a coalition government.
   Thirty-five top reserve officers from both left and right signed
a petition accusing religious party leaders of being ``actively
against army service.''
   Industry Minister Ariel Sharon, himself a reserve general,
accused signers of mixing army duty and politics and called the
petition a ``dangerous and serious development'' in an interview
Thursday on army radio.
   One signer, reserve Gen. Meir Zorea, challenged Sharon on the
same station.
   Zorea said of the religious leaders:
   ``They want to send our sons to war and keep their sons at home.
Is there a difference between their blood and ours?''
   The deferment practice already has stirred anger in a country
where nearly all 18-year-old Jewish men and women go into military
service as a sacred duty.
   The petition was sent Wednesday to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
and was printed Thursday in three major Israeli newspapers.
   Shamir rejected it, said his spokesman, Yossi Ahimeir. He said
Shamir understood the signers' motives, but would pursue efforts to
build a government with three ultra-Orthodox parties.
   The petition said the signers were fearful ``about the intention
to form a government in which 20 percent of its components aid and
abet evasion of army duty by yeshiva students.''
   ``We are fearful of the dimensions of evasion and the dangers of
it being widened and deepened.''
   It expressed ``concern for the moral and educational implications
of having many ministers and deputy ministers active in the
government against army service and against devotion to the defense
of the State of Israel.''
   Former military commanders in the occupied territories and
Lebanon were among the signers.
   ``I want to make very clear to my colleagues, we are embarking on
a very dangerous path,'' Sharon said. ``Today it is one reason and
tomorrow it could be another reason why army personnel will try to
determine who should be a Cabinet minister.''
   Political sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, say the
ultra-Orthodox parties may gain five Cabinet ministries.
   Shamir's Likud bloc won 40 seats in the 120-member parliament in
Nov. 1 elections and the Labor Party won 39. Shamir seeks support
from small religious parties to govern.
   Religious parties worked out an arrangement after Israel's
founding in 1948 for seminary students to postpone army duty. The
number deferred amounts to up to 20,000 men a year.
   Ultra-Orthodox leaders argue that religious study is as crucial
to the survival of the Jewish people as serving in the army.
   Nine legislators from right-wing and Orthodox parties meanwhile
said in a bill submitted Thursday that any soldier or civilian who
violates standing regulations on opening fire ``for security
reasons'' should be pardoned.
   Army radio said the bill came in response to pressure from Jewish
settlers confronted with the nearly yearlong Palestinian uprising in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip in which 317 Palestinians and
11 Israelis have died.
   Standing orders allow troops to fire only in event of danger to
life. Settlers can use firearms only as a last resort.
</TEXT>
