<HEAD>Three Accused of Helping Banker Flee in Greek Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor charged a leading businessman
Thursday with helping a banker flee Greece in his private jet during
a major scandal, and the government said it asked the United States
to extradite the fugitive.
   The scandal has shaken Premier Andreas Papandreou's socialist
government, which was accused of initially hesitating to investigate
charges involving misuse of hundreds of millions of dollars in bank
funds. Two Cabinet ministers have already been forced to resign.
   Athens District Attorney Yannis Gavrilis accused Argyris
Saliarelis of allowing banker and publisher George Koskotas to leave
Greece aboard Saliarelis' Lear jet on Nov. 6. Two pilots were
charged Thursday with concealing a criminal and helping him escape.
   Saliarelis reportedly said his private jet was used without his
knowledge.
   U.S. agents arrested the 34-year-old Koskotas in Bedford, Mass.,
on Wednesday night shortly after he arrived at a small airport.
   Koskotas, former chairman of the Bank of Crete and now wanted for
fraud and embezzlement in Greece, was in Brazil before flying to
America.
   The Greek government announced Thursday it asked U.S. authorities
to extradite Koskotas to face charges of misusing over $300 million
of bank funds.
   News media said earlier that several ministers and senior
socialist party officials were involved with Koskotas in illegal
money transfers abroad.
