<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SovietConstitution     11-24 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Constitution,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kremlin May Compromise on Constitutional Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin indicated Thursday it is open to
compromise on proposed constitutional changes that provoked
accusations of an attempt by Moscow to usurp power from the 15
Soviet republics.
   Tass said ``it was noted'' by the Communist Party's ruling
Politburo ``that nationwide debates on draft laws on changes to the
constitution and on elections of people's deputies of the U.S.S.R.,
which are drawing to a close, have attested to a widely shared
public interest in these matters.''
   ``Suggestions that have come in from working people make it
possible to substantially improve the bills (and) reflect public
opinion in them more fully,'' said the report by the official news
agency.
   The Supreme Soviet, the national parliament, is to meet Tuesday
to consider constitutional amendments that would establish a Council
of People's Deputies, which in turn would elect a full-time
legislature and a president with enhanced powers.
   One republic, Estonia, denounced changes that would centralize
power and declared its own ``sovereignty'' in all but defense and
foreign affairs, claiming the power to reject national laws.
   Authorities have mounted considerable opposition to the Baltic
republic's declaration, but some republics and a parliamentary
commission studying the amendments have recommended concessions.
   In Tbilisi, capital of the southern republic of Georgia, several
thousand demonstrators were reported to have gathered Thursday to
protest the amendments.
   Members of a grassroots Lithuanian political group arrived in
Moscow with a petition to the Supreme Soviet demanding sovereignty
for their republic. They claimed it bore 1.8 million signatures.
   Lithuania's legislature balked at pressure from activists for a
``declaration of sovereignty'' similar to Estonia's and the
legislature of the other Baltic republic, Latvia, also stopped short
of declaring autonomy.
   The three Baltic republics were independent between the world
wars but the Soviet Union annexed them in 1940 by agreement with
Nazi Germany.
   There have been indications the Supreme Soviet will declare
Estonia's actions unconstitutional, which could force a showdown
with the tiny republic.
   According to Tass, the executive body of the Byelorussian
leglislature said Estonia's actions ``contradict the constitution of
the U.S.S.R., are at odds with the fundamental principles underlying
the Soviet socialist federation and do not contribute to
strengthening the integral Soviet multinational state and furthering
the perestroika reform drive.''
   It approved the ``basic provisions'' of the proposed amendments,
Tass said, but the dispatch gave no indication whether it expressed
reservations about particular sections or recommended changes.
   Several other legislative bodies also have criticized the
Estonian declaration.
   Perestroika is the name Mikhail S. Gorbachev, president and
Communist Party chief, gives to his program of economic and social
reform.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
