<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brite     11-24 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brite,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FOREST PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Candy and flowers are all right for some
folks, but Providenza Imburgia's children salute their 93-year-old
matriarch every day, year round, on a bus-stop bench.
   ``When your mother gets up in years, what can you do? She's
already got everything she needs,'' said son Joseph Imburgia, 64.
   These days, Mrs. Imburgia's bench displays a family tree _
children, grandchildren, great-grandchildren _ 46 names descended
from Providenza and her husband, Dominic, a fruit peddler who died
in 1949. They came to America from Palermo, Sicily, and married in
1913.
   ``It's wonderful!'' Mrs. Imburgia says of the bench.
   In the past, the bench has carried loving messages like
``Happiness to all, and to Providenza Imburgia,'' or ``Happy
Mother's Day to all mothers, especially Providenza Imburgia.''
   Thousands of people walk or drive past the advertising bench
daily, many en route, by bus or on foot, to the nearby elevated
train station.
   The bench was a 1982 inspiration, when Mrs. Imburgia's children
ran out of birthday ideas.
   ``We thought about skywriting, or renting a neon `Happy Birthday'
sign with a generator to put in front of her house, but we decided
on the bench because it was more permanent,'' said Joseph.
</TEXT>
