<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-24 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow, Rain, Wind In The West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A winter-like weather system spread snow over the Rockies on
Thursday and a second storm dumped rain and snow along the northern
Pacific Coast.
   A low pressure system over Colorado with a cold front trailing to
the southwest affected the central and northern Rockies. Cold air
behind the front held afternoon temperatures in the 30s and 40s.
   Northern Utah got heavy, wet snow that apparently contributed to
scattered power outages. In the Wasatch Front range, Snowbird ski
resort reported 16 inches of new snow, Alta had 15 inches and Park
City had 12.
   Much of southeastern Idaho got 1 to 2 inches of snow, and 2
inches fell at Boise during the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m. EST.
   Light snow fell over parts of Wyoming. The heaviest snowfall in
north-central Wyoming was 6 to 8 inches at Bear Lodge and Arrowhead
in the Big Horn Mountains. Five inches of new snow was reported at
Dayton and 4{ inches fell at Story.
   Strong, gusty wind blew ahead of the low pressure system, with a
gust to 55 mph at Guadalupe Pass in Texas, and 70 mph near Fort
Collins, Colo.
   Another low pressure system approaching the Pacific Northwest
spread moist air over the northern and central Pacific Coast.
   Rain fell along the coasts of northern California and western
Oregon. Heavy snow fell over parts of the Cascade range, with a foot
over the Santiam Pass in Oregon.
   A heavy snow warning was issued for Oregon's Cascades and
Siskiyou, a winter storm warning was posted for Oregon's Coast
range, and snow advisories were issued for eastern Oregon, the
Cascades of Washington, northeastern California, the northern Sierra
Nevadas, and mountain areas near Lake Tahoe.
   A series of storms that began Tuesday blanketed the Sierra Nevada
with up to 4 feet of new snow. ``This will be one of the best, if
not the best, Thanksgiving weekends we've ever had,'' Squaw Valley
spokesman Bill Jensen said. Heavenly Valley opened last Saturday,
the earliest since 1973.
   In the Atlantic, weakening tropical storm Keith blew through the
British island of Bermuda, where no major problems were reported,
and began disappearing into a northern storm front, forecasters
said. Its sustained wind speed was 45 mph, down from the 65 mph wind
it had when it cross Florida late Tuesday and early Wednesday.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 19
degrees at Yellowstone National Park to 82 degrees at Laredo, Texas.
Thursday morning's low was zero at Ely, Nev.
   For Friday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from
Louisiana across the middle Mississippi Valley. Light snow was
forecast over western Minnesota. Widespread rain was forecast over
the central and northern Pacific Coast with snow inland and at
higher elevations.
   Highs in the 20s and 30s were predicted over the northern
Intermountain region between the Sierra Nevada and Rockies, the
northern and central Rockies, the northern Plains, northwestern
Minnesota and northern Maine; in the 40s and 50s from the northern
Pacific Coast across the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah, the
southern Rockies, northwestern Texas and Oklahoma, the central
Plains, the lower Missouri Valley and the Great Lakes to the
northern and middle Atlantic Coast; in the 80s over south-central
Texas and the southern half of the Florida Peninsula; and in the 60s
and 70s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
