<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Keith     11-24 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Keith,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Heads for Bermuda After Raking Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weakening Tropical Storm Keith blew through the
British island of Bermuda on Thursday and began disappearing into a
northern stormfront, forecasters said.
   As a tropical storm, Keith crossed Florida's midsection late
Tuesday and Wednesday with winds of 65 mph and slashing rains. Lower
Atlantic temperatures chilled it down to 45 mph sustained winds by
Thursday afternoon, although there were gusts of 64 mph.
   ``It's now extratropical. It's expected to merge with a big
wintertime storm to the northeast and we will lose track of its
identity,'' said forecaster Bob Case at the National Hurricane
Center.
   At 5 p.m. EST Thursday, the center of Keith's remnants was near
latitude 35.0 north and longitude 64.0 west, or about 200 miles
north-northeast of Bermuda, and it was moving north-northeast at 40
mph.
   No major problems were reported on Bermuda after gale-force winds
and rains swept across with Keith.
   In Florida, it left large sections of shoreline eroded in the
Sarasota and St. Petersburg Beach areas and on the island of Captiva.
   At its worst, the storm was blamed for heavy winds and rain that
flipped over a truck near Tampa Bay area. Tornadoes spawned by the
storm damaged some 25 mobile homes in Lake County, in the state's
midsection, and in Tampa, and flooding was reported in low-lying
areas in the storm's path.
   The storm also was blamed for the derailment of 34 cars of a
cargo train Wednesday near Lakeland because of a railroad bed washed
out by rain.
</TEXT>
