<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0611,0943</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Violence in Azerbaijan; Hundreds of Armenians Flee</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 1-2 to recast. PICKS up 3rd pvs: `Musa Mamedov, ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More deaths were reported Thursday in a renewed
outbreak of ethnic rioting in Azerbaijan despite the deployment of
Soviet troops and tanks to put down violence in three cities,
officials said.
   Hundreds of ethnic Armenians were said to be fleeing the republic
of Azerbaijan for their adjacent homeland. Troops reportedly used
helicopters and trucks to evacuate women and children from one
troubled area after the worst outbreak of violence since the first
days of ethnic disturbances in the Soviet south in February.
   Musa Mamedov, chief of the information department of the
Azerbaijani Foreign Ministry, said Thursday night that reports from
the city of Kirovabad were sketchy but that several people had been
killed in the latest outburst.
   ``There were more outbreaks of violence,'' Mamedov said, speaking
by telephone from the Azerbaijani capital of Baku. ``There are
victims, deaths.''
   Tass, in a report read on the nightly news program ``Vremya,''
blamed the deteriorating situation on ``irresponsible nationalistic
elements'' and acknowledged there was fighting between Armenians and
Azerbaijanis.
   Meanwhile, in the neighboring republic of Georgia, several
thousand demonstrators were reported to have gathered in the capital
of Tbilisi to protest proposed amendments to the Soviet Constitution
that have prompted complaints the Kremlin is trying to monopolize
power and weaken the legislatures of the 15 constituent republics.
   Also, members of a grassroots Lithuanian political organization
arrived in Moscow to deliver a petition to the Supreme Soviet, or
parliament, demanding sovereignty for their republic. They claimed
the petition bore the signatures of 1.8 million citizens of the
once-independent Baltic republic.
   In Kirovabad on Tuesday, mobs killed three soldiers, and 126
people were injured, according to Azerbaijani and Soviet officials.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov told
reporters in Moscow that tanks and troops had been sent to
Kirovabad, Baku and a third Azerbaijani city, Nakhivechan, to
restore order. A 10 p.m.-to-5 a.m. curfew had been imposed, he said.
   In Nakhichevan, border troops evacuated at least 500 Armenian
women and children to Armenia, using ``helicopters, trucks and
anything else they could find,'' said Boris Kufaryan, senior editor
of Armenia's official Armenpress news agency. ``The men stayed
behind to defend their homes.''
   Kufaryan, speaking by telephone from the Armenian capital of
Yerevan, said more than 1,700 Armenians who fled from Azerbaijan in
recent days had registered as refugees in his republic with an
official commission created to help them.
   Nakhichevan is the capital of a region of the same name that
belongs to Azerbaijan but is separated from the main part of the
republic by Armenia. According to the 1970 census, 190,000
Azerbaijanis share the region with 6,000 Armenians.
   The two groups, divided by religion, language and national
heritage, have a long history of ethnic rivalry. Armenians are
predominantly Christian and Azerbaijanis are predominantly Moslem.
   In Kirovabad, frightened Armenians formed an emergency committee
to send their women and children to Armenia, Arpenay Popoyan, wife
of Armenian activist Rafael Popoyan, said from Yerevan. She said
they asked the military authorities sent to the city to provide
transport.
   ``The situation is sharply deteriorating in Azerbaijan,'' Mrs.
Popoyan said in a report echoed later by Tass, the official Soviet
news agency.
   Tensions have been running high in the Caucasus since February,
when Armenians began agitating for the annexation of
Nagorno-Karabakh, a predominantly Armenian enclave in Azerbaijan.
Azerbaijani officials and Kremlin leaders have rejected the demand.
   Azerbaijanis say hundreds of thousands of people began taking to
the streets in Baku last week to protest what they say is an
Armenian effort to send settlers to Nagorno-Karabakh to strengthen
the Armenian majority there. The numbers could not be confirmed, and
obtaining reliable reports from the affected areas was difficult.
Telephone operators said phone lines to Azerbaijan were constantly
busy, and few calls were getting through.
   According to Azerbaijani officials and media, Armenian settlers
were taken last week to the Shusha area of Nagorno-Karabakh in
official trucks and began building an aluminum processing plant and
barracks with materials supplied by the Armenian government.
   ``The reason for these recent events is the illegal construction
in Nagorno-Karabakh,'' Savelli A. Perets, head of the official
Azerbaijani news agency Azerinform, said in a telephone interview.
   Mamedov, the republic's Foreign Ministry spokesman, said mobs in
Kirovabad and Nakhichevan attacked local government headquarters and
thetroops defending the buildings.
   Gerasimov said an army lieutenant and two privates were killed in
the Kirovabad violence.
   Mrs. Popoyan said reports from Kirovabad said the soldiers were
attacked while trying to defend Armenians, and that dozens of the
rioters were injured.
   A ``special situation'' was declared in Nakhichevan and
Kirovabad, and army troops, tanks and armored personnel carriers
sent into the streets of Baku and the two other cities to quell the
unrest, Azerbaijani officials said.
   ``The cities are now under control of the army,'' Mamedov said
earlier Thursday. ``The situation is still difficult.'' Later, he
reported violence had broken out again.
   He said from 50,000 to 100,000 protesters were on the streets of
Baku, and Perets said only 70 percent to 80 percent of the labor
force in the oil-producing industrial city on the Caspian Sea was at
work.
   A half-million Armenians live in Azerbaijan, whose total
population is 6.9 million, and Perets said the Armenian quarters of
Baku had been ringed by soldiers backed by armored personnel
carriers to protect the inhabitants.
</TEXT>
