<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     11-24 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Decides to End Coalition Talks with Likud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Party's governing body voted
overwhelmingly Thursday to end coalition talks with the right-wing
Likud bloc and set strict guidelines for any future negotiations.
   The new rules, opposed by Shimon Peres, the party leader and
Israeli foreign minister, prohibit party leaders from negotiating
with Likud without the consent of the 125-member governing bureau.
   Talks between the center-left party and Likud on a possible joint
government deadlocked this week. Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir leads
the conservative bloc.
   Shamir and Peres have been in a tenuous ``national unity''
coalition as equal partners since indecisive elections in July 1984.
Likud won 40 of the 120 parliament seats in Nov. 1 elections and
Labor got 39.
   Likud has negotiated with small religious and right-wing parties
for a majority coalition, but the small parties made numerous
demands and Likud offered Labor a junior partnership in a new
coalition.
   Israel radio said Likud was continuing negotiations with the
small parties and might form a coalition by next week.
   Of the Labor vote Thursday, party secretary-general Uzi Baram
said on the radio: ``The decision shows that there is no basis for
negotiations with the Likud.''
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, a former Labor prime minister,
said on state television: ``In my view there is no significance to
what was decided. The talks with Likud were at their invitation to
form a joint government and the Likud knows that official
negotiations would need the party's permission.''
   Peres said talks could continue as long as official proposals
were brought before the party bureau. ``If in the future there is a
proposal, it will be brought before this body,'' he said as he left
the meeting.
   The radio said Shamir and Peres planned to meet by eary next week.
   A Foreign Ministry official said privately he could not confirm
whether a meeting would take place but added that contacts could
continue. ``The vote does not rule out contacts between party
members,'' he said.
</TEXT>
