<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0594,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Fatally Shot; Nine Palestinians Wounded In Clashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with attacks on
Jewish settlers, chemical warfare exercises. No pickup</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALANDIA, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and
wounded at least nine Palestinians in clashes in the occupied
territories Thursday, hospital officials said.
   The officials also said troops fatally shot a Palestinian woman,
but the army said she died in a family feud.
   At the Kalandia refugee camp north of Jerusalem, a mosque was
ransacked overnight, with windows smashed, holy books torn up and
religious tapes destroyed.
   Camp residents blamed Israeli security forces for the
desecration, but police said robbery involving local residents
appeared to be the motive.
   A Jewish settler was injured in the West Bank town of Qalqilya
when a brick was hurled at her car, Israel radio said.
   It said that in another attack in nearby Jenin, 15 Palestinians
threw stones at the car of a Jewish settler and tried to pull him
out and grab his gun, but he escaped.
   About 50 Jewish settlers demonstrated Thursday in front of Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's residence in Jerusalem, demanding tough
measures to make roads safe in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Officials at Mukassad Hospital in Jerusalem said Marwan Kneiry, a
27-year-old Palestinian from the West Bank village of Yaabad, died
Wednesday after he was hospitalized Nov. 7 with a concussion and
bruises.
   His family told doctors Kneiry was beaten by soldiers. Army
officials denied the military was involved and said Kneiry was
attacked ``by local villagers in a feud between two clans.''
   In the Gaza Strip, a 40-year-old woman, Nawal Abu Ittryah, was
fatally shot in the head, officials at Gaza's Shifa Hospital said.
   They quoted Arab residents who brought the woman as saying she
was shopping in the Shati refugee camp market when troops fired on
Arab youths who stoned a passing military jeep, and was apparently
struck by a stray bullet.
   The army denied any shooting incident in the area and said Ms.
Ittryah died in a family feud.
   ``She was brought (to Shifa) by a local car that immediately
escaped. The body was taken to the Abu Kabir Institute in Israel for
autopsy and it was determined she was shot from a weapon that is not
army-issued,'' said a military spokesman, who cannot be identified
under military rules.
   The nine Palestinians wounded Thursday included a 10-year-old boy
struck in the left leg in the open-air market in Nablus in the West
Bank, hospital officials said.
   One of the wounded, a 21-year-old man from a village near the
West Bank town of Ramallah, was in serious condition with a gunshot
wound to the stomach, doctors said.
   The military spokesman's office said it was checking the reports.
   At least 315 Palestinians have been killed, most by army gunfire,
since the Arab uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip began last December. Eleven Israelis also have died.
   Israel seized the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from
Egypt during the 1967 Middle East war. The territories are home to
1.5 million Palestinians.
   About 20,000 children in 36 Israeli schools practiced chemical
warfare defenses Thursday in Israel's largest exercise of the kind.
   Israel TV showed students rushing to bomb shelters to the sound
of sirens, extinquishing a schoolyard fire and evacuating the
wounded.
   It said the students were required to wear gas masks for a
half-hour, but that many removed the masks earlier.
   Israel is worried that its Arab foes may use chemical weapons to
attack the Jewish state's civilian rear in the event of war. Last
month, U.S. CIA director William Webster said that Iraq, Syria and
Libya possess chemical weapons.
</TEXT>
