<HEAD>Afghan Mutineers Defeated in Attempt to Seize Headquarters</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   MOSCOW ( AP) _ An Afghan army detachment of 400 men mutinied and
tried to seize a provincial headquarters but was ambushed by troops
loyal to the government and defeated in a bloody battle, Tass
reported Thursday.
   The Soviet news agency, in a dispatch from Kabul, called the
Monday night incident a coup attempt in the city of Kandahar in
southern Afghanistan.
   According to the report, officers and soldiers loyal to the
pro-Soviet Afghan government learned of the plan and ambushed the
mutineers, forcing them into retreat.
   In another report from Kabul, capital of the war-torn country,
Tass said Afghan troops uncovered 70 corpses in plastic bags near
the border city of Torkham.
   ``Investigating bodies reached the conclusion that they were
tortured to death,'' it said, adding that the victims' hands and
legs were chained and traces of chemicals were found on the faces of
some of the dead.
   Fighting in the area reportedly forced suspension of the
investigation.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov told reporters at
a briefing in Moscow that a Pakistan-based rebel group used poison
pills to kill a Soviet prisoner and tested the pills on two Afghan
officers, who also died.
   ``Rebels from the Gulbuddin Hekmatyar group intend to use the
tablets to kill unsuitable persons,'' Tass said.
