<HEAD>Three Dead, One Seriously Wounded In Murder-Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOVELAND, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man upset about his wife's request for a
separation killed her and his daughter and critically wounded his
son before turning the gun on himself, authorities said.
   Beverly Vansant, 33, had moved to Loveland with her two children
to ``basically to seek shelter from him as a result of domestic
violence,'' said police Sgt. John Teeples.
   William Vansant, 38, went to the home Wednesday night and Mrs.
Vansant refused to let him in, Teeples said. Vansant then demanded
that the children be brought to the front window so he could see
them, the officer said.
   ``The victim complied,'' Teeples said. ``Then he produced a
handgun and fired an undetermined number of shots through the window.
   ``He then went back to the car, retrieved a shotgun and made
entry through the window he had blown out and completed the homicide
of his daughter and the homicide of his wife,'' Teeples said.
   Vansant walked to his car in a parking lot nearby, pulled out a
second shotgun, placed it in his mouth and ``fired one fatal shot.''
   Mrs. Vansant and her daughter, Lindsey, 6, died at the scene,
Teeples said. Her son, Lee, 7, was in guarded, but stable, condition
at McKee Medical Center Thursday. He had been shot in the face,
shoulder and leg.
   Mrs. Vansant had filed for separation on Tuesday, Teeples said.
