<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1931EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan     11-24 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier's Party Approves Peace Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi's Umma Party
approved a peace agreement that the governing coalition's junior
partner signed with southern rebels, two newspapers reported
Thursday.
   The Al-Ayam and Al-Siyassa newspapers quoted Ali Hassan
Taj-el-Din, Umma's secretary-general, as saying the Wednesday night
vote among party leaders was unanimous. It was the first time Umma
had reacted to the pact.
   Parliament still must approve the accord.
   The understanding was signed last week in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia,
by John Garang, leader of the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army,
and Mohamed Osman al-Mirghani, spiritual leader of the Democratic
Unionist Party.
   It calls for a cease-fire in the 5{-year-old civil war in which
rebels are fighting the Moslem-dominated national government for
economic and social changes in the mainly Christian and animist
south.
   Under the accord, controversial Islamic laws in Sudan would be
suspended and a constitutional conference would be convened next
month.
   According to Al-Siyassa, Taj-el-Din said Umma leaders had
reservations about details of the pact which they would communicate
to the Democratic Unionists. The newspaper report did not elaborate.
   Mahdi earlier expressed satisfaction with the accord and with
rebel statements denying responsibility for a missile attack on a
C-130 plane carrying Defense Minister Abdul-Maguid Khalil.
   The attack came one day after the pact was signed and was blamed
by the government on the rebels. It damaged the plane but caused no
casualties.
   The fundamentalist National Islamic Front, also a member of the
coalition Cabinet, has rejected the agreement, mainly because it
suspends Moslem law.
</TEXT>
