<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 2012EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hearst-Pardon     11-24 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hearst-Pardon,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patricia Hearst Makes Bid For Full Pardon; FBI Agent Opposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former FBI agent who headed the
nationwide hunt for Patty Hearst 14 years ago opposes the heiress'
request for a full presidential pardon of her bank robbery and
weapons possession convictions.
   Hearst, her family and friends have maintained that she was
brainwashed by members of the Symbionese Liberation Army, a group of
self-styled revolutionaries who abducted her from a house in
Berkeley in February 1974.
   Months later, she announced she had joined her kidnappers and
took the name ``Tania.'' She was arrested 19 months later in San
Francisco following one of the largest manhunts in U.S. history.
   ``I don't believe she was brainwashed to the point where she was
not responsible in some way for her actions. I just don't buy it,''
said retired FBI Special Agent Charles Bates, who led the hunt for
Hearst and the SLA.
   Bates, who has informed the pardon office of his opposition,
added he believes ``everybody has a right to right their wrongs, but
in crimes of violence, you shouldn't get a pardon the first time you
asked for it.''
   Hearst, 34, whose seven-year federal prison sentence was commuted
by President Carter in 1979, is asking to be forgiven for the crime,
according to a petition filed with U.S. Pardon Attorney David
Stevenson in Washington. She served 23 months at the Women's
Correctional Facitlity in Pleasanton near San Francisco.
   The papers for the pardon were filed on Aug. 4, said a spokesman
for the office, Brad Marman. A pardon would not erase Hearst's
criminal record, Marman added.
   The heiress to a San Francisco newspaper family was convicted by
a U.S. District Court jury in 1976 for her role in the SLA's robbery
of a Hibernia Bank branch two years before. The evidence included a
photograph by a bank camera that captured her wielding an automatic
weapon.
   Hearst's prosecutor, former U.S. Attorney James Browning, today a
San Mateo County Superior Court Judge, said earlier this year he was
leaning against giving his approval to a possible request by Hearst
for a full pardon.
   Browning declined to comment on the case this week, saying it is
inappropriate because of his position as a judge.
   A spokesman for the pardon office said the application review
process could take several years and depends completely on the
discretion of the president.
   The thrust of Hearst's petition is that she has been a model
citizen, wife and mother since being released from prison on Feb. 1,
1979.
   Hearst lives in Westport, Conn., with her husband and former San
Francisco police bodyguard, Bernard Shaw, and their two young
daughters.
   Hearst's attorney, George Martinez of San Francisco, said
Wednesday there was no connection between her request for a full
pardon and the release of the movie ``Patty Hearst'' in late
September. The movie is based on Hearst's book, ``Every Secret
Thing,'' her version of the bizarre time she spent in the SLA.
   Martinez said ``she wants to put it all behind her ... And she
wants to get some indication that there is now complete
understanding by the government of the extraordinary circumstances
under which she participated'' in the bank robbery.
   A commutation of sentence is generally considered a partial
pardon of a crime.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
