<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OPEC 2ndLd-Writethru a0653 11-24 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0653,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Oil Ministers Work Out Tentative Agreement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs with comment from other ministers, impact
on retail prices, details. PICKS UP 16th pvs `Formal
negotiations....' DELETES 22nd pvs `Oil prices...' as extraneous.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC oil ministers struck a tentative
agreement Thursday to curtail their soaring production and lift
crude prices. If adopted, the pact would mean higher prices for
gasoline and other petroleum products.
   Oil Minister Gholamreza Aghazadeh of Iran said he would return to
Tehran on Friday to consult with his government before accepting the
plan. He said he might return to the OPEC meeting on Sunday.
   The arrangement, he said, would set total OPEC production at 18.5
million barrels a day for the first six months of 1989. It would
maintain the cartel's benchmark price of $18 a barrel.
   Recent production increases have driven oil prices well below
that mark.
   Cartel members often have ignored their quotas and analysts say
current production has well exceeded 20 million barrels a day.
   Each dollar increase in the price of crude oil theoretically
means a rise of 2.5 cents a gallon in retail gasoline prices.
   A minister involved in the discussions with Iran, asked if the
plan could be modified, replied, ``Not from our point of view.'' He
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Venezuelan Oil Minister Julio Cesar Gil said, ``It's a fluid
situation. It depends. ... Mr. Aghazadeh (is going) to Tehran for
consultations.''
   The tentative plan, worked out by the 13-nation Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, was put forth to break a deadlock
between Iran and Iraq over a new output accord.
   Issam Abdul Raheem al-Chalabi, Iraq's oil minister, has been
insisting that Iraq's production ceiling in any new pact be the same
as Iran's. Aghazadeh had said no.
   It was unclear exactly how that dispute was resolved.
   Asked if was still refusing to allow Iraq to have the same quota
as Iran, Aghazadeh replied, ``This is exactly the issue which I have
to consult with my government.''
   Aghazadeh, who spoke to reporters after a late evening meeting
with other ministers, said Iran would retain its share of total
cartel output at 14.27 percent.
   ``I received a new proposal,'' he said, ``in which my main
concern, which is to preserve my percentage share, is taken into
consideration.''
   A ceiling of 18.5 million barrels would give Iran a quota of 2.64
million barrels a day. It currently has a ceiling of 2.4 million
barrels.
   Iraq's quota in the current accord is 1.5 million barrels a day.
Iran has been allowed more to serve its larger domestic oil market.
   Aghazadeh said the other 11 members have agreed to give part of
their share to Iraq in an effort to break the deadlock.
   The plan must be approved by all 13 OPEC ministers.
   Formal negotiations among the OPEC ministers had broken off
shortly after the winter meeting began here Monday.
   The ministers had been scheduled to return to the bargaining
table on Wednesday but postponed their formal meeting until
Thursday, then put it off until Friday.
   OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman, who is Nigeria's oil chief, and
Oil Ministers Sadek Boussena of Algeria, Ginandjar Kartasasmita of
Indonesia and Gil of Venezuela met with Aghazadeh for about an hour
Thursday.
   Asked earlier Thursday whether officials had delivered an
ultimatum to Iran, Ginandjar replied, ``We don't work on that basis.
We never give an ultimatum to anybody. Everything should be done on
consensus.''
   The apparent inability of the ministers to break the Iran-Iraq
deadlock had raised the possibility that they might adjourn their
talks this week and try again in December or January.
   If the ministers fail to reach a production agreement this week,
analysts have said prices could weaken further.
   The January contract price for West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude, closed Wednesday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange at $13.97 a barrel. The markets were closed Thursday in the
United States for the Thanksgiving holiday.
   The current ceiling for 12 members _ Iraq refused to join _ is
about 15 million barrels a day.
   The cartel has been exceeding that sum, with production estimated
at more than 21 million barrels a day.
   The ministers want to include Iraq in any new output accord.
   Some of the OPEC ministers arrived in Vienna more than a week ago
to try to stop the feuding between Iran and Iraq. The bitter rivals
agreed to a cease-fire in August in their 8-year-old war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
