<DOCNO> AP881124-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 2022EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ThanksgivingRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0655 11-24 1047</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thanksgiving Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0655,1067</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Day Of Feasting, Parading, Helping The Poor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 14th, `Some 25,000 ..., to UPDATE with
Seattle and Ohio activities; picks up 15th graf pvs, `In Texas ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY27</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tornado victims and thousands of the disadvantaged got free
Thanksgiving meals Thursday, while millions of other Americans
watched parades and football games and sat down at family dinner
tables.
   Pennsylvania State Police attached red ribbons to door handles of
all marked patrol cars and New Hampshire State Police drove with
their lights on to remind motorists of the dangers of drinking and
driving. Many roads in the Northwest were wet with rain or slick
with new snow.
   California's Sierra Nevada range had up to 4 feet of snow from a
storm the day before. ``This has to be the best Thanksgiving skiing
we've ever had,'' said receptionist Beverly Garrett at Squaw Valley
USA. Around Los Angeles, 55- degree water didn't deter surfers.
   Millions of people watched on television and an estimated 2.2
million lined sidewalks as 11 huge helium balloons depicting cartoon
characters highlighted Macy's 62nd annual parade in New York City.
``I think parents come for themselves and the kids are just an
excuse because they want to see it themselves,'' said Vivien Maisey
of Rockland County, N.Y.
   Some 900,000 people turned out for the annual parade in Detroit
which featured Los Angeles Lakers star Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson, a
Michigan native, jazz musician Lionel Hampton and civil rights
pioneer Rosa Parks.
   Thousands of Texans lined Houston streets for the 39th annual
Foley's Thanksgiving Day Parade, with floats depicting Christmas
songs.
   The nation's oldest Thanksgiving Day parade, established in 1919,
drew an estimated 100,000 people to Philadelphia with giant
balloons, marching bands, floats and 5,500 participants. ``Each year
it gets more spectacular,'' said Donna Grant, who said has been
going to the parade ``for years.''
   President Reagan and his wife Nancy gathered with relatives and
friends for a quiet Thanksgiving dinner at their mountaintop
California ranch near Santa Barbara. President-elect George Bush and
his wife Barbara spent a quiet day at their seaside vacation home at
Kennebunkport, Maine, with just two longtime employes as guests for
dinner, according to aides.
   In Birmingham, Ala., more than 50 football-loving families had
Thanksgiving dinner together in campers outside Legion Field, a
ritual for early arrivals for Friday's Iron Bowl clash between
Auburn University and the University of Alabama. Peggy Rickett of
Grove Hill, Ala., brought three gallons of shrimp gumbo, a gallon
and a half of turkey and dressing, a smoked turkey, smoked venison
and five pounds of taco salad.
   Cotham's Country Store in tiny Scott, Ark., isn't usually open
Thanksgiving, but this year the store and restaurant served turkey
dinner free to victims of a tornado that killed three people in the
town Nov. 15.
   ``These people are trying to at least get roofs back on their
houses, to rebuild. They are busy trying to get things prepared to
start over. They can come here and at least not worry about
Thanksgiving dinner,'' said owner Bill Cotham said. ``I guess if we
have any leftovers, we'll just give 'em away when the townsfolk get
their freezers working again.''
   Donations and volunteers enabled up to 18,000 homeless and other
underprivileged people to received a free Thanksgiving meal in
Atlanta. The Rev. Hosea Williams said volunteers also would deliver
at least 3,000 meals to shut-ins.
   Some 25,000 senior citizens and homeless people in Philadelphia
got Thanksgiving dinner Wednesday thanks to Minnie Moore. She
started serving people in her home about 20 years ago, but the crowd
now gets dinner funded by donations at the Civic Center.
   Bob Willmott, a longtime helper of the homeless in Seattle, set
up his organization's annual Thanksgiving Day meal in drizzly,
40-degree weather. Willmott estimated about 1,800 people would
consume 3,000 meals.
   In Dayton, Ohio, 6,000 people packed a convention hall for the
20th annual Community Thanksgiving Dinner. They consumed 166
turkeys, 1,600 pounds of stuffing and 822 pies. It took 150
volunteers to help prepare the meal, sponsored by the Beerman
Foundation.
   In Texas, volunteers in Houston began cooking Wednesday and
expected to feed about 20,000 homeless and poor people in front of
City Hall.
   Dozens of agencies served dinner to homeless, hungry or lonely
people in Chicago and thousands of needy people in Michigan also got
a hot dinner. ``For 95 percent of the people, this is the only meal
they'll have today,'' said one participant at the Capuchin Community
Center in Detroit who declined identification.
   All 11,000 residents of the Southern Illinois hamlet of Herrin
were invited to dinner but only 600 showed up, mostly single and
elderly. ``Everybody's trying to help the needy but nobody tries to
help the people who are alone, and that was our biggest intention on
this thing,'' said Mayor Ed Quaglia.
   On a smaller scale, the owner of a hot dog stand in Pittsburgh
offered free turkey dogs, coffee and candy to the needy.
   In Miami, frozen Thanksgiving dinners for 2,500 elderly people
were recalled after the Little Havana Activities and Nutrition
Center distributing the meals discovered the mashed potatoes had
spoiled during freezing.
   Representatives of the catering company and the center planned to
go to the homes of the recipients to retrieve and replace all of the
spoiled meals by Thursday, said Josefina Carbonell, president of the
center.
   Several Indian nations sent tribal leaders to the Cathedral of
St. John the Divine in New York for an evening ceremony of
reconciliation between descendants of the Indians and those of the
Pilgrims.
   ``We, the boat people, will be thanking the natives for giving us
Thanksgiving, giving us their tradition,'' said the Rev. James Parks
Morton, the cathedral's dean, ``and asking forgiveness for the ways
in which they have been mistreated by the newcomers with respect to
their lands, and with respect to respect.''
   Other Indians gathered for a mourning ceremony in Plymouth,
Mass., near the statute of Massasoit, the Wampanoag chief who made a
peace treaty with the Plymouth Colony in 1621. Wampanoags are
believed to have attended the first Thanksgiving dinner.
   ``We helped them out, and we're still under oppression,'' said
Ellworth Oakley, present supreme sachem of the Wampanoag nation.
</TEXT>
