<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Romania, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungary Expels Romanian Envoy In Retaliatory Move</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to CORRECT spelling of Gyorfi, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary ordered a Romanian envoy out of
the country Thursday in retaliation for Romania's expulsion of a
ranking Hungarian diplomat, the Foreign Ministry said.
   Relations between the neighboring Soviet bloc allies have been
strained by Hungary's allegations about discrimination against 1.7
million ethnic Hungarians living in Romania.
   A formal protest of the expulsion Saturday of Karoly Gyorfi, a
Hungarian commercial counselor, was given to the Romanian Embassy in
Budapest, the official Hungarian news agency MTI reported.
   The note said that ``as a response,'' Pavel Platona, a Romanian
political counselor erroneously described by MTI as Gyorfi's
counterpart, was declared persona non grata and given 72 hours to
leave the country.
   Andras Gulyas, head of the Foreign Ministry press department,
spoke of a warranted Hungarian reaction to a ``serious provocative
act'' by Romania, which he said was unparalleled in relations
between Warsaw Pact nations.
   Last Friday, the Foreign Ministry released a statement saying
Gyorfi was detained for six hours by Romanian police and accused of
distributing inciting leaflets.
   Hungary ignored a Romanian request to recall Gyorfi and said the
Romanian accusations were ``completely unfounded.''
   Last summer, Romania closed the Hungarian consulate at
Cluj-Napoca in Transylvania and expelled its staff after a
demonstration in Budapest by up to 50,000 people protesting Romanian
policies.
</TEXT>
