<DOCNO> AP881124-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 2110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ecuador-Strike     11-24 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador-Strike,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Walk Out in Communist Strike in Ecuador, One Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old boy was killed and three
people were wounded in gunfire at two demonstrations during a
communist-led general strike Thursday to protest the government's
new austerity measures. officials said.
   They reported 35 arrests in clashes.
   A drivers' walkout dramatically reduced bus transportation in the
capital, Quito. Many thousands of workers had to walk to their jobs,
but most businesses appeared to be open.
   In the port city of Guayaquil, about 180 miles south, dozens of
strikers and non-strikers battled at a plastics plant, said Guayas
Province Gov. Rafael Guerrero. He said three non-strikers were
injured by buckshot in the fighting and that police arrested 32
strikers and seized six shotguns.
   News reports said the daylong strike had little effect elsewhere
in this small nation of 10 million in the Andes Mountains.
   It was the first nationwide strike against the center-left
government of President Rodrigo Borja, who took office Aug. 10. He
faced 55 percent annual inflation, a foreign debt of $9.2 billion,
and depressed oil prices.
   Ecuador depends on oil sales for 60 percent of its foreign
exchange earnings.
   His government imposed austerity measures this week trying to cut
inflation and solve other economic problems. Measures included a 35
percent devaluation, a doubling of the price of gasoline, and
foreign-exchange controls.
   The United Front of Laborers, Ecuardor's most powerful labor
organization, called the work stoppage in protest.
   Government spokesman Luis Felix said the boy was killed during a
street demonstration in Quito but that authorities did not know who
fired the shot.
   Police chased off small numbers of protesters downtown.
   At one point, they fired tear gas to disperse about 50 people
painting strike slogans on the walls of the government palace,
police said. The building serves as Borja's home and office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
