<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MiamiNews     11-24 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miami News,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Out-of-State Investor Groups Bid on Cox Newspaper Up for Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two out-of-state investor groups have made formal
bids to buy The Miami News, slated to close Dec. 31 unless a buyer
is found, it was reported Thursday.
   The amount of money offered in both bids for the 92-year-old
paper was not disclosed but was ``nominal'' and were in the same
ballpark on sale terms, said David Easterly, president of the Cox
Enterprises newspaper division.
   Negotiations are under way to resolve differences, and Cox
officials are hopeful a tentative agreement can be reached with one
of the bidders by next week, Easterly told The News in a story
published Thursday.
   ``It's a matter of dealing with some complexities that would not
seem extraordinarily difficult to resolve,'' he said. ``Both offers
will have to be explored.'' He said no more bids are expected.
   The identities of the bidders were not revealed, but Easterly
characterized them as investor groups of businessmen from outside
Florida. He said the groups are not in the newspaper business, but
one may include ``some people with past newspaper experience.''
   Cox announced Oct. 14 that The News would be close Dec. 31 if no
buyer was found, citing declining circulation and continuing
financial losses at the three-edition, afternoon daily which has won
five Pulitzer Prizes.
</TEXT>
