<DOCNO> AP881124-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 2144EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FirearmInjuries     11-24 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Firearm Injuries,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Gun Injuries Cost Taxpayers Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firearms-related injuries cost American taxpayers
an estimated $429 million a year in hospital expenses, researchers
say.
   The estimate does not include the costs of such services as
physicians' fees and ambulance charges, which, if included, could
bring the national price tag to more than $1 billion a year, the
researchers said.
   The scientists based their conclusions on a study of 134 people
with gun injuries who were admitted in 1984 to San Francisco General
Hospital, where all city ambulances are required to take gunshot
victims.
   The government paid 85.7 percent of hospital costs, not including
professional services, while the patients paid only 1.4 percent of
costs, the researchers reported in Friday's Journal of the American
Medical Association.
   Private insurers paid for the remainder, they said.
   In 1984, public sources paid 53 percent of the costs for all
hospitalizations in the United States, researchers said.
   ``It is clear from these data that public sources bear the
greatest burden of the cost of hospitalization for firearm
injuries,'' said co-author Michael Martin and his associates in
epidemiology at the University of California in San Francisco.
   Patients, most of whom were injured during hangun assaults,
stayed in the hospital an average of 6.2 days. All but 10 survived.
Hospital costs ranged from $559 to $64,470, with an average of
$6,915.
   The authors acknowledged their national cost estimates were ``a
rough approximation,'' but said they believed they had made
reasonable assumptions in their estimates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
