<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Libya 1stLd-Writethru a0613 11-24 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0613,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Aide Visits Italy For First Time Since Missile Firing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-5 UPDATE with Jalloud meeting Italian premier.
Picks up 5th pvs, Jalloud, a friend ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top aide to Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi
conferred with Premier Ciriaco De Mita Thursday night at the
beginning of a visit to Italy seen as part of a Libyan campaign to
shed its image of supporting terrorism.
   Staff Maj. Abdulsalam Jalloud is the highest-ranking Libyan to
visit Rome officially since the firing of a Libyan missile at an
Italian island hours after the U.S. bombing of Tripoli in April 1986.
   Jalloud's last official visit to Italy was in December 1984.
   His meeting with De Mita lasted 1{ hours. The Libyan official is
also expected to see Pope John Paul II, whom he has met before.
   Italian news agencies, citing unidentified official sources, said
the Italian government considered Thursday night's meeting
significant because it demonstrated the ``renewal of the dialogue
between the two countries'' after previous misunderstandings.
   Jalloud, a friend of Col. Gadhafi since high school, has played
leading roles in Libyan politics since the 1969 coup that brought
Gadhafi to power and often has been sent abroad as the country's top
emissary.
   Both Libyan and Italian sources recently have indicated that
Gadhafi is eager to have better relations with the West and sees his
country's former colonizer as a vehicle to respectability and to
prospects of expanded economic ties with Western Europe.
   Italy depends greatly on Libyan oil and is the Arab state's
largest trading partner. Italian companies do billions of dollars in
construction, engineering, commerce and other business in Libya.
   Italian officials indicated Italy welcomes the visit as an
opportunity to increase commercial ties.
   But there was some concern in political circles over Jalloud's
visit.
   It ``represents an important moment in the attempt that Tripoli
is making to achieve a better image for a country long accused of
having too many ties with terrorist groups,'' said Filipppo Caria,
head of the Social Democrats in the lower house of Parliament.
   ``As far as we're concerned, it's an important occasion to check
out the real proposals of Gadhafi.'' He noted that only last month
Gadhafi denounced Italy for its colonial rule and deportation of
Libyans during the fascist regime of Benito Mussolini.
   Caria said he was concerned that ``in the attempt to recover a
dialogue with Tripoli, commercial interests don't prevail over
political ones.''
   The United States bombed the Libyan capital, Tripoli, and the
coastal city of Benghazi on April 15, 1986 after accusing Libya of
involvement in the terrorist attack on a Berlin disco. Among the
sites hit was Gadhafi's house in a military compound in Tripoli.
   A few hours later, a Libyan missile was fired at the tiny
Sicilian island of Lampedusa, home to a U.S. Coast Guard facility.
But the rocket landed harmlessly in the Mediterranean.
   Then-Premier Bettino Craxi warned Libya against future attack,
saying Italy would hit back. Since then the two countries have been
working to improve relations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
