<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Stocks     11-24 0099</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0106</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Down At Midday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: will be led after closing</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices drifted lower by midday Thursday in
the absense of market-moving news.
   Dealers said they expected little trading activity ahead of
Friday's release of British trade figures for October and with Wall
Street closed Thursday for the Thanksgiving Day holiday.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was off 6.3
points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,830.8, the day's worst level, at about
1 p.m. local time.
   Volume was a moderate 288.1 million shares compared with 359.7
million at the same time Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1356EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OPEC-Notebook Bjt   11-24 0962</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC-Notebook, Bjt,1017</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Meeting: Trading in Information</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto cq as one name.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the OPEC oil ministers come to town,
a small part of Vienna is nearly turned into a Middle Eastern souk
where the trading is in information rather than Oriental rugs or
brass plates.
   A vast array of people appear when the ministers of the 13-nation
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries gather for their
meetings.
   The lobby of one of Vienna's luxury hotels is packed with
reporters, oil industry analysts and traders, company officials,
U.S. state legislators and assorted others.
   It has all the hustle, bustle, pushing, shoving, shouting and
dealing that characterizes any market.
   Any remark made by a minister is seized upon. Rumors abound and
are spread quickly in small groups, behind hotel pillars or on the
lobby telephones.
   Reporters trip over oil traders in the pursuit of the latest
scrap of news.
   The right word can send the financial markets soaring. Millions
of dollars can be made or lost.
   Unlike summits of other influential government officials, OPEC
meetings are open-ended. Briefings are scarce and press releases
non-existent.
   The focus of attention is on the comings-and-goings of the
ministers. They stay in three nearby hotels overlooking the city's
Stadtpark, a large garden with a statue of composer Johann Strauss.
   Most ministers are in one hotel. Bitter rivals Iran and Iraq are
in separate hotels.
   The ministers carry out most of their business by shuttling among
the hotels. Their formal talks are held at OPEC headquarters about a
mile away.
   At this meeting, they are trying to reach agreement on a new
production accord that would limit their output and lift sagging oil
prices.
   As the ministers, surrounded by bodyguards and aides, hurry out
of and into hotel elevators, they are bombarded with questions.
   Some are more willing to talk than others and hold mini-news
conferences that generally last until the next elevator arrives.
   Iran's oil minister, Gholamreza Aghazadeh, a former newspaper
editor, is more tolerant.
   He and Iraqi oil chief, Issam Abdul Raheem al-Chalabi, are
feuding over how much oil each will be allowed to produce in any new
agreement.
   Their remarks are highly prized.
   Aghazadeh on Tuesday sounded an optimistic note on the outcome of
the meeting.
   His brief statement _ ``I think we can reach an agreement '' _
sent oil prices soaring.
   Aghazadeh, who gives the impression of a humble man, later
remarked ruefully, ``I get the feeling that probably some traders
benefited a lot'' by the reported remarks.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aghazadeh seems to prefer to have an aide translate his remarks
into English when a large group gathers.
   He sometimes speaks in English to add to the translation,
occasionally leading to confusion over his meaning.
   One day, he was asked if he were seeking both a higher OPEC quota
and a higher percentage of the total output.
   He said he couldn't change his percentage share. But listening to
the words on a tape recorder, the translator could barely be heard
saying, ``Probably I'm asking for both.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aghazadeh's rival, al-Chalabi, is less willing to talk.
   In fact, he slips in and out of side doors to avoid reporters. So
the movements of his security personnel, some of whom wait in the
lobby, are closely watched.
   One man is easy to spot _ he has a shock of white in the front of
his dark hair.
   When he hasn't been seen for some time, it's likely his boss is
gone.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia's minister, Hisham Nazer, is the object of intense
scrutiny.
   Observers like to say that each OPEC country has a single vote,
but Saudi Arabia has the barrels, a reference to its enormous oil
capacity and influence in the organization.
   Nazer says little and sometimes seems exasperated by the
attention.
   One day he returned to the hotel after a lunch with other
ministers, briefly went upstairs and then returned to the lobby.
   Noticing a few reporters starting to move toward him, he remarked
he hadn't been gone long enough to do anything.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Subroto, the cheery former Indonesian oil minister who is now
secretary-general of OPEC, seems to enjoy the activity.
   One day an elevator door opened and out stepped Subroto. No
reporters gathered.
   He stopped, did a small tap dance and waved his arms. The hordes
quickly surrounded him.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Libya's oil chief, Fawzi Shakshuki, met with Mana Saeed Otaiba of
the United Arab Emirates.
   Afterward, Shakshuki summed up their talks: ``We discussed our
problems.''
   After a few seconds of silence, a reporter desperate for
information asked, ``What ARE your problems.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Ecuador's energy minister, Diego Tamariz, is new and many don't
yet immediately recognize him.
   But a member of his security detail stands out. He wears a
borsalino hat with part of the brim snapped stylishly down, an
earring in one ear and his coat continently draped over his
shoulders _ movie star-style.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Prince Abdul Aziz bin Salman of Saudi Arabia, a man with a keen
public relations sense, invited a group of reporters for coffee in
the wee hours of the morning.
   The young prince, a member of the royal family, acted the
gracious host making sure his guests were enjoying themselves.
   Analysts, who have watched the prince at recent OPEC meetings,
say he is obviously being groomed to be a mover and shaker in the
oil world.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   One of the few predictable things at the meeting is the departure
and arrival of Qatar's minister, Abdul Aziz bin Khalifa al Thani,
from the formal cartel talks.
   The minister has an uncanny knack for arriving after everyone and
leaving before anyone else.
   Long-time OPEC watchers have given him the nickname of LIFO _
last in, first out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1404EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HolidayHelp Bjt   11-24 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holiday Help, Bjt,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>As Busy Holday Season Approaches, Retailers Vie For Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Credit-card customers of Stern's department
store in Jersey City, N.J., received a little something extra with
their November bills: an invitation to work.
   Officials of Mervyn's, a Hayward, Calif.-based retail chain, this
fall made the rounds of Rotary Clubs with the same invitation.
   With the approach of the Christmas selling season that begins
Friday, stores nationwide have sought to finesse their way around a
growing demand for retail sales help.
   ``It seems sometimes there are more help-wanted signs than job
seekers,'' said Samuel Ehrenhalt, Middle Atlantic regional head for
the federal Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   That's not good news for stores contemplating the Christmas
season, which accounts for about quarter of their yearly sales.
   Some stores are offering bounties to employees who recommend
seasonal help who stay past Christmas. Those who do stay can get
bonuses. Other stores are recruiting retirees or college and high
school students with presentations at the beginning of the school
year, said Jack Fraser, human resources vice president at the
National Retail Merchant Assocation.
   Some are putting ``stuffers'' in shopping bags or taking out
display newspaper advertisements that tout store discounts, a major
drawing card.
   Mervyn's, which has 213 stores in the West and South, has placed
posters and brochures in stores seeking ``people who are proud of
their accomplishments in life,'' such as raising children, managing
a household or volunteer work.
   ``We have been able to maintain our workforce, but it's a
continuous challenge,'' said Mervyn's spokeswoman Kathy Blackburn.
   Several factors have made it more difficult for retailers to fill
their sales clerk ranks.
   The pool of employees, particularly younger people who make up a
higher proportion of retail workers, is declining. Unemployment
hovered around 5.5 percent for most of 1988, down from an average
6.2 percent in 1987 and 7 percent the year before, according Labor
Department statistics. Employment of 16- to 19-year-olds dipped to
7.9 million last month from 8.8 million in October 1987.
   At the same time, demand is increasing, as demonstrated by other
Labor figures: general merchandisers employed 2.5 million people in
August 1988, up 100,000 from August 1987.
   ``The pool is increasingly more limited, and it's created a very
competitive environment for all retailers,'' said Ms. Blackburn.
   Still, wages _ historically low because of competition _ have not
risen with the demand, Ehrenhalt said. ``Companies are very much
under constraints to keep costs in line,'' he said.
   Most stores at the Newport Centre Mall, a new shopping complex in
the densly urban setting of Jersey City, N.J., are having problems
finding clerks who stick with the job, said mall spokeswoman Barbara
Wills. The ``small, less trendy'' stores have the worst time, she
said.
   Upscale retailers such as The Limited, a women's clothing store,
present themselves as ``the place to be,'' said Ms. Willis.
   Donna Connolly, co-manger of the Lane Bryant store in the Garden
State Plaza Shopping Center in Paramus, N.J., said she has had no
problem hiring people, probably because the mall is easily
accessible by bus.
   Transportation difficulties have made it difficult to find help
at some Sears outlets, said spokesman Gordon Jones of Chicago-based
Sears, Roebuck & Co.
   ``It's a very spotty problem,'' he said, worse in the Chicago
suburban market and Northeast.
   ``Quite often, it's where you've got a fast-growing area where
the labor supply has not caught up with the shopping areas,'' he
said, or where higher-income residents would rather shop than work
during the holidays.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1414EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-IrishDistillers     11-24 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Irish Distillers,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pernod Clears Final Hurdle In Battle For Irish Distillers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pernod Ricard SA cleared the final hurdle
Thursday in its takeover battle for Irish Distillers Group PLC when
the Irish government approved the French company's $442 million bid
for the country's biggest whiskey maker.
   Rival bidder Grand Metropolitan PLC of Britain said it would
allow its higher offer of $499 million lapse because of the decision.
   The ruling was announced early Thursday by Albert Reynolds just
before he stepped down as industry and commerce minister in a
Cabinet reshuffle.
   Dublin-based Irish Distillers said it ``welcomes the minister's
decision and looks forward to a speedy resolution to the bid.''
   The Pernod offer, which came to about $6.98 a share, vs. Grand
Met's $8.14 a share, has been given the green light by the European
Community Commission and courts in Dublin.
   On Wednesday, the High Court in London refused a request by Grand
Met for a judicial review of a British takeover panel ruling in
favor of Pernod.
   In approving the takeover, Reynolds stipulated that Irish
Distillers' new owners cannot dispose of any of the target's brands,
which include Jameson's and Paddy whiskeys, without ministerial
approval and that nothing should be done to distort the Irish
spirits market.
   Pernod controls 53.6 percent of Irish Distillers' shares. Grand
Met claims control of 30.06 percent, but Reynolds also ruled that
the British food and drinks giant must reduce its holding to no more
than 30 percent of Irish Distillers.
   Grand Met spokesman Tim Halford said the company was ``content''
to hold onto its minority stake in Irish Distillers because ``we
believe that Irish whiskey has a lot of potential as a world product
if marketed properly.''
   ``We have close links with Pernod around the world and a good
working relationship with them,'' Halford said, adding that ``we'll
have to see what develops over the next few weeks and months.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1420EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Iraq-StockExchange     11-24 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Iraq-Stock Exchange,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq to Set Up Stock Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq will establish a formal stock exchange
to deal with a growing volume of transactions in shares of newly
established private or government-owned companies, the minister of
finance announced Thursday.
   Minister Hikmat Omer Al-Hadithi told the daily newspaper
Al-Thawra that the initial, small-scale financial market will be
temporarily housed at the Industrial Bank before private sector
dealers will be allowed to buy and sell stocks and bonds.
   The minister did not specify when trading will begin.
   He said an increasing number of stocks are being traded in Iraq
due to the emergence of many new companies.
   The government recently offered more than 70 industrial,
agricultural and service projects for sale to the private sector,
but many have not been sold for lack of private capital.
   Since the August cease-fire in the 8-year Iran-Iraq war,
President Saddam Hussein has been trying to liberalize the country's
economic laws to encourage more private investment in reconstruction
projects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1423EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0003 11-24 0108</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0003,0111</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Off</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with market closing</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices drifted lower Thursday in the absence
of any concerted buying.
   Dealers said trading was light since Wall Street was shut down
for the Thanksgiving holiday.
   ``I'm afraid that when the U.S. market is closed, we lose a lot
of our incentive,'' one trader said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed off 4.1
points, or 0.2 percent, at 1,833.0, up from the day's lowest level
of 1,827.8 but below its peak of 1,837.7.
   Volume was a modest 521.5 million shares, compared with 586.6
million shares Wednesday.
</TEXT>
