<DOCNO> AP881124-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1432EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-24 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls In Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged lower against all major
currencies in European trading Thursday despite reports of
central-bank intervention. Gold rose.
   Currency dealers said trading was quiet because of the
Thanksgiving Day holiday in the United States, but that sentiment
toward the dollar remained bearish.
   Dollar purchases by central banks in Japan and West Germany
failed to prop up the U.S. currency, dealers said.
   The dollar closed at 121.15 yen in Tokyo, down from 121.78 on
Tuesday. Later, in London, it traded lower at 120.85 yen.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8375, more expensive for
buyers than Wednesday's late $1.8355.
   Other late dollar rates Thursday compared with late Wednesday:
1.7135 West German marks, down from 1.7155; 1.4375 Swiss francs,
down from 1.4415; 5.8585 French francs, down from 5.8685; 1.9340
Dutch guilders, down from 1.9365; 1,273.75 Italian lire, down from
1,276.50; and 1.1960 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1982.
   Gold bullion prices were modestly higher, helped by the weakening
dollar, which makes gold a more attractive investment.
   Gold closed in London and Zurich at a bid $420 a troy ounce, up
from $419.25 in London and $419.30 in Zurich on Wednesday.
   Hong Kong gold closed at $421.16 an ounce, up from $427.87
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $6.14 a troy ounce,
up from $6.12.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881124-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1547EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-China-Agriculture     11-24 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Agriculture,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money-Short Banks Issuing IOUs To Farmers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese banks, caught short of cash because of
excessive lending and falling deposits, have had to issue IOUs to
farmers selling grain contracted by the state, officials said
Thursday.
   Agriculture Ministry official Sun Xiaoping said the cash
shortfall has occurred in several areas of the country and is
creating problems for farmers needing money to buy materials.
   He said the livelihoods of some farmers could be affected if they
are not paid soon for their grain crops.
   But Chen Qizhen, an official from the Commerce Ministry, said the
use of IOUs was not widespread and that farmers receiving the
promissory notes were being paid within days.
   The official China Daily reported earlier this month that branch
managers of the Agriculture Bank of China had met in Beijing to
discuss how to come up with about $5.1 billion needed to pay farmers
over the next two months.
   The report said the bank would have to attract large amounts of
deposits during the rest of the year to support its farm product
purchases.
   The cash shortage, it said, was caused by unchecked lending in
the first half of the year, spiralling inflation and a $2.1 billion
decline in the increase of new deposits over the first 10 months of
the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
