<DOCNO> AP881124-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-88 1555EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Japan-GATT     11-24 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-GATT,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Willing To Discuss Rice Issue At GATT Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan is prepared to discuss rice and other
agricultural issues in the Uruguay Round of world trade talks,
officials said Thursday as reports surfaced that U.S. President
Reagan has urged Japan to disband its rice market barriers.
   ``We take a positive view toward negotiations ... and we, too,
will not avoid discussion on the issue of market access for basic
foodstuffs,'' said a senior ministry official, briefing reporters on
condition of anonymity.
   He added, however, that officials preparing for the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade ministerial meeting Dec. 5-8 in
Montreal, Canada, have not yet mapped out how Japan will respond to
possible GATT demands for foreign access to the country's protected
rice market.
   Japanese officials insist nations should be entitled to maintain
import restrictions on ``basic foodstuffs.'' They note Japan must
protect rice, its stable food, in order to maintain self-sufficiency
in the grain for security reasons.
   In a related development Thursday, Foreign Ministry officials
said President Reagan called on Japan to open up its rice market in
a personal letter to Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita in early
November.
   They said Reagan urged Japan to offer to open its rice market at
the upcoming GATT trade negotiations, which will be known as the
Uruguay Round because the selection of Montreal as the site was made
at the last GATT talks two years ago in Montevideo.
   The officials added that Reagan's letter was dispatched after
U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter rejected a petition by the
U.S. Rice Millers' Association to investigate Japan's rice market
barriers. Yeutter said, however, he was prepared to reconsider his
decision if Japan does not demonstrate willingness at the Montreal
meeting to open its markets.
   Agriculture Minister Takashi Sato, responding to Yeutter's
warning in late October, said while Japan was prepared to disuss
rice at the GATT meeting, ``it would be difficult for us to
respond'' if the United States singles out Japan.
   In his first letter to Takeshita on the issue, Reagan said
Yeutter's decision to reject the rice millers' petition does not
mean Washington supports Japan's rice policy and warned that Japan's
stance to date had been overly cautious.
   Yasuo Goto, deputy Agriculture Minister, told reporters Thursday
that Takeshita, in a reponse to Reagan, said Japan could only
discuss rice along with other agricultural issues at the Uruguay
Round, according to news reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
